<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AngelIsland     07-06 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angel Island,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angel Island Eucalyptus Groves Could Face Logging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angel Island's familiar eucalyptus groves
may be cut down following a yearlong environmental study that says
native trees would make better homes for wildlife on the island in
San Francisco Bay.
   The study by the state Department of Parks and Recreation
concludes that there would be no adverse environmental effects from
logging 86 acres of the 50-year-old trees and replacing them with
native buckeye, live oak and laurel.
   In June 1987, the state announced it planned to cut down the
eucalytpus, an Australian species, as part of a policy to remove
non-native plants from state park preserves.
   But the plan drew immediate protests in the San Francsico Bay
area. ``Essentially, we're pretty unhappy with the report,'' said
Chris Womack of a Marin County group called Preserve Our Eucalyptus
Trees.
   Parks and Recreation Department Director Henry Angonia will make
a final decision on the Angel Island plan after a public hearing
Tuesday night.
   The Army planted the trees about 50 years ago as windbreaks. If
the logging is approved, six groves of eucalyptus covering 24 acres
would be removed this fall. The island, now a park, once served as
an immigration center.
   The environmental study recommends that the other 62 acres be
logged gradually to minimize the short-term effects. The state
would preserve large, older eucalyptus trees near buildings for
their historic significance.
</TEXT>
