<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Germany-AIDSGloves     07-06 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Germany-AIDS Gloves,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Law Requires Motorists To Add `AIDS Gloves' To First Aid Kits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists in West Germany must add two
pairs of surgical gloves to the first aid kits they are required to
carry in their automobiles under a new law designed to prevent the
spread of AIDS.
   Transportation Ministry spokesman Bernd Bialleck said Wednesday
that the regulation takes effect October 1.
   He said it aims to halt the spread of disease, especially AIDS,
in situations where motorists give first aid to bleeding traffic
accident victims.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's ability
to fight disease. It is fatal and a cure has not been found.
   The virus is spread most often through sexual contact, needles
or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
