<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TycoonSuicide     07-06 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tycoon Suicide,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Developer Awaiting Trial In Bank-Loan Fraud Dies in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate developer awaiting trial in what
prosecutors said was one of the biggest bank-loan fraud cases in
U.S. history electrocuted himself by rigging a stripped cord to an
outlet, officials said Tuesday.
   The body of J.R. McConnell, 40, was discovered on the floor of
the Harris County Jail's medical ward about 3:50 a.m. Monday,
sheriff's Lt. G.L. Moore said. McConnell was transferred to the
medical ward after he tried to hang himself in his jail cell March
21 with a cord from an immersion heater.
   Moore said this time McConnell apparently stripped the ends of a
three-stranded electrical cord, placed one end into a wall outlet,
``and then used himself to make a full circuit by attaching the
exposed end to his leg.''
   It was not known how McConnell obtained the cord, but such items
are usually purchased by inmates at the jail's commissary, Moore
said.
   Moore said a note believed to be written by McConnell was found
on a table next to McConnell's bed.
   The note was addressed to his wife, Mary Gantt, said Dick
DeGuerin, his former attorney.
   ``We have a note that we're examining at this time,'' Moore
said. ``It's somewhat illegible and we're attempting to decipher
what it says. But it appears it might possibly be a suicide note.''
   Following his March suicide attempt, McConnell said he was
despondent over delays in his court proceedings.
   His trial was scheduled for July 19 and he had been in jail
since Nov. 17 on a $750,000 bond.
   McConnell surrendered to federal authorities when he got off a
plane from Mexico after having been missing for more than a year.
He and five associates were indicted last October on charges of
plotting to defraud Texas National Bank-Post Oak and Home Savings
Association of $4.2 million to $5.7 million by claiming to own
property in which they had no interest.
   Loans approved by the institutions and backed by property the
defendants did not own were funneled to McConnell through fronts,
prosecutors alleged.
   McConnell, a one-time multimillionaire, said he had 35 cents in
his pocket when he was arrested. He was assigned a federal public
defender because of lack of money.
   His holdings _ which his wife estimated to be between $300
million and $500 million _ are being liquidated under Chapter 11
and Chapter 7 of U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   McConnell, who made his fortune in Houston, amassed hundreds of
rental properties and development projects here and in Galveston.
   His most ambitious project was a planned 440-acre resort called
Grand Beach on Galveston Island.
   But before the resort's first building could be completed, his
empire began to crumble and McConnell filed for protection from
creditors in October 1986.
   A court-appointed trustee's report said McConnell and the 10
companies included in the bankruptcy filing owed $427 million
against $281 million in assets.
   Two loans listed in the indictment, one at a Houston bank and
another at a savings and loan, were only part of a larger scheme to
defraud lending institutions of at least $162 million, authorities
claimed.
</TEXT>
