<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Airliner-Pentagon Bjt   07-06 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Pentagon, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Jetliner's Altitude, Speed, Course Still in Doubt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon officials still have not resolved
confusion over the altitude, speed or course of the Iranian
jetliner shot down by the USS Vincennes over the Persian Gulf.
   House Armed Services Committee Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., said
after a closed briefing Tuesday that Pentagon officials backed away
from their initial claim that the Iranian plane was outside the
civilian air corridor.
   But a Navy spokesman contacted later said that was still one of
the ``hazy'' areas that has yet to be fully resolved.
   American military officials also have not dispelled doubts about
the altitude and speed at which the Iranian A300 Airbus was
traveling after leaving Bandar Abbas in Iran for Dubai, in the
United Arab Emirates on the opposite side of the Persian Gulf.
   The Pentagon did say Tuesday that the plane was transmitting an
identification signal on a frequency normally used only by military
aircraft, leading the commander of the Vincennes to believe he
faced an attack from an Iranian F-14 fighter.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said a six-member team headed by
Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty landed on the Vincennes on Tuesday to
try to determine why the plane was making those transmissions, how
high and fast it was traveling, and whether it was in the civilian
corridor.
   Iran has asked for an independent investigation by a United
Nations agency, the International Civil Aviation Organization. But
the organization's president, Assad Kotaite said, ``We have not
received ... preliminary reports regarding the circumstances from
the parties involved, except from Iran.''
   Aspin said that Navy officers told him the airliner had strayed
to the western edge of the civilian air corridor, then corrected
course, heading toward the eastern edge, but never left the zone.
   ``It was in the corridor all the time,'' Aspin said.
   The commercial air corridor from Bandar Abbas to Dubai extends
5.5 miles either side of a line between the two cities.
   A Navy spokesman, Lt. Brian Cullin, contacted after Aspin spoke,
said ``the information we have is that it was four miles off track,
to the west. The Vincennes was to the east of the corridor.''
   ``That is one of the hazy points,'' said Cullin, and will be
reviewed by investigators.
   Another point of conflict involves the Vincennes determination
that the airliner was descending from 9,000 to 7,000 feet, and
traveling at 450 knots, a flight pattern that an attacking fighter
might follow.
   Air traffic controllers in Dubai said the Airbus was at 7,800
feet when it was hit by at least one of the two SM-2 Standard
missiles fired by the American cruiser, more or less the same
altitude reported by the Vincennes.
   But another American warship in the area, the USS Sides, which
has less sophisticated radar than the Vincennes, reported that the
Airbus was flying at a steady 12,600 feet, a more common altitude
for commercial jets, and was not descending.
   Pentagon officials initially reported Sunday that the Vincennes
had shot down an F-14. Hours later, Adm. William Crowe, chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, acknowledged Iranian claims that an
airliner had gone down.
   Crowe had said the decision to fire was based in part on
classified ``electronic emanations,'' but declined to give details,
saying the information was classified.
   Faced with worldwide shock at the incident, the Pentagon
declassified the information to strengthen its case.
   The Iranian Airbus, said Howard, was broadcasting ``in two
modes. It was squawking on Mode 3'' using a four-digit number
assigned by air traffic controllers to civilian and military air
craft for identification.
   ``It was also sending signals on a military mode, Mode 2,'' said
Howard. ``And the signals that ... the Vincennes was receiving from
that aircraft were signals that we had previously identified or
associated with an F-14. No commercial airliners use Mode-2.''
   The Mode 2 transponder, he said. ``is a special piece of
equipment which has to be put on the aircraft and it can only be
set on the ground.''
</TEXT>
