<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Korea-Helicopters     07-06 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Helicopters,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Shorten Sentence for Brothers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Tuesday to shorten
sentences given two brothers who sold helicopters to North Korea
and vowed to ``never let these guys out'' of jail if there is a
serious incident at the Olympics in Seoul this summer.
   Barry Semler, 38, of Santa Barbara, and Ronald Semler, 44, of
Malibu, pleaded guilty in February to conspiracy to file a false
shipping declaration, exporting a radio handset to Syria without a
license, making a false statement on an export form and failing to
report income earned by a West German company they secretly
established.
   The judge said the men sold hundreds of helicopters to North
Korea through their North Hollywood company, Associated Industries.
   Barry Semler is serving a one-year sentence, while his brother
is serving a three-year sentence.
   Among those writing to Judge Dickran Tevrizian urging him to
allow the men to work off their terms in community service were
actor Kirk Douglas and game show host Monte Hall.
   But Tevrizian refused to cut the sentences, adding, ``If any
kind of incident (happens) at the Olympics, I'll never let these
guys out.''
   South Korea is taking extraordinary precautions to prevent
terrorist incidents they fear might be fomented by communist North
Korea during the Olympics.
   Defense attorney Richard Kirschner has said someone else
arranged the sale of the helicopters through a West German company,
and that the helicopters would have needed millions of dollars
worth of alterations for military use.
</TEXT>
