<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MarinaFire     07-06 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marina Fire,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boats Destroyed In Marina Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LORAIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out at a Lake Erie marina in this
northeast Ohio city Tuesday night, destroying about 150
recreational boats and injuring two people, officials said.
   About 100 firefighters from Lorain and five nearby communities
remained late Tuesday at the Copper Kettle Marina, where two
storage buildings collapsed after catching fire before 7:30 p.m.
   ``You could hear little pops when the gas cans of the boats went
up,'' said Loren Barnheiser, who lives across the street from the
marina.
   The fire also produced thick smoke because of the fiberglass
content of the boats.
   Lorain safety inspector Richard Yepko estimated damage at $3
million to $5 million. The cause of the fire was not known.
   The two injured people apparently were in the building working
on their boat when the fire broke out, said Lorain Community
Hospital spokeswoman Thelma Price.
   She said David Dorner, 30, was taken to the hospital and
transferred by helicopter to the Metro General Hospital burn unit
in Cleveland, about 25 miles to the east, with burns over 50
percent of his body.
   Dorner's father Ken Dorner, 51, was admitted to the Lorain
hospital, Ms. Price said. The nature of his injuries was not
immediately available.
</TEXT>
