<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-DisclosureForm     07-06 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Disclosure Form,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Transferred Assets From Controversial Partnership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Meese Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III transferred
many of his assets into mutual funds in 1987, after the breakup of
a controversial financial partnership he had with an investment
manager linked to scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp, his financial
disclosure report shows.
   The new 10-page form, issued Tuesday, shows that Meese funneled
from $50,000 to $100,000 into a Merrill Lynch CMA money fund
account last Aug. 5.
   The report also shows that he invested from $15,000 to $50,000
in each of two mutual funds last October _ Pacific Dunlop Ltd. and
MuniInsured Fund Inc.
   In addition, Meese invested $15,000 to $50,000 in the Merrill
Lynch Pacific Fund last October, selling it for an undisclosed loss
in December.
   Meese opened the various fund accounts after dissolving a
partnership with a corporation operated by W. Franklyn Chinn, who
has been indicted on racketeering charges in the Wedtech scandal.
   Chinn turned a $40,000 profit for Meese on a $50,000 investment
in just 18 months through a series of stock trades. Chinn, using
his contacts in the brokerage industry, obtained hard-to-get
brand-new stock issues and sold them for Meese later the same day,
usually at a substantial profit.
   Meese's financial arrangements with Chinn constituted part of
the investigation of the nearly 14-month-long criminal
investigation of the attorney general by independent counsel James
McKay, sources familiar with the probe have said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. McKay concluded his probe Tuesday by filing
an 830-page report with a federal court, signaling that he is
unable to come up with sufficient evidence to seek an indictment of
the attorney general.
   As White House counselor, Meese in 1981 and 1982 assisted
Wedtech by directing his staff to ensure that the Army gave the
South Bronx, N.Y., defense contractor a fair hearing from the Army
when Wedtech was trying to win a $32 million no-bid contract to
build small engines. The firm ultimately got the work.
   In 1985, Meese formed the limited partnership with Chinn at the
suggestion of Meese's longtime friend, E. Robert Wallach. It was
Wallach who originally urged Meese to become involved with Wedtech
and the San Francisco lawyer eventually was paid over $1 million in
cash and Wedtech stock by the defense contractor. Wallach also is
under a racketeering indictment in the Wedtech scandal.
   In addition to breaking up the partnership with Chinn in 1987,
Meese also sold stock in regional Bell telephone companies last
September. Meese's stock in six of the regional Bells was valued at
from $1,000 to $5,000. Stock in a seventh was valued at less than
$1,000.
   Meese's phone stock provided another focus of McKay's
investigation. The attorney general met with executives of four of
the regional Bell companies who wanted the Justice Department to
reverse its stand and recommend that the regional Bells be allowed
to engage in a number of new types of business. After meeting with
the Bell executives in 1985 and 1986, Meese obtained a White House
waiver which permitted him to participate in the matter, which he
did by approving the sought-for reversal of the Justice
Department's position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AbortionAid     07-06 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Aid,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AID Barred From Restricting Family Planning Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has declared unconstitutional
a Reagan administration policy of barring aid money for private
organizations that promote abortion as a form of worldwide family
planning.
   U.S. District Judge June L. Green ruled that the policy, first
announced in 1984 at a United Nations conference on population in
Mexico City, violated the free speech and association rights of a
U.S.-based organization that promotes family planning projects in
Third World nations.
   The policy, announced by then-Undersecretary of State James L.
Buckley, has drawn accusations from Third World nations that the
United States is interfering with the family-planning policies of
those countries.
   In an opinion issued Friday but not made public until Monday,
the judge ordered the Agency for International Development to stop
enforcing the policy.
   But Green said AID could bar foreign organizations that receive
U.S. aid from using the money to finance abortion services.
   The ruling was made on a 3-year-old lawsuit by three
family-planning organizations that operate programs in the Third
World, including DKT Memorial Fund Ltd, which is based in New York.
   Green ruled that Parivar Seva Santha of New Delhi, and
Population Services Family Planning Programmes Ltd., of London,
lacked legal standing to press their constitutional claims because
they are foreign organizations.
   But she said the regulations ``impair the associational rights
of DKT'' under the First Amemdment.
   ``AID is in essence coercing the plaintiffs to refrain from
abortion-related programs if they wish to receive AID funding, even
though they are using their own funds for the abortion-related
programs,'' she added.
   AID spokesman Jerry Lipson said the agency had not seen the
opinion. But he said AID will ``certainly recommend that the
Justice Department appeal any aspect of the court's ruling that is
unfavorable to the agency and (that) hey do so on an expedited
basis.''
   ``We believe that the policy and AID's implementing procedures
fully comply with the Constitution and we are confident that the
government will be successful on appeal.''
   Richard Frank, an attorney for the plaintiffs , said the
decision means that ``population activities abroad will not be
hampered as they have been in the past.''
   ``It also will remove substantial irritants in the foreign
relations between the United States and certain other countries''
that object to ``the United States trying to tell their
organizations what their organizations should do with their own
money,'' he said..
   The three groups had planned to seek AID funds to operate a
family-planning program in India but became ineligible to receive
U.S. aid when the policy was announced.
   Under the policy, AID gives money to foreign governments that
support abortion, but the funds are placed in a segregated account
and cannot be used for that purpose.
   The policy requires that non-government groups certify they ``do
not perform or actively promote abortion as a method of family
planning in AID-recipient countries and do not provide financial
support'' to other groups that do.
   Green ordered AID to drop the requirement.
   But AID may require the groups ``to certify that they will not
use AID funds to perform or actively promote abortions.''
   U.S. contributions to foreign groups could be made ``through
segregated accounts, as AID is doing presently in its
government-to-government dealings,'' she said.
   Under the order, U.S.-based groups will no longer be required to
certify that the funds they receive won't be used to support
foreign organizations that promote abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EpiscopalConvention     07-06 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Episcopal Convention,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Episcopal Church Tries To Accommodate All Regarding Women Bishops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the Episcopal Church's 69th General
Convention are moving to pave the way for a woman bishop, yet avoid
a schism with those who object.
   The 200-member House of Bishops on Tuesday voted 135-18 to
approve two resolutions that would soften the impact of the
elevation of a woman.
   The church has no women bishops, even though about 900 women
have been ordained as priests since 1976. Some church leaders say
one could be elected within six months. Conservative members have
said the consecration of a woman bishop could cause a split in the
church.
   Tuesday's vote came while fellow Anglican leaders in the Church
of England in London voted in favor of proposals to admit women to
the priesthood, despite opposition from those who warned of a
schism.
   One resolution approved by the American bishops calls for
respect of the position of those disagreeing with the ordination of
women bishops and the other provides for male clergy to attend the
needs of dissenting parishioners.
   ``I am of two minds. I'm pleased that it represents a larger
number of different groups within the church made a commitment for
women, but it concerns me that such an exception has to be made for
women bishops in the Episcopal Church,'' said the Rev. Annette
Braunlee of Cleveland.
   ``It says that there is something about us that is
threatening,'' she said.
   The proposal now goes to the 900-member House of Deputies.
   AIDS-related issues also were on Tuesday's agenda.
   The House of Deputies unanimously approved an AIDS
anti-discrimination resolution and debated other proposals,
including teaching and paying for AIDS education.
   The anti-discrimination measure ``prohibiting discrimination in
the church on the basis of AIDS, AIDS related complex or HIV
infection,'' was scheduled for debate in the House of Bishops.
   ``We have to give the healing gifts to all,'' said John Fryer, a
psychiatrist from Philadelphia who founded the Philadelphia AIDS
program. ``Jesus healed without moral judgment.''
   The 3,000 delegates to the General Convention meet every three
years to set policy for the 2.6 million-member church. The
convention runs through Monday.
</TEXT>
