<1ST_LINE>r a BC-JapaneseConcert     07-06 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japanese Concert,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Composer Attends Concert at Japan Society</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer Toru Takemitsu was in the audience
Tuesday as one of his works was featured at the first of four
concerts of contemporary Japanese chamber music at Japan Society.
   It was ``Rocking Mirror Daybreak,'' commissioned by violinists
Ani and Ida Kavafian for their first duo concert at Carnegie Hall
in 1983 and performed by them again Tuesday.
   The concert, which also featured six other works, is part of the
First New York International Festival of the Arts.
   ``Mankind is facing difficulties,'' Takemitsu commented before
the concert. ``I don't think there is a good way to resolve the
problems. I think it can be done only by friendship, friendship
forever.''
   On Wednesday, before a concert featuring three compositions by
Takemitsu, the composer will give a lecture, ``Contemporary Music
in Japan.''
   Takemitsu has had more than 60 works recorded. Many of his
orchestral and chamber compositions have entered the international
classical repertory. He also has scored more than 75 films,
including ``Woman in the Dunes'' and ``Ran.''
   The chamber group which is performing the four concerts is Sound
Space ARK, founded in Tokyo in 1972 and specializing in modern
music. It is composed of a pianist, percussionist, flutist,
clarinettist and harpist. American guest artists on Tuesday were
the Kavafian sisters and cellist Fred Sherry.
   It was a fascinating concert. Only one piece, ``Recurrence,'' by
Toshi Ichiyanagi, is minimalist. Instead of musical phrases
repeating and varying slightly, musical phrases are repeated
exactly while one of seven instruments solos over the others.
   ``A Winter Day, Homage to Basho'' by Joji Yuasa was modern
impressionism, with musical phrases entering and floating.
``Clarinet Solitude,'' played by Yoshiaki Suzuki, also was
especially noteworthy, in its first shrill, then other-worldly
tones. Joji Yuasa composed it in memory of composer Yoshiro Irino,
who introduced 12-tone music to Japan.
   Yasunori Yamaguchi was surrounded by a vast array of percussion
instruments and used them with an admirably light hand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
