<DOCNO> AP880706-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Airliner-Transponders     07-06 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Transponders,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airbus Sent Signals On Military, Civilian Frequencies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon says the Iranian jetliner shot
down in the Persian Gulf was broadcasting identification signals on
two frequencies, one of them reserved exclusively for military
aircraft.
   Every commercial and military aircraft operating in the United
States or overseas is supposed to carry what is known as a
transponder, according to Pentagon and civilian authorities.
   When a radar beam or other radio signal hits the plane, it
activates the transponder to broadcast an identification code under
a system known as ``Identify Friend or Foe,'' designed to prevent
attacks on friendly or civilian aircraft.
   A six-member investigating team, headed by Rear Adm. William M.
Fogarty, arrived in the Persian Gulf on Tuesday and will review
tapes aboard the American warship, the USS Vincennes, to shed light
on the tragedy, officials said.
   Commercial and military aircraft normally broadcast on what the
Pentagon calls Mode 3, sending a reading of their altitude and a
four-digit identification code that is arbitrarily assigned to them
by air traffic controllers.
   Only military aircraft broadcast on Modes 1, 2, and 4, said Lt.
Brian Cullin, a spokesman for the Navy.
   Mode 1 is a two-digit signal which describes the mission and
country of origin of the aircraft, said Cullin. The message is not
encrypted, or put into code that cannot be read by the enemy, and
does not give the type of aircraft involved, he said.
   Mode 2 is not encrypted, either, and identifies the type of
airplane, the country of origin, and the plane's unit, Cullin said.
   Daniel Howard, the Pentagon spokesman, told reporters that the
Iranian aircraft was broadcasting ``in two modes.''
   ``It was squawking on Mode-3 ...,'' he said. ``It was also
sending signals on a military mode, Mode-2. And the signals that
... the Vincennes was receiving from that aircraft, were signals
that we had previously identified or associated with an F-14. No
commercial airliners use Mode-2.''
   The Mode 2 transponder, he said. ``is a special piece of
equipment which has to be put on the aircraft and it can only be
set on the ground.''
   Another type of transponder, designated Mode 4 by the Pentagon,
is classified and encrypted, said Cullin, the Navy spokesman.
Futher details were not available.
   All four modes of the IFF use a Mark-12 transponder which
transmits and receives on the D-band frequency range, which is
1,000 to 2,000 megahertz. The reply signals use different
frequencies and package their information in pulses of differing
lengths, said Cullin.
   It is impossible for normal civilian aircraft to broadcast the
information that would be carried by a Mode 2 transmission,
according to Pentagon and civilian authorities.
   The transponder would have to be altered by the addition of
circuit boards or other equipment in order to transmit in Mode 2,
according to Navy and civilian experts.
   Bill Reed, a spokesman at Allied-Signal Inc.'s Bendix
Communications division in Towson, Md., says airliners are normally
equipped with two transponders, one as a backup. Bendix
manufactures transponders, but it was not known whether it supplied
the ones used by the Iranian A300 Airbus.
   ``Identifying friend or foe is a challenge. It's a process of
elimination. If you've eliminated all the other possibilities you
are left with only one choice: `I can't verify he's a friend so
therefore he's an enemy,''' Reed said.
   Another civilian expert said that Mode 2 and Mode 3 transmitters
``are basically incompatible.''
   ``A military one would send out a signal that would be
incomprehensible to a civilian air traffic controller,'' said the
civilian expert, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``On your
typical U.S. airliner, you would not find a military transponder.''
   A spokesman for the Airbus manufacturer in France said the
airliner was delivered to Iran Air six years ago with two
transponders aboard that should have responded to identification
requests from the cruiser.
   The Airbus spokesman, David Velupillai, did not specify whether
the transponders were calibrated to broadcast at civilian or
military frequency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Meese-Text 9Takes   07-06 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Meese-Text, 9 Takes,590-4600</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III's news conference Tuesday.
   I have a statement to make, and then I'll be glad to answer any
questions.
   The independent counsel today filed his statutory report after
an investigation that has lasted approximately 14 months and has
gone into many subjects, heard dozens of witnesses, and scrutinized
thousands of documents, including all of my personal financial
records since 1981.
   The filing of the report by the independent counsel, in line
with his previously stated finding, confirms that after an
exhaustive investigation, he has determined that there is no basis
for criminal proceedings with respect to any of the matters that he
has examined.
   I am gratified by this result, but not surprised.
   I knew from the beginning of this investigation that my conduct
has been at all times lawful, and that if the truth were told,
there would be no grounds for any criminal action.
   This past year has been enormously difficult for my family and
me.
   We have been subjected to a barrage of unfair, misleading and
false information circulated through the media.
   I answered any and all questions that the independent counsel
put to me in grand jury sessions and through depositions throughout
the year.
   But I have not yet been able to publicly confront the misleading
and false allegations because of the ongoing independent counsel's
investigation.
   Now that the report has been filed, however, I will begin to
present a full public response.
   My attorneys and I will study the independent counsel's report,
which we have not yet received, but which we hope to receive today
or tomorrow, and we will prepare an appropriate and timely reply,
as the law provides.
   When the court determines what portion, if any, of the report
should be made public, I trust that my written response will
accompany that publication.
   I will then make myself available to answer any and all
questions.
   I look forward to that opportunity, because I am confident that
when the public is able to hear both sides of the story, not just
the prosecutor's view, presented by the independent counsel, it
will be clear to all that I have acted lawfully and properly.
   Now that the independent counsel has finished his task, and one
of the most exhaustive, thorough and costly investigations of any
public official has been completed, the false allegations have been
put to rest, it is therefore an appropriate time for me to announce
certain decisions with respect to my personal future.
   Over the past two months, I have indicated publicly that when I
have achieved several objectives in the Department of Justice and
have set the record straight, and when it is in the interest of my
family and myself that I return to private life, I would leave the
post of attorney general.
   I have stated that I would not resign under a cloud or until I
was completely vindicated.
   I have refused to bend to the constant drumbeat of political and
media pressure, because I have a responsibility to uphold which
involves an important principle, not only for myself and this
administration, but for future government officials who are
subjected to untrue allegations.
   As I have said before, to allow myself to be hounded out of
office by false accusations or allegations, unjust political
attacks, and media clamor, would undermine the integrity of our
system and would abandon the principles of justice which I have
championed throughout my life.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
