<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Meese-Text 1stadd   07-06 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Meese-Text, 1st add,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SACRAMENTO, Calif.: my life</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With the successful conclusion of the investigation and the
burden of false allegations now lifted, I can look ahead to
returning to private life where I intend to continue making a
contribution to society.
   Accordingly, I have informed the president that I will be
leaving the administration towards the end of July or early in
August, in order to accept new opportunities in the private sector.
   Between now and my departure, I will vigorously pursue the
agenda that I have established at the Department of Justice.
   I am proud of that agenda, and of the accomplishments that have
been realized by the department and the administration.
   I deeply believe that President Reagan's administration has
regained the proper course for law enforcement and for the true
administration of justice in the United States.
   I am particularly proud of our successes in the long and
difficult war on drugs, and of the appointment of a large number of
highly qualified judges who will return this country's judicial
system to the path intended by the founding fathers.
   During these past difficult months, my family and I have been
sustained by hundreds of messages of friendship and support from
friends and colleagues, and in many cases, from strangers, who have
extended their encouragement and good wishes.
   I am particularly grateful to the president for his unwavering
support which has been so important to me.
   I also want to thank Vice President Bush for his fairness and
decency in regard to this matter.
   Finally, let me say that it has been an honor and a privilege
for me to work with and for President Reagan.
   Under his leadership this administration has had an outstanding
historical impact on the direction of our country and the welfare
of our people.
   I am proud to have a part in establishing that legacy.
   Now I'd be happy to take any questions anyone might have.
   Yes?
   Q. Mr. Attorney General, is there any truth to the rumor that
either Robert Bork or Elliot Richardson may replace you?
   A. I don't think there's any truth to any rumor about a
replacement because I just talked with the president a few minutes
ago.
   Q. Is there any coincidence in the fact that you will be leaving
your position as attorney general just before the Republican
National Convention?
   A. No _ it's a coincidence purely.
   It just happens that I _ in looking at a variety of things that
I'm considering to do, determined that the end of July or the early
part of August would be the most propitious time for my own
personal plans and the president agreed to that.
   Q. What opportunities are you _
   A. There are a number of things.
   I've had several opportunities presented to me over the past few
months, and I felt it was not appropriate to pursue those or decide
on anything until I had talked with the president and made public
my announcement of leaving.
   Now that that has been accomplished, I will be pursuing some of
these opportunities, making some decisions, and I'll let you know
my specific plans within a short while.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
