<2ND_LINE>BC-Meese-Text, 2nd add,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SACRAMENTO, Calif.: short while.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. Do you admit _
   Q. Are you going to offer yourself to the Bush campaign?
   A. In the Bush campaign, I would think that his campaign is
already pretty well filled.
   I _ certainly not in a full-time way.
   If I can be of help to Vice President Bush in his campaign I
certainly will once I'm in private life.
   Q. General Meese, in the report that was filed with the
(inaudible) said to be indications that there were some ethical
questions which could be looked into, but not criminal questions.
(Inaudible) your own stock when you were dealing with the
deregulations of the telephone companies and some of the other
matters. Are you aware of those? And are you concerned about the
internal Justice Department investigation?
   A. Well, nobody has seen the report, so I don't know what and
how anybody could know what's in it.
   Even my own lawyers, when I last talked with them just before
coming down here, had not seen the report.
   So I don't know what's in it.
   But I think the important thing to remember is that the single
duty of the independent counsel was to determine whether any of
these allegations that had been made, the false allegations I
referred to, formed the basis for criminal proceeding.
   The independent counsel found that there was no basis for
criminal proceeding.
   So he has accomplished that task.
   Anything that may be in the report is mere commentary and
opinion.
   If it raises any questions, I'll be glad to answer those.
   Yes.
   Q. Mr. Meese, are the standards to which we can hold public
officials currently legal, then? Or is there a less stringent
ethical standard that we should _
   A. Well, I don't think there's a less stringent ethical standard.
   I think public officials should be held to the highest ethical
standards.
   And I believe, certainly, that in my case I have kept those
standards.
   Yes.
   Q. Didn't you create the appearance of preferential treatment
for help you gave Wallach on the pipeline _
   A. Well, as far as those individual issues, I said that as soon
as the report is made public I'll answer those questions.
   I can only say that certainly there was no indication of
preferential treatment of any sort, and I will go into that more
fully when I can when I am _ when the report and my response are
published and I can comment in full publicly.
   Q. You indicated that the court would make a decision which
portions, if any, of the report would be public. Would you under
any circumstance oppose making that report and your response public?
   A. I don't know because I don't know what's in the report, so I
_ there's no way I can answer any question like that.
   Q. Then how do you know that you've been proven vindicated?
   A. Because if _ if the _ as I say, the only purpose of the
independent counsel, his only duty, is to find out if there's any
basis for criminal proceedings.
   By filing a report as opposed to an indictment, he makes clear
his decision that there's no basis for criminal proceedings.
</TEXT>
