   Q. Mr. Meese _
   Q. But that doesn't answer _ I mean, you spoke that you would
leave office only if completely vindicated.
   A. Right.
   Q. How do you know you've been completely vindicated, I mean, if
you don't know if there are ethical questions, I mean?
   A. Because, as I say, the only purpose of the independent
counsel is to determine whether criminal proceedings _ he has no _
his opinion or whatever it might be on ethical issues is not a
matter of his duties.
   So, the fact that these allegations have been proved false and
there's no criminal proceedings fully vindicates me.
   Q. But aren't the proceedings pretty general _ or is that the
only level that you view as being vindicated _ no other ethical _
   A. Well, that's the only _ that's the only _ that's the only
basis on which any allegations had been made that there was some
kind of criminal misconduct.
   Q. If there's any of these ethical questions perhaps that are
turned over to the Office of Professional Responsibility within the
Justice Department, will you cooperate with those steps.
   A. Well, I don't know that there will be.
   But obviously, as I've said before, I will publicly answer any
questions that anybody has about any aspect of my conduct.
   And as I've also said before, I'm sure that a fair-minded
public, when they hear my responses to any questions that might
arise, will agree that everything that I have done has been purely
lawful and proper.
   Q. Have you been waiting for this report to announce your
resignation?
   A. Actually, I've been thinking about my future, and as these
opportunities have come forward, I have determined over the course
of a few weeks here that it would be advantageous for me to return
to private life before the administration ends.
   I have made the final decision on that really over the last week
or weekend actually, and based upon also my conversation with the
president and getting his permission.
   Q. Why is it advantageous? Why not serve out the remainder of
the few months left?
   A. Well, I think when I discuss my plans, it should be made
clear _ it should make itself clear as to why it's advantageous to
leave before the administration ends.
   Q. Mr. Meese, did you know about the $150,000 from Rappaport to
Wallach which went into a pooled investment account for you and
others, and didn't you benefit from that account?
   A. Well, again, I'm going to answer all of these questions when
I'm able to speak fully, but in no way did I benefit from any
$150,000 from Mr. Rappaport nor did it go into any pooled
investment account in which I was a beneficiary.
