<HEAD>SACRAMENTO, Calif.: the capital?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A. No, it was just _ this has been a long-scheduled visit.
   I was here not only for the marijuana campaign, but also
yesterday I spoke here in Sacramento to the International
Association for Identification, a group of law enforcement,
scientific and forensic specialists.
   That's been planned for several months.
   And so it was just happenstance that I happened to be here on
the day that the report indicating there'd be no criminal
proceedings was filed.
   Q. Has anyone from the Bush campaign ever suggested that you
step down?
   A. No.
   Q. Will you be writing a book about your Washington experience?
   A. (Laughs.) I don't know.
   We'll see what happens.
   Again, there are a lot of things I've got to think about, and so
we will consider a lot of possibilities.
   So I couldn't tell you whether I will or not.
   Q. As A.G. you supported a plan in Central America to use a
defoilant, I believe called Spike against cocaine growers. There's
been some controversy about that because of its highly toxic
nature, not just with cocaine, but with other plants. Would you
support the continuation of that plan?
   A. I certainly would, because it's not highly toxic.
   As a matter of fact, it's a herbicide that is used in the
western United States every day by farmers and by agricultural
experts.
   So I think there's no real danger from it.
   And obviously we have already taken soil tests to be sure that
it would not be environmentally harmful in the areas of South
America, actually, where it was proposed to be used.
   So I support it.
   I also support extensive environmental testing, to be sure it's
safe.
   But assuming that it is, based on the previous tests, I think it
would be an excellent means of helping those countries eradicate,
in this case, the coca plants, and do what their presidents have
told me they want to do, and that is, get their countries out of
being source locations for these narcotics that are coming to the
United States and to Europe.
   Q. (Inaudible) manufacturer has balked at that. Apparently one
of the reasons is they didn't want the drug lords down there to get
after (inaudible). How did you respond to their balking?
   A. Well, their so-called balking is something that's being
discussed with them now.
   It had nothing to do with environmental damage.
   I think it was fear, perhaps, for their employees or operations.
   If that was the case, then those are problems we just have to
work out.
   But I don't think tht anybody, any firm that is manufacturing a
safe product that can be used in the war against drugs, has the
right or the _ certainly not the _ should not have the moral
opportunity to withdraw from the fight against narcotics.
   I think it'd be a terrible thing if people who could help end
the tremendous suffering from narcotics would not let their
products be used.
   I think that would be a moral black mark against any such
company that did that.
</TEXT>
