<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Airliner     07-06 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Airliner,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Downing Of Iranian Airliner Strengthens Soviet Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Navy's downing of Iran Air Flight
655 will likely fuel debate on a proposed U.N. naval peacekeeping
force the Soviets are pushing as a way to diminish Washington's
presence in the Persian Gulf.
   The attack Sunday on the airliner with 290 people aboard will
also complicate U.N. efforts to mediate between Iran and Iraq and
bring about a cease-fire in their 7{-year-old conflict.
   Last September, in his annual report, U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar called for new, innovative forms of
peacekeeping, perhaps including a U.N. naval force to protect
civilian shipping and maintain maritime peace.
   But Washington, which has deployed the Navy in the gulf to
assert its strategic interests and protect neutral commercial
shipping, has said it is not leaving the oil-rich strategic
waterway.
   Still, the U.S. naval presence in the gulf is increasingly
controversial and Sunday's jetliner downing _ during the latest in
a series of U.S.-Iranian clashes _ demonstrates the volatility of
the region and the problems U.S. forces face in trying to keep the
peace.
   The Soviet Union, its allies, Iran and other nations argue that
far from keeping the peace, the U.S. presence inflames tensions.
   In commenting on the disaster, the official Soviet press agency,
Tass, said: ``The tragedy has borne out once again that the United
States naval fleet must leave the Persian Gulf without delay.''
   The Pentagon said the U.S. warship that shot down the Iran Air
Airbus mistook it for an Iranian F-14 jet fighter.
   Iran has requested a Security Council meeting that is expected
early next week and would likely see the Soviets press their call
for withdrawal of all U.S. military forces from the gulf and
introducing an international naval force under U.N. command.
   The council's five permanent members are the United States, the
Soviet Union, Britain, China and France.
   The two superpowers have not participated in other U.N.
peacekeeping operations because they were perceived as putting
their national strategic interests first. The Soviet Union now
wants to change that.
   Since last September, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze has been saying that the time has come for a U.N.
naval peacekeeping force.
   Under the principles of U.N. peacekeeping, such a force can only
operate with the consent of the parties concerned.
   It must be impartial and not favor either side and it must not
use force, except as a last resort and only in self-defense.
   But the United Nations and its peacekeeping forces are facing a
financial crisis and the prospects of funding a new naval force are
bleak and compounded by U.S. resistance.
   The attack Sunday will also hurt efforts to end the Iran-Iraq
war.
   U.N. officials and diplomats say the attack on the Airbus has
generated sympathy for Iran and hardened Iran's determination not
to stop fighting until Iraq is branded the aggressor.
   That demand has been a major roadblock in getting Iran to accept
a cease-fire in the bloody conflict.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR`S NOTE: Victoria Graham is former AP bureau chief in
China and India and currently is chief correspondent at the United
Nations.
</TEXT>
