<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Election 1stLd-Writethru a0753 07-06 0890</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Election, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0753,0910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexicans Voters Promised Honest, Peaceful Presidential Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 14th, `Cardenas, 54 ...' to UPDATE
with police denial that killing was politically motivated; picks up
15th pvs: `A Gallup ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government promised to make Wednesday's
general elections free of violence and fraud, and opposition
parties mobilized thousands of poll-watchers nationwide to hold the
government to its word.
   The final tally wasn't expected before the end of the week, but
the outcome is virtually certain _ the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party hasn't lost a presidential election since its
founding in 1929.
   Voters will choose a new president and members of congress at
55,000 polling places across the country, under guard by thousands
of troops.
   Polling stations open at 8 a.m. (10 a.m. EDT) and counting is to
begin when they close 10 hours later. Many parties plan to begin
releasing unofficial results on election night.
   Civilians were barred from carrying arms and most workers were
to have the day off. Bars also were ordered closed for election day.
   President Miguel de la Madrid, in a nationally televised speech
Monday night, pledged to guarantee ``clean, legal and peaceful''
elections, saying ``it is a commitment of the Government of the
Republic to comply strictly with the law.''
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari is the candidate of the PRI, as the
governing party is known by its Spanish initials. His winning the
election is already presumed, and the only suspense lies in his
margin of victory and the aftermath.
   Salinas de Gortari, a 40-year-old Harvard-trained economist, was
expected to break PRI tradition and win with less than the nearly
70 percent accorded de la Madrid.
   Opposition parties on the left and on the right of PRI have
turned this campaign into a vigorous race and put the governing
party's legitimacy on the line by making allegations of fraud the
dominant issue and attempting an ambitious monitoring effort.
Several opposition parties said they would send thousands to
polling stations across Mexico to ensure honest elections.
   Some, like 54-year-old businessman Manuel J. Clouthier of the
rightist National Action Party, or PAN, vowed to lead campaigns of
civil disobedience if the elections were crooked.
   A double slaying Saturday cast a pall over a campaign that for
the most part has been a war of words.
   Four bullets to the head killed one of candidate Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas' top strategists, Francisco Ovando Hernandez, on his way
home from a political meeting. Cardenas is a maverick reformer who
quit the PRI to run as the candidate of a predominantly leftist
coalition.
   Ovando's aide, Ramon Gil Heraldez, also was shot and killed and
documents on the National Democratic Front's election monitoring
vanished from their car.
   Cardenas, 54, spent Tuesday mourning Ovando, a longtime friend
and political ally who served as his attorney general when Cardenas
was governor of the central state of Michoacan.
   Jorge Obrador Capellini, Mexico City judicial police director,
said Tuesday that an investigation determined that the killing was
in revenge for Ovando's battles against organized crime while
Michoacan attorney general.
   He said he ruled out a political motive for the murder. Police
are investigating about 15 suspects but none have been arrested, he
said.
   A Gallup poll of 2,960 Mexican voters last month showed Cardenas
running a strong second to Salinas de Gortari. According to the
poll, the responses indicated that Salinas de Gortari would get
about 56 percent of the vote, Cardenas 23 percent and Clouthier 19
percent.
   The remaining 2 percent were undecided or favored the two other
candidates: Rosario Ibarra de Piedra, a human rights activist
running on the ticket of the small, radical Revolutionary Workers
Party, and Gumersindo Magana Negrete, the conservative Roman
Catholic activist who is the candidate of the Mexican Democratic
Party. The margin of error was 3 percent.
   The poll was conducted in late May and early June and was
commissioned by ECO, Inc., a Los Angeles-based company affiliated
with Televisa, a private Mexican television station with ties to
the government.
   Clouthier and his free-market economics are popular in northern
Mexico. Cardenas' base of support is in his home state and in
sprawling Mexico City, home to a quarter of the nation's 80 million
people.
   The PRI's strength lies in organized labor, among the
traditional folk of the countryside and in the many labor, business
and social organizations it controls. It also is the only party
with organizations nationwide.
   On Tuesday, the liberal newspaper La Jornada published a poll
showing Salinas de Gortari could receive 50 percent of the vote,
Cardenas 27.6 percent and Clouthier 18.3 percent. It had a 5
percent margin of error.
   More than 38 million people are registered to vote in Mexico,
where a one-term president takes office every six years on Dec. 1.
   The 64 senators, two from each of the 31 states and the federal
district, also serve single, six-year terms. Deputies serve
three-year terms.
   In a nation where one party has dominated politics for
generations, voter apathy is common. For weeks, the government and
party leaders had been urging people to vote and to do so
peacefully.
   Even the Roman Catholic Church broke its long silence on
politics, exhorting the faithful to do their civic duty and the
government to hold clean elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
