<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Meese-Glance     07-06 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Glance,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Legal Troubles At A Glance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, is a look at Attorney
General Edwin Meese III's legal troubles, which began last May 11
when independent counsel James C. McKay launched a criminal
investigation of his activities. McKay, who filed his report
Tuesday to a three-member federal appeals court panel, found
insufficient evidence to recommend criminal prosecution of Meese at
this time.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the various matters that have been
investigated:
   _The involvement of Meese when he was White House counselor with
Wedtech Corp., a New York City defense contractor on whose behalf
Meese intervened in 1981 at the behest of his longtime friend, E.
Robert Wallach.
   _The attorney general's actions, again at Wallach's request, in
connection with a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline project. Wallach, a
San Francisco lawyer, was representing one of the project's
partners.
   _Meese's $14,000 in telephone industry stock holdings at a time
when he met with executives of the regional Bell companies, who
were seeking a reversal of Justice Department policy opposing
expansion into new areas of business by the regional firms. Wallach
wrote a memo to Meese urging him to become personally involved in
the matter, and within weeks the attorney general approved a
reversal of the department's position.
   _The role of Wallach in helping obtain a job for Meese's wife,
Ursula, whose $40,000-a-year salary came from a contribution from a
Washington real estate family leasing space to the Justice
Department.
   _The Office of Professional Responsibility, a Justice Department
unit which examines improper behavior inside the department, is
expected to study ethical questions raised by McKay's office in its
report.
   _In a matter unrelated to McKay's inquiry, the Office of
Government Ethics is launching an investigation into why Meese
solicited 30,000 lawyers and businessmen to pay more than $3,000
apiece to a profit-making organization to attend a conference in
Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoatCapsizes     07-06 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boat Capsizes,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Dead, One Missing After Boat Capsizes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diving crews searched for a full day
but were unable to locate the body of a 5-year-old boy presumed
killed in a July Fourth boating accident that left three others
dead, police said.
   The 20-foot boat, which authorities said was overloaded, was
carrying 15 people as it returned from a fireworks display. The
boy's mother and sister were among the victims.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Scott Whalen said the search was
suspended because of darkness Tuesday and that local authorities
would resume the search today without Coast Guard assistance.
   The bodies of the other three victims were immediately recovered
but the 5-year-old, Kenneth Carvalho, was not found, according to
New Bedford Police Officer Ray Furtado.
   The boat was headed to the dock when ``two boats passed them,
one on each side, at a high rate of speed, causing large waves,''
Furtado said. The wakes caused the overloaded boat to flip over in
the New Bedford Harbor.
   ``It was definitely overloaded, definitely over capacity,''
Coast Guard Petty Officer David Foley said.
   Other boaters rescued the 11 survivors, Petty Officer 1st Class
Brandy Ian said.
   When the Coast Guard arrived, they found the bodies of Jean
Fauteaux, 49, and Maria Carvalho, 27, the missing boy's mother.
Coast Guard divers pulled the body of Mrs. Carvalho's 15-month-old
daughter, Melissa, from under the overturned boat. The victims were
all of North Dartmouth.
   The missing boy's sister, Amy Lynn Carvalho, 8, was released
Tuesday from St. Luke's Hospital in New Bedford. Alan Vieira Jr.,
1, of New Bedford was in good condition today, hospital spokeswoman
Jennifer Pollard said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL-Bakkers     07-06 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL-Bakkers,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Security Chief Says He Didn't Bar Bakkers from Heritage USA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker and PTL officials disputed the
reception the former television evangelist received when he
appeared at the ministry's Heritage USA theme park over the holiday
weekend.
   Bakker said Tuesday that PTL Chief of Security Gene Ervin asked
him and his wife, Tammy, to stay away from Fourth of July
ceremonies at Heritage USA Monday night after earlier weekend
appearances caused a commotion.
   Bakker said Ervin told him that PTL trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton
``was worried because of the amount of people that would gather
around us, that it would be dangerous.''
   But Ervin said, ``I only advised them that if they came on the
property, we didn't want any type of disturbance. That was it.
There was no talk about prohibiting them from the property.''
   Bakker, who is seeking to buy back Heritage USA, said he and his
wife drew 2,400 supporters in afternoon visits Sunday and Monday.
On Sunday night, he said he and Tammy went out for ice cream and
were surrounded by supporters at a shopping mall connected to the
Heritage Grand Hotel.
   ``It was so overwhelming,'' Bakker said. ``They started saying,
`We want you back.' They followed us to our car. We decided to go
home.''
   But Ervin said th crowd of between 150 and 200 people included
many who do not support their return.
   ``There was some hecklers and jeers coming from the crowd. Some
elderly people were shoved, bumped, (and) pushed around,'' he said.
``It caused what I considered a safety hazard.''
   Ervin also said Bakker told him his supporters could riot upon
his command, a claim the evangelist denied.
</TEXT>
