<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reparations-LegalIssues     07-06 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reparations-Legal Issues,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families of Iran Air Victims Have Shaky Legal Claim, Lawyers Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner-Compensation, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the United States offers reparations to the
families of people killed in the attack on an Iranian jetliner, the
amount is likely to be far less than U.S. courts typically award in
liability cases, lawyers say.
   And if the U.S. does not voluntarily offer reparations, the
relatives of the 290 victims will have difficulty staking a claim
for compensation in the courts, according to experts in
international law.
   ``If the facts are as the Navy has said ... I would be surprised
if the Iranians would have a claim,'' said Don Wallace Jr., a
professor of international law at Georgetown University in
Washington and director of the International Law Institute.
   ``There is no remedy ... that I can think of offhand,'' agreed
Steven C. Nelson, a Minneapolis lawyer who is chairman-elect of the
American Bar Association's section on International Law and
Practice.
   Some members of Congress have called on the United States to
offer voluntary reparations to the relatives without conceding any
wrongdoing. Lawyers familiar with such ``ex gratia'' payments
predict that the payout would be modest by U.S. standards.
   ``If we said, `OK, we'll pay $20,000 per person' and did it
quickly, that's probably the sensible way to do it,'' said Andrew
Lowenfeld, a professor of international law at New York University.
   That is the amount specified by an international treaty, the
Hague Protocol, to which Iran is a signatory.
   Another lawyer, Lee S. Kreindler, who specializes in aviation
cases, estimated that such payments might run as high as $150,000
per passenger. But, he said, ``I would not expect offers to be made
in the magnitude of offers that are made in domestic U.S. air
accidents.''
   As far as suing for compensation, most lawyers say the
survivors' standing to demand compensation is tenuous at best.
   The problem for the survivors is that the U.S. government is
protected by sovereign immunity from claims by foreigners. Although
there are exceptions to that _ such as claims under the federal
Tort Claims Act _ they would appear to be ruled out in the Iranian
case because the accident occurred during combat.
   ``It's not simple negligence,'' said Lowenfeld. The Tort Claims
Act, he said, would apply in a case in which ``you're crossing
Fifth Avenue and a postal truck runs a red light and hits you.''
   Another possibility is that the Iranians could file a claim with
the International Court of Justice, as Nicaragua did after the
United States mined its harbors. In that case, however, the U.S.
simply rejected the jurisdiction of the world court, and presumably
it would do so again.
   ``This is the ultimate problem under international law _ there's
no sheriff,'' Nelson said.
   Kreindler said he believes the Iranians may have a case _ either
against the United States or against the airline. His clients have
included relatives of the passengers of the Korean Air Lines plane
that was shot down by the Soviet Union in 1983. Their case against
the Soviets was rejected; their case against KAL is pending before
the U.S. Supreme Court.
   ``I'll take the case,'' Kreindler said of the Iranian crash. ``I
think there's going to be a recovery if somebody makes a claim.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
