<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   07-06 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes in Armenia, Azerbaijan; Petition in Estonia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Armenians have gone on strike in two
southern republics, closing a major airport in Armenia and bringing
to a halt industry in a disputed area of adjacent Azerbaijan,
according to the official press.
   The report indicated the protesters were angered at how their
leaders had represented their demands to the national Communist
Party conference in Moscow.
   Earlier Tuesday, dissidents in the northern Baltic republic of
Estonia said they had gathered more than 6,000 signatures calling
for freedom for three imprisoned Estonian nationalists.
   The Soviet government daily Izvestia said the strike in Armenia
began Monday, a day after thousands of people met in the Theater
Square of Yerevan, the capital of the southern republic.
   The Armenians called for a strike after hearing the comments of
Armenia's representatives to the party conference that ended
Friday. The leaders had urged caution and restraint.
   Most Armenians want a region of Azerbaijan called
Nagorno-Karabakh annexed to Armenia. The mountain enclave's
predominantly Armenian population has been agitating since February
to be united with neighboring Armenia.
   Armenia supports the demand. Azerbaijan opposes it.
   In February, at least 32 people were killed in riots over
annexation which broke out in Sumgait, Azerbaijan.
   Most Armenians are Christian, most Azeris Moslem.
   In its report Tuesday, Izvestia said most flights in and out of
Yerevan were canceled and the airport was filled with stranded
travelers.
   ``Like yesterday,'' the report said, ``a series of the city's
industrial concerns aren't working, or are working with less than a
full work force.''
   The newspaper said that in Stepanakert, the largest city in
Nagorno-Karabakh, many industries and institutions were shut down.
   On Sunday, Izvestia said, thousands of people gathered on the
Yerevan city square to watch a television broadcast by delegates to
the four-day party conference in Moscow.
   During the conference, Armenian party leader Suren Arutyunyan
said authorities could not normalize the situation in Armenia,
where large demonstrations frequently have occurred in support of
the annexation demand.
   He proposed that the conference take up unspecified amendments
to the Soviet constitution.
   Delegates who spoke Sunday supported Arutyunyan's call for
restraint and went directly to the square to talk to the crowd.
Izvestia said that after a ``stormy debate,'' a committee was
formed and called for a general strike.
   The committee demanded that the Soviet Supreme Court take over
the trials of those charged in the Sumgait violence _ most of the
victims were Armenians _ and full disclosure about the alleged
poisoning of workers at a factory in the town of Masis.
   Izvestia provided no more information about the Masis incident,
except to say an investigation was under way.
   Solving ethnic disputes and increasing the economic autonomy of
the country's republics are two of the key issues in Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's program to restructure the Soviet state and economy.
   The dispute between Azerbaijan and Aremenia has given an
immediacy to these issues. Indeed, the party conference called for
greater attention to republics' calls for economic autonomy, but it
said authorities would not tolerate efforts to whip up ethnic
tensions.
   In addition to Azerbaijan and Armenia, delegates from the Baltic
states of Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia also brought up ethnic
questions at the conference.
   On Tuesday, about a dozen protesters demanding freedom for three
Estonian political prisoners said they had gathered more than 6,000
signatures during a five-day demonstration in Tallinn, Estonia.
   One of the protesters, Eve Parnaste, said the three prisoners
had been demanding publication of a secret 1939 non-aggression pact
between Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union that placed the Baltic
republics of Estonia, Lithuania and Latvia under Moscow's control.
   ``We will continue the demonstration until they are freed or
until the authorities give us an exact date for their release,''
she said during the protest outside the Estonian Supreme Court
building.
   All three were arrested this year, charged with spreading
anti-Soviet propaganda or slandering the Soviet state.
</TEXT>
