<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Chihuahua     07-06 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Chihuahua,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern State A Key In Presidential Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIHUAHUA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party is capable of gracefully accepting defeat could
be decided in this large and rebellious northern state.
   Nationally, party candidate Carlos Salinas de Gotari is expected
to win the presidency. But it is generally agreed that it will be
by the lowest margin ever, perhaps as low as 54 percent.
   In Chihuahua, a traditional stronghold of the conservative
National Action Party and also a state where the governing party
has been known to rig elections, the Institutional Revolutionary
Party has, for the first time, admitted it could lose four of six
congressional districts.
   National Action Party leaders said this week that the state
government has agreed to changes in the electoral procedure that
give them some hopes for a clean election.
   ``But I will tell you Thursday morning whether this was a fair
election,'' said Guillermo Prieto, a National Action Party
candidate favored to win a congressional seat.
   The opposition party has one congressional district in Chihuahua.
   In 1983, shortly after President Miguel de la Madrid took office
and promised respect for opposition electoral triumphs, state
elections in Chihuahua gave the National Action party seven
municipalities.
   It was a short-lived experiment. In 1986, in elections widely
believed to have been rigged, the governing party won back all of
the municipalities.
   If the Institutional Revolutionary Party loses the four
congressional districts in the two largest cities, Chihuahua and
Ciudad Juarez, at least one of the Senate seats could be in danger
too.
   National Action Party officials said the state government had
agreed to several of the opposition group's demands to improve the
electoral process, including the use of a better indelible ink than
that recommended by the national government.
   The electoral commission also agreed to move 300 voting booths
into schools instead of private homes, where they originally had
been scheduled.
   ``The state government is trying to improve its image,'' Prieto
said. ``It does not want any conflicts.''
   There are 1.3 million registered voters in the state. About 60
per cent of them are expected to vote.
</TEXT>
