<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     07-06 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Warns Against Misuse of Acne Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration says
consumers should be careful not to indiscriminately use the
prescription acne drug Retin-A to reduce wrinkles.
   Along with the consumer warning issued by the agency on Tuesday
came a warning that the agency is beginning a crackdown on
unlicensed manufacturers that have started to advertise and
distribute bogus drugs identified as Retin-A.
   ``Use of all these products amounts to an expensive therapeutic
gamble,'' FDA Commissioner Frank E. Young said in a statement.
   ``Long-term animal studies and well-controlled clinical trials
involving larger numbers of patients in various age groups are
needed to assess the risks and benefits of Retin-A as a wrinkle
reducer,'' Young said.
   Retin-A, manufactured by Ortho Pharmaceutical Corp. of Raritan,
N.J., has long been approved to treated acne and normally is
applied to small areas of the skin for limited periods of time, but
the drug received nationwide attention earlier this year when a
research article published in a mainstream medical journal
suggested it could reduce or reverse wrinkling due to aging and sun
damage.
</TEXT>
