<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-IRA     07-06 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-IRA,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Commandos Will Not Attend IRA Gibraltar Inquest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British commandos who killed three unarmed IRA
guerrillas in Gibraltar four months ago will not attend the inquest
there because doing so could endanger their lives, newspaper
reports said today.
   The Times of London said the seven commandos involved will not
go because Gibraltar coroner Felix Pizzarello, in a preliminary
ruling Tuesday, rejected conditions drawn up by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's government for concealing their identities.
   The seven belong to the British Army's Special Air Service
regiment. The elite undercover unit is hated by the Irish
Republican Army because of its deadly efficiency in killing
guerrillas inside and outside Northern Ireland.
   The Times quoted unidentified government sources as saying the
government decided not to send the agents to Gibraltar because they
``could not possibly risk being seen by anyone else other than the
coroner.''
   The Thatcher government had demanded the men only be interviewed
by Pizzarello. The coroner refused to comply.
   Speaking during a visit to Northern Ireland, Defense Secretary
George Younger said Tuesday it was for the seven commandos and
their lawyers to decide whether or not to attend the inquest, which
Pizzarello ruled will open in Gibraltar on Sept. 6.
   But The Times said today: ``Effectively, the government has
already decided that they should not appear.''
   Legislator Michael Mates said he was distressed that Pizzarello
had suggested no harm could come to the agents if they were seen
and identified by lawyers at the inquest.
   Mates, a member of Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative Party and
chairman of the House of Commons all-party defense select
committee, said it was possible the lawyers could be intimidated by
the IRA into giving descriptions of the commandos.
   The seven soldiers cannot be forced to attend because though
Gibraltar off the southern tip of Spain is a British colony, it has
its own local government and courts system and the inquest is
outside mainland British jurisdiction.
   The IRA admitted that guerrillas Mairead Farrell, Daniel McCann,
and Sean Savage were on ``active service'' in Gibraltar when they
were killed by the commandos on March 6.
   Active service is an IRA euphemism for gun and bomb attacks.
   British authorities said they were plotting a car bomb attack on
a British Army parade.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA wants to end British rule in
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland and unite it with
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic under socialist rule.
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey's government in the Republic of
Ireland has criticized the slayings on grounds the commandos
apparently made no attempt to arrest the guerrillas.
   The slayings triggered violence in Catholic areas of Northern
Ireland in which two British soldiers and seven other people were
killed.
   Alleged eyewitnesses said in a Thames Television documentary
that the guerrillas were shot as two apparently tried to surrender
and the third attempted to flee.
   This appeared to contradict a statement by Foreign Secretary Sir
Geoffrey Howe the day after the shootings. He told Parliament the
three were challenged as they walked toward the nearby Spanish
border and were slain because they ``made movements which led
security personnel to believe their lives were in danger.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
