<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile     07-06 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chile Blasts European Plan To Monitor Presidential Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry has denounced as
``grotesque'' the European Parliament's decision to monitor Chile's
presidential vote.
   A ministry statement, read by spokesman Carlos Ducci, said the
parliament's members exhibited ``ignorance and a distorted
appreciation of the Chilean institutional process.''
   The parliament on Tuesday approved a proposal by French deputy
Frances Andres Savi and agreed to create a special mission to
monitor the Chilean political campaign and balloting.
   The action represents ``a shocking attempt to unnaturally
intervene in the Chilean people's own affairs,'' the ministry said.
``It is grotesque.''
   Chile's military government plans a yes-or-no ballot later this
year on a single presidential candidate, to be picked by the heads
of the armed forces and national police.
   It will be the first presidential ballot since President Augusto
Pinochet, the right-wing army commander, seized power in a 1973
coup.
   No precise date has yet been established, nor has a candidate
been picked. Pinochet is expected to be the nominee.
   Pinochet's critics, along with the local Roman Catholic church,
have charged that his government is not giving proponents of a
``no'' vote equal access to television and other mass media.
   They also accuse him of using government resources to promote a
``yes'' vote and suppress dissent.
   Several opponents have called on the international community to
pressure Pinochet into providing fairer election conditions.
</TEXT>
