<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CaribbeanMeeting     07-06 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caribbean Meeting,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caribbean Leaders Condemn U.S. Interference In Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caribbean leaders say U.S. drug
policy has allowed Washington to meddle in the affairs of other
nations, including Panama and Caribbean countries.
   The prime ministers, meeting Tuesday for the ninth summit of the
Caribbean Community and Common Market, condemned drug trafficking
but criticized U.S. efforts to halt it, said Lester Bird, deputy
prime minister of Antigua-Barbuda and spokesman for the closed-door
meetings.
   Bird said ministers ``determined that the question of the
Justice Department in the United States seemingly wishing to have
its writ to run sovereign countries outside its territory is a
development which is of deep concern to the heads of government.''
   He said that while the ministers specifically discussed the case
of Panama, they also were concerned about similar situations
developing in Caribbean nations.
   The leaders plan to send a statement to President Reagan
``expressing our concern for what we see is a derrogation from the
rule of law within our territories,'' Bird said.
   Caribbean nations are poor and unable to wage a full-scale
battle against drugs and need outside help, the leaders agreed. The
issue, mentioned only briefly, was to be discussed further today,
Bird said.
   Prime Minister Sir Lynden Pindling of the Bahamas has been
investigated by a Florida grand jury in connection with allegations
of drug trafficking in the Bahamas.
   The United States has used economic sanctions in its attempt to
make Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega step down as that
country's de facto leader. Noriega was indicted in Florida earlier
this year for alleged drug trafficking.
   The Caribbean Common Market, formed in 1973 to promote trade
among its members, includes Antigua-Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados,
Belize, Dominica, Grenada, Guyana, Jamaica, Montserrat, St.
Kitts-Nevis, St. Lucia, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, and
Trinidad and Tobago.
</TEXT>
