<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PacificEarthquake     07-06 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pacific Earthquake,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Jolts Northern Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe earthquake hit
the northern islands of Papua New Guinea in the Pacific Ocean early
today, but there were no reports of major damage.
   The geophysical laboratory in Port Moresby reported a quake
registering 6.2 on the Richter scale and centered about 35 miles
west of Kandrian in West New Britain.
   It was felt as far away as Port Moresby about 320 miles to the
south, said laboratory spokesman Horst Letz.
   Letz said several aftershocks had been recorded but no serious
damage had resulted.
   The Hong Kong Royal Observatory earlier reported the quake had
measured 6.7 on the Richter scale.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   An earthquake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in
populated areas, while one measuring 7 is considered a major quake
capable of widespread heavy damage.
</TEXT>
