<DOCNO> AP880706-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-06 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sleek G-15 computer had all the
latest features: a reel-to-reel tape drive and punched-paper
software in two refrigerator-sized units, and a Teletype, all in
decorator robins' egg blue.
   In 1954, it was a state of the art marvel of compactness and
practibility, and at $50,000, a bargain to boot. It's inventor says
it just may have been the first personal computer.
   ``I like to think so. It was the first one you could put in a
regular office ... and let one person handle,'' the G-15's creator,
Harry D. Huskey, said Tuesday.
   The Smithsonian Institution agrees. It is acquiring Husky's own
model of the computer, manufactured by Bendix.
   ``We think it was a landmark device in shaping the computer
industry,'' said David Allison, chief curator of the Smithsonian's
Computer, Information and Society exhibit, planned for March 1990.
   ``It was the packaging of the hardware that made it important,''
he said.
   Huskey, 71, developed the G-15 over a period of several years,
beginning in 1952, while he was at Wayne University in Detroit on a
year's leave from the U.S. Bureau of Standards. He later sold the
design to Bendix.
   ``This was back at a time when the (computers) that worked were
all large ones in the million-dollar class,'' Huskey recalled in a
telephone interview. Huskey used a magnetic drum similar to today's
floppy disks for a memory instead of vacuum tubes then in use.
   His computer was dubbed G-15 _ G for general use and 15 to make
prospective buyers think there were more models, Huskey said.
Bendix, which thought it would sell only about 200, actually sold
400.
   ``Bendix was so happy at time, the chrome fittings (on the 400th
G-15) were gold plated,'' Huskey said. He said he doesn't know what
happened to that model.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ENCINITAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare French donkey born on the Fourth
of July has been dubbed Lafayette by its owners _ in honor of the
French general who served in the Continental army in the American
Revolution.
   ``He looks like a toy and has tiny feet,'' owner Sharon
Vanderlip said of the newborn. ``He's really sweet. He follows you
all around the place, kind of like a puppy.''
   Vanderlip believes that the 50-pound Lafayette is the first
Poitou donkey born in the United States. There are only 40 Poitous
worldwide, she said.
   ``This really is a critical moment in time for this breed, so it
was a very exciting experience. ... So far, he looks healthy. But
we've got our fingers crossed,'' she said.
   Vanderlip and her husband, Jack, both veterinarians in San Diego
County, have four other Poitous _ Sonette, Lafayette's mother;
Tartarin, his father; a third male named Tabarin, and a second
female Tosca. All were imported from France.
   Sonette, now 4, drew attention in late 1984 when U.S.
Agriculture Department officials ordered her destroyed or deported
for failing tests designed to detect equine disease.
   The Vanderlips and others criticized the nearly eight-decade old
testing procedures as outdated and unfair to donkeys and other
exotic equines, which have an unusual substance in their blood. The
outcry prompted a change in testing methods and allowed Sonette to
remain in the United States.
   Vanderlip said she and her husband had hoped for a female for
breeding purposes, but added: ``We're happy we have a live baby and
will take what we get. What we will do is breed Sonette again and
try for a female again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
