<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-06 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen today in
slow trading in Tokyo, while stock prices rose substantially.
   The dollar closed at 133.53 yen on the Tokyo Foreign Exchange
Market, down 0.77 yen from Tuesday's close. It opened at 133.45 and
traded between 133.30 yen and 133.88 yen during the day.
   Volume totaled $7.44 billion today, compared with $11.57 billion
the day before.
   The dollar went up to 134.85 yen Monday, the highest closing
rate since last Nov. 24, then dropped for two consecutive days.
   Dealers said dollar-selling pressure pervaded the market in the
wake of the U.S. currency's weakening against the yen and the West
German mark on overseas markets.
   An official of the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the market was dull in anticipation of the
announcement of U.S. unemployment figures, expected on Friday.
   On the Tokyo Stock market, the Nikkei stock average of 225
selected issues, the market's main barometer, rose by 189.43 or
0.69 percent, to close at 27,766.60 points.
   Trade volume totaled 2.8 billion shares, up from 1.5 billion
shares on Tuesday.
   An official of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage
house, said the rise in stock prices here reflected the increase in
the New York stock market.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, added that
investors now believe the dollar will not advance further against
the Japanese yen.
</TEXT>
