<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Work     07-06 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Work,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Demands End to Interference in Farming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the national Communist Party
conference want state and collective farms to operate with less
meddling from party and government bureaucrats.
   The delegates called for less interference in farm operations in
a resolution adopted at the conference last week and published
Tuesday.
   Among the most frequent criticisms during the conference was the
refrain that despite three years of economic reform programs, few
improvements in living standards are reaching average people.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said the biggest single
problem was improving food supplies in a country of chronic
shortages and frequent rationing.
   In the resolution, delegates told party and government agencies
to let farms work out their own arrangements with workers and
cooperatives.
   ``Any attempts to command collective and state farms should be
stopped immediately,'' the resolution said, adding that the farms
are capable of solving their problems independently.
   Soviet officials had said before the conference that Gorbachev
hoped for a quick boost in farm production by encouraging state and
collective farms to lease land to individuals and families who
would be permitted to grow what they wish and keep most of their
profits.
   Some experiments suggest family farming could boost Soviet
agricultural productivity by several times.
   The delegates, in their resolution on ``perestroika,'' or
restructuring, as Gorbachev calls his reform program, said the
shortest way to solve the food problem ``is to tap the potential of
the collective and state farms in full.''
   The farms could do this, the resolution said, by ``spreading
diverse forms of contract and lease arrangements (and) building a
far-flung network of cooperatives, both in relations with other
enterprises and sections of the economy.''
   Attacking the often-criticized Soviet labor force for working
too little and producing shoddy goods, the resolution said the
party must overcome the tendency to pay everyone the same wage,
regardless of who performs best.
   The Soviet system of full employment, low rent, heavily
subsidized basic foods and fully paid health care is often cited
for discouraging individual initiative and tolerating poor
performance.
   ``We must make people much more interested in a better end
result,'' the resolution said, ``utterly overcome equalization
tendencies, adhere more boldly and everywhere to the principle of
compensating work in accordance with its quantity and _ especially
_ quality, to rule out a possiblity of living a comfortable life
while doing shoddy work.''
   In a separate document attacking ``petty patronism'' and
unresponsive, inconsiderate and overcautious bureaucrats, the
delegates proposed to tie managers' salaries to ``the
cost-effective results of the work performed by individual
industries, enterprises, organizations and territories.''
   The delegates issued what amounts to a license for the
state-controlled press to root out ``manifestations of bureaucratic
attitudes.''
   Apparently offering encouragement to would-be humorists, the
resolution added: ``The potential of the genre of satire should be
fully used in combating the negative phenomena.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
