<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoctorArrested     07-06 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctor Arrested,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Arrested After Shooting Patient Who Broke Into Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent neurologist was arrested on a
weapons charge after shooting a former patient who broke into his
Fifth Avenue office in Manhattan, police said.
   The patient, Jay Shaheri, was also arrested Tuesday on burglary
and attempted assault charges, police said.
   According to police, Shaheri, 38, was dissatisfied with
treatment by Dr. David Coddon after an accident in which the
unemployed waiter was struck by a woman who committed suicide by
jumping from a building.
   A $20 million lawsuit Shaheri filed against the woman's estate
was settled last week for $500,000.
   Shaheri was angry over Coddon's testimony in the case, and
apparently owed him $6,000 for treatment, said the physician's
lawyer, Harry Lipsig.
   Shaheri, carrying a 3-foot cane, went to Coddon's office
Tuesday, and began pounding on a locked door. He then punched
through a glass door, opened the door and began pounding on another
door, police said.
   At that point, Coddon, 65, retreated to a conference room and
locked the door. Shaheri broke into the conference room and
approached Coddon, who fired once, hitting the man in the left
side, said Aaron Rosenthal, Manhattan chief of detectives.
   ``I didn't want to kill him. I just wanted to stop him,'' the
doctor said.
   Shaheri was in stable condition at Mount Sinai Hospital.
   Police said Shaheri, who has said he is having financial
difficulties, has threatened Coddon.
   The 65-year-old doctor, an author and expert on headaches, runs
the Headache Clinic at Mount Sinai. He was charged with illegal
weapon possession, police said.
   Coddon, of Englewood, N.J., is licensed to carry his .38-caliber
handgun in New Jersey but not in New York.
</TEXT>
