<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Powerful Thunderstorms Over the Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Powerful thunderstorms boomed over the northern Plains today
after unleashing as many as five tornados in North Dakota and
Montana that destroyed a barn and other buildings.
   Thunderstorms brought brief heavy rain to drought-hit eastern
sections of North Dakota and northwest Minnesota.
   Scattered thunderstorms rumbled from the northwest Texas
Panhandle to southwest New Mexico, and widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms fell along the Gulf Coast into central Floria.
   As many as four tornadoes were reported Tuesday in Montana,
including one that touched down southeast of Big Sandy, destroying
a barn, a bunkhouse and other buildings. Twisters were also sighted
near Westby, Fort Benton and Langdon. Near Ulm, strong thunderstorm
winds destroyed a barn and moved a large trailer 60 feet.
   In North Dakota, a tornado was reported near Wales, hail 1{
inches in diameter fell near Fordville and winds gusted to 85 mph.
   Heavier rainfall in six hours overnight included nearly 2 inches
at Grand Forks, N.D., more than 1\ inches in the Dallas-Fort Worth
area and more than an inch at Barksdale Air Force Base near
Shreveport, La.
   A new heat wave baked the Midwest with temperatures over 100
degrees in some places Tuesday. Temperature records were broken in
13 cities and tied in eight.
   Today's forecast called for hot, humid weather prevailing in the
eastern two-thirds of the nation; scattered showers and
thunderstorms over Florida and from lower Alabama to the southern
Great Plains, with showers most numerous in Louisiana and southwest
Alabama; widely scattered showers and thunderstorms over the Rocky
Mountain states and over most of New England and New York; and a
few showers over the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s or 90s in most of
the nation; 100 degrees in parts of the northern and central Great
Plains and western Minnesota; over 110 degrees in the desert
Southwest; and 60s or 70s from the northern Rockies to the Pacific
Northwest and along the California Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Baker and Burns, Ore., and McCall, Idaho, to 95 degrees
at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 partly cloudy; Boston 68 partly cloudy;
Buffalo 69 fair; Charleston, S.C. 69 fair; Cincinnati 72 fair;
Cleveland 68 fair; Detroit 69 fair; Miami 78 fair; New York 67
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 68 fair; Pittsburgh 69 fair; Portland,
Maine 62 partly cloudy; Washington 71 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 80 fair; Chicago 78 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 74 fair; Denver 71 fair; Des Moines 74 fair;
Indianapolis 78 fair; Kansas City 82 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 80
fair; Nashville 71 fair; New Orleans 75 fair; St. Louis 81 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 66 fair; Anchorage 57 cloudy; Las Vegas 80
fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 95 fair; Salt Lake City 78 fair;
San Diego 65 fair; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 52 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 68 fair; Toronto 63 fair.
</TEXT>
