<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Taiwan     07-06 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Taiwan,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Seeks To Snare Taiwan Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China announced regulations today designed to
lure Taiwanese investors to the mainland to ``tap the potential
here and make money.''
   The word comes a day before Taiwan's governing Nationalist Party
holds a crucial congress at which it will discuss relaxing its ban
on trade with the mainland.
   The 22 regulations consolidate rules on tax breaks and other
incentives already offered by many coastal provinces and cities
closest to Taiwan, whose residents have covertly invested millions
of dollars on the mainland.
   ``We welcome Taiwan business people to come and tap the
potential here and make money, and we would like to learn from
their expertise,'' Yuan Mu, spokesman for the State Council,
China's cabinet, told a news conference in the Great Hall of the
People.
   ``It is profitable for (Taiwan residents) to come and invest
here,'' he said. ``The cost of production in Taiwan is rising. Some
Taiwanese capital needs to find outlets to other parts of the
world.''
   Taiwan has been estranged from the mainland since 1949, when the
Nationalists under Chiang Kai-shek lost a civil war to the
Communists. Chiang and thousands of followers fled to Taiwan, about
100 miles off the southeast coast, and set up a rival government.
   After decades of banning all contacts with the mainland, the
Nationalists last year began allowing Taiwan residents to visit
close relatives there. This spring, Taiwan began to permit mail
exchanges via the international Red Cross.
   Although Taiwan still bars trade and investment ties, many
Taiwanese businessmen secretly have invested in their mainland
ancestral homes. Two-way indirect trade totalled about $1.51
billion last year.
   The Nationalist congress is to consider allowing the indirect
import of raw materials such as coal from the mainland.
   The Communist government's investment regulations clearly were
timed to provoke debate at the session and encourage younger
Nationalists to press for faster liberalization.
   Beijing regards relatively prosperous Taiwan as a valuable
source of needed capital and technology and has said repeatedly it
is willing to forget the civil war legacy of hatred.
   The regulations generally treat Taiwanese the same as any
foreign investor, though Shen Jueren, vice minister of the Ministry
of Foreign Economic Relations and Trade, told the news conference
that terms are slightly more favorable.
   They guarantee the right to remit profits in convertible
currency, promise that no assets will be nationalized and exempt
Taiwan-funded enterprises from import and export taxes when they
manufacture goods for export.
   Taiwanese may develop land in coastal areas of the mainland, set
up wholly owned companies, enter into joint ventures with mainland
companies, buy stock or shares in mainland companies and engage in
compensation trade, the regulations say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Galanis     07-06 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Galanis,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tax Shelter Promoter Convicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tax shelter promoter who lost
millions of dollars for dozens of investors faces up to 207 years
in prison and $8 million in fines after being convicted of
masterminding fraud and racketeering schemes.
   Following a three-month trial, jurors deliberated for nine days
before finding John Peter Galanis guilty Tuesday of 44 counts,
including racketeering, tax fraud, securities fraud, bank fraud,
bribery and criminal contempt.
   Galanis, 44, who resides in Manhattan and Greenwich, Conn., is
scheduled to be sentenced Sept. 20 by U.S. District Judge Charles
Brieant.
   One co-defendant, Anthony Marchese, 47, of Southport, Conn., was
convicted of racketeering and bribery involving the now-defunct
Peoples National Bank in Rockland County and the Heritage Bank in
Salt Lake City.
   Marchese faces up to 55 years in prison and $530,000 in fines
when he is sentenced the same day.
   Two other co-defendants, Samuel Rosengarten, 66, of Armonk, and
Arthur Mason, 46, of Chevy Chase, Md., were acquitted of a variety
of counts.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Vincent Briccetti told jurors that
Galanis, who had pleaded guilty to securities fraud 15 years ago,
ran what he called the ``Galanis Organization'' to raise capital
for its members.
   Galanis was convicted of bribing officials of Peoples Bank,
which was forced into insolvency; fraudulently trying to take
control of Heritage Bank, which later was taken over by Utah
banking officials; seizing control of Columbia Federal Savings Bank
in Westport, Conn., through fraudulent misrepresentation to federal
regulators; and illegally taking over ISI Mutual Funds in Oakland,
Calif., and stealing $4 million in mutual fund assets.
   Galanis also was convicted of creating a syndication known as
Transpac Drilling Venture which promised investors grossly inflated
tax losses that could be used to reduce their income tax
liabilities.
   The 2,500 investors in the oil drilling business received more
than $172 million in fraudulent partnership losses between 1982 and
1984.
   Eleven other people pleaded guilty for their roles in Galanis'
various schemes and nine testified against him, Briccetti said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
