<DOCNO> AP880706-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SalemBombs     07-06 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salem Bombs,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thirteen Bombs Laid Around Quiet Town Failed to Explode</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomber's incompetence probably saved Salem
from explosions that could have damaged six bridges serving this
southern Indiana city as well as offices and businesses,
authorities said.
   At least 13 improperly wired bombs were discovered Tuesday, but
only three of them had ignited, producing only smoke and small
fires. Army bomb disposal units defused the others. There were no
injuries and no suspects.
   ``They used black powder as the cap, and it didn't detonate,''
said Paul Lyles, emergency management director for the Washington
County Department of Civil Defense. ``Luckily, the guy who put it
there didn't know much about explosives.''
   The bomber either lacked the expertise to properly wire the
bombs or did not have an essential component, said Capt. Ronald V.
Downing, an Army spokesman. He did not elaborate.
   The devices, which contained timers attached to as many as 26
sticks of gelatin dynamite, were all packaged in paper grocery
sacks and concealed next to bridges or buildings in this town of
6,000 people.
   Mayor Frank Newkirk Sr., who found one of the bombs next to a
bridge, said it ``was obviously an act of terrorism in my book,
certainly done by a wacko.''
   Morris Strange, who lives across from the service station, said
he arrived home to find officials surrounding it as they searched
for more bombs.
   ``Of course I was scared. You don't expect this to happen in any
town in the U.S. This isn't the Middle East,'' Strange said.
   A transient found under one of the bridges was taken in for
questioning but later released, police said.
   ``We have no indications of any motive at this time. We have no
suspects,'' said state police Sgt. Marvin Jenkins. ``Due to the
fact no one has been injured and there's no property damage yet,
we're very strongly hoping this is just a poor joke.''
   Portions of the city, which is surrounded by the Blue River and
Brock Creek, were evacuated and sealed off as bomb squads from Fort
Benjamin Harrison in Indianapolis and Fort Knox in Kentucky defused
the bombs.
   The devices were turned over to agents of the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms, which was investigating along with the Army,
FBI, state police and local agencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
