<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Television     07-06 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Television,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Will Probe Complaint It Used Phony Network News Crews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel will investigate a complaint that its
security agents posed as an ABC news crew so they could arrest a
Palestinian youth, a government spokesman said today.
   The television network made the allegation public on Tuesday and
demanded an investigation.
   ``We are going to check the whole issue,'' said Avi Pazner, an
aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. ``I can not tell now what
our response will be.''
   ``My first reaction was amazement over the strange way in which
the complaint was passed,'' Pazner added. ``A messenger brought it
to my house at 2 a.m. I find it strange that somebody has ordered
the complaint to be delivered at such an hour, as if a war has
started.''
   Dean Reynolds, ABC's Israel correspondent, said the network
learned about the incident on June 26, two days after it allegedly
occurred, and complained to the Israeli police, army and prime
minister's office.
   He said the network decided to make the complaint public after
receiving no satisfactory response.
   ``There have been other reports of this happening to other
agencies,'' Reynolds said. ``The central issue here is the danger
it puts my cameramen in'' should Palestinians think his crew is
Israeli security agents.
   ABC News President Roone Arledge sent a protest by telex Tuesday
to Shamir.
   ABC World News Tonight reported Tuesday that the phony news crew
had arrested a 17-year-old youth named Nizar Dakdouk of the
occupied West Bank village of Salfit.
   ABC News said it learned that ``the impostors were members of
the Israeli secret security service, Shin Bet.''
   Israeli troops demolished Dakdouk's home on June 16, saying the
youth had thrown a firebomb at a bus, the report said.
   The youth and his mother complained the next day on Israeli
television that if he was suspected of something the army should
have arrested him before blowing up the house, ABC said.
   A week after the TV appearance, Israeli civilians posing as ABC
News personnel arrived at the Dakdouk family's temporary housing in
two cars and said they wanted to interview Dakdouk and his brother
on the site of the destroyed house, the report said. The boys
agreed to go.
   At the site, one of the cars sped off with Dakdouk and he was
later arrested, ABC said.
</TEXT>
