<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `Gold opened ...,' with 1 graf to CORRECT
closing gold bid Tuesday. PICKS up 14th graf, `In Zurich ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in light European trading early
today as the British pound continued to gain on Monday's increase
in British interest rates. Gold rose.
   Dealers said an overnight bout of profit-taking appeared to have
sputtered out and they expected the dollar to trade in a narrow
range for the rest of the day.
   The dollar continued to be buoyed by increased tension in the
Persian Gulf following Sunday's downing by the U.S. Navy of an
Iranian civilian jetliner, they said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to a closing 133.53 Japanese yen from
134.30 yen at Tuesday's close. Later, in London, it slipped to
133.50 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8170 West German marks, down from 1.8235
   _1.5105 Swiss francs, down from 1.5165
   _6.1195 French francs, down from 6.1430
   _2.0464 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0600
   _1,347.75 Italian lire, down from 1,355.50
   _1.2120 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2134
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7150 from $1.7075 late
Tuesday. British commercial banks increased their base lending rate
to 10 percent Monday to stem the pound's five-week slide.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $438.50 an ounce, up
from $437.25 bid late Tuesday. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $438.10.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $438.20, up from $437.50 bid
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid price of
$441.05 from $440.41 bid at Tuesday's close.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $6.78 an ounce,
up from $6.74 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
