<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     07-06 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Wounds Catholic, Chases and Kills Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assailant shot and wounded a
Roman Catholic from a passing car today, then sped after the
fleeing man, fired again and killed him, police said.
   Terry Delaney, 30, was walking to work along a main street in
the market town of Dromore, 17 miles southwest of Belfast, when he
was shot in the head, police said. He was shot several more times
as he ran away, police said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility. Delaney's
father, Hugh, said his son belonged to no armed organization.
   Forty people, including 20 civilians, have died in Northern
Ireland this year in political and sectarian violence.
   The almost exclusively Catholic Irish Republican Army is
fighting to push the British out of the Protestant-dominated
province, join it with the Republic of Ireland and set up an
all-Ireland socialist state.
   Town councilor Draw Nelson said local people ``are absolutely
shattered and are in a state of shock. This is the first incident
of this type that has been in Dromore, although there were people
killed in a firebombing at their home many years ago. It is an
appalling crime and totally sickening.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
