<HEAD>North Korea Denounces U.S. Downing Of Iranian Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Airliner-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea denounced the U.S. Navy's downing of an
Iranian jetliner over the Persian Gulf, in which all 290 people
aboard died, an official report said today.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman issued a statement calling the
incident a ``barbaric massacre'' and ``a hideous crime against the
Iranian people,'' according to the North Korean Central News
Agency, monitored in Tokyo.
   The spokesman, whom the report did not name, termed the attack a
``deliberate provocation to escalate the war in the Persian Gulf.''
   The United States said its forces mistook the civilian jetliner
for an Iranian jet fighter.
   The Foreign Ministry spokesman also accused the United States of
massing military forces in and around South Korea.
   ``No one can vouch that the United States, while leading the
situation on the Korean Peninsula to a higher pitch of strain,
would not commit again some terrorism and provocation against our
republic when it thinks necessary,'' the statement said.
   ``Our people are sharply watching every move of the enemy with
heightened vigilance,'' it added.
