<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 2ndLd-Writethru a0523 07-06 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0523,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Say Soldiers Kill One at Airport; Government Denies It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Foreign Ministry denying
reports of people killed. Pick up 17th graf pvs: `Mikhail
Padalovich...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists said today that soldiers opened fire on
protesters who shut down the airport in the Armenian capital of
Yerevan and that at least one protester was killed. A Foreign
Ministry spokesman denied the report.
   The Foreign Ministry spokesman, Vadim Perfilyev, told reporters
that soldiers routed 400 protesters from inside the terminal at
Zvartnots airport Tuesday. He said 36 people were hurt in the
confrontation and that one man was killed in another town as a
result of ``hooliganism'' not related to the incident.
   Perfilyev said the protesters threw rocks and bottles at police
and soldiers, according to the news agency Tass.
   Alexi Mananikov, an editor of the unofficial Moscow journal
Glasnost, said 22-year-old Khachik Kazaryan was killed in the
airport confrontation.
   He said sources in Yerevan told him as many as 40 people were
wounded by soldiers trying to reopen the airport Tuesday night.
   Artist Kuryun Nahabidyan, an Armenian activist in Moscow,
reported three unidentified students were killed. ``Officers shot
them with pistols,'' he said.
   Yerevan has been the scene of massive protests by demonstrators
demanding annexation of the Nagorno-Karabakh region of the
neighboring southern republic of Azerbaijan. The demonstrations had
been peaceful.
   The government daily Izvestia reported Tuesday that thousands of
Armenians went on strike in Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh and that
most flights in and out of the airport had been canceled.
   Perfilyev told reporters that security soldiers were sent to the
airport, but he denied that anyone was killed. He said one man was
hurt in the town of Masis about six miles southwest of Yerevan.
   ``He was taken to the hospital on the same day and died there.
But this man had nothing to do with the events at the airport,''
Perfilyev said. ``The rumors that an Armenian was killed are
groundless.''
   Nahabidyan said demonstrators went to the airport to try to stop
military planes from bringing in paratroopers, tanks and machine
guns. ``The army has occupied all of Armenia. Nagorno-Karabakh,
too,'' he said.
   Perfilyev said more than 400 people gathered inside the terminal
at Zvartnots Airport, and another 1,500 surrounded it.
   ``They impeded the sale of tickets and the collection by
passengers of their luggage, ventured out onto the landing strips,
prevented passengers from entering the terminal and paralyzed the
work of the dispatcher services,'' Tass said.
   Internal security soldiers using loudspeakers finally got the
protesters out of the terminal, it said. ``They were forced out,
but there were no clashes or fights,'' Perfilyev said.
   An editor at the Armenpress Armenian news agency, reached by
telephone in Yerevan, was asked if there were many soldiers in
Yerevan. ``I didn't see any soldiers,'' she said. The telephone
call was interrupted before she could be asked her name or further
information.
   The reports indicated the protesters in Armenia were angered at
how their leaders represented their demands to last week's national
Communist Party conference in Moscow.
   Most Armenians want Nagorno-Karabakh united to neighboring
Armenia. The mountain enclave's predominantly Armenian population
has been agitating for the annexation since February.
   Armenia supports the demand. Azerbaijan opposes it.
   In February, at least 32 people were killed in riots over
annexation which broke out in Sumgait, Azerbaijan.
   Mikhail Padalovich, an editor of the Communist Party newspaper
Kommunist in Yerevan, said he had no information about an airport
incident. He said there were no demonstrations in the city and
workers were at their jobs.
   The Armenian republic's office in Moscow declined comment on the
reports.
   Izvestia said activists met Sunday in Yerevan with delegates to
the Communist Party conference, which ended Friday in Moscow.
Apparently dissatisfied with the Armenian delegation's presentation
of the dispute, they called a strike.
   Solving ethnic disputes and increasing the economic autonomy of
the nation's republics are two key issues in Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
program to restructure the Soviet state and economy.
   The party conference called for greater attention to republics'
calls for economic autonomy, but it said authorities would not
tolerate efforts to incite ethnic tensions.
</TEXT>
