<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Dell     07-06 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Dell,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gabe Dell, One of Original ``Dead End Kids,'' Dies at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gabe Dell, who parlayed his youthful success
as one of the original ``Dead End Kids'' into a career spanning
more than 50 years as a writer, director, teacher and stage and
film actor, has died. He was 68.
   The Brooklyn, N.Y.-born Dell, whose real name was Gabriel del
Vecchio, died at his North Hollywood home Sunday of leukemia.
   ``That leaves two of us,'' said Dr. Bernard Punsley, a Torrance
physician who is one of the two surviving ``Dead End Kids.'' The
other is actor Huntz Hall, who was in mourning and declined to take
calls Tuesday.
   Dell, Punsley, Hall and the other Dead End Kids shot to fame on
Broadway in 1935 in ``Dead End,'' Sidney Kingsley's examination of
slum life and its connection to crime.
   Following the play's success, the young actors were brought to
Hollywood to star opposite Humphrey Bogart in the movie version.
   Like the rowdy characters they portrayed on stage and screen,
the actors pulled pranks on the porters and played ball in the
aisles during their train trip to Hollywood.
   Meanwhile, their movie went on to garner four Academy Award
nominations, and the young actors went on to make a number of major
films and low-budget productions under the names the Bowery Boys
and Eastside Kids. Among them were ``Angels With Dirty Faces'' and
``Crime School.''
   Some of the other Dead End Kids, such as Leo Gorcey, Billy Halop
and Bobby Jordan, were unable to shed their bad-boy screen images
in later years.
   Dell, however, went on to star as an adult in such Broadway
plays as ``Luv'' and ``The Goodbye People'' as well as work as a
character actor in such films as ``Earthquake'' and ``Who Is Harry
Kellerman ....''
   A student of Zen, he once said: ``I love the freedom that acting
gives me. I don't care if a show I'm in is a hit or not.''
   Surviving are two sons, Gabriel Jr. and Michael, both actors,
and a sister, Ethel Dell. Funeral services will be private.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
