<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Shultz-Asia     07-06 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Asia,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Begins Asian Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
arrived in Thailand today to begin a nine-nation Asian tour and to
deal with issues ranging from the Olympics in Seoul to the future
of Cambodia.
   He also will likely face questions on Sunday's downing of an
Iranian airliner by U.S. naval forces in the Persian Gulf.
   A senior Thai military officer said security precautions were
being increased because of the gulf tragedy. The officer, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said sharpshooters were included in a
security task force that included police, air force and army
personnel.
   Shultz's two-week journey is to be his last and longest to Asia
as secretary of state. After Thailand, he goes to Malaysia,
Indonesia, the Philippines, Hong Kong, China, South Korea, Japan
and the new Marshall Islands Republic in the Pacific.
   In Bangkok, he planned to meet Thursday with ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations and representatives from
Japan, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, Australia and the European
Community.
   The future of Cambodia, where Vietnamese forces have begun
withdrawing after invading the country nearly a decade ago, is
expected to be a major topic of discussion.
   Shultz is expected to stress that the United States would find a
return to power of the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge totally
unacceptable. The communist Khmer Rouge are the most powerful group
within a coalition fighting the Vietnamese, who have pledged to
withdraw from Cambodia by 1990.
   U.S. policy calls for total withdrawal of Vietnamese forces;
support for the coalition led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk; and
seeking of a political solution to the Cambodian conflict.
   The Association of Southeast Asian Nations, who held their
annual conference here this week, said they would ask the United
States and other countries to increase their intake of Indochinese
refugees from Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
   Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia and Hong Kong have recently
toughened their policies on providing Vietnamese ``boat people''
with temporary asylum, moves that Washington has criticized.
   U.S. trade deficits with newly prosperous Asian nations, U.S.
government subsidies to American farmers and an extensive aid
package for the economically troubled Philippines also will be
discussed.
   Shultz is likely to meet a sympathetic official audience when
explaining the downing of the Iranian jet carrying 290 people, all
of whom are believed to have died.
   But the Malaysian Foreign Ministry on Tuesday deplored the
incident, saying it was difficult to accept U.S. claims that its
forces mistook the large civilian aircraft for a military jet.
   Talks in Beijing may focus on American concern about a reported
flow of Chinese missiles to the Middle East, according to sources
in Washington.
   Shultz expects to deliver a major speech in Seoul on July 18 on
expanding democracy and human rights in South Korea. There will
also be discussions on the running of a trouble-free summer Olympic
Games which begin in the South Korean capital Sept. 17.
   The presence of U.S. air bases in the Philippines will probably
be debated in Manila.
   Trade issues and Japan's emerging role as both a political and
economic force in Asia are likely to feature in discussions in
Tokyo, Shultz's last stop on the Asian continent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0094 </DOCNO>
