<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     07-06 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Says She Will Not Stop Marcos' Return For Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said today
she will let Ferdinand Marcos return to the Philippines so he can
stand trial on charges of stealing billions of dollars during his
20-year rule.
   Mrs. Aquino made the remark shortly before today's Cabinet
meeting.
   When asked by reporters if she would allow Marcos, her ousted
predecessor, to return to defend himself, she replied, ``Yes, of
course.''
   ``As I have said, if due process will be observed, then
naturally the decision of the court will be respected,'' she added.
   Officials of the Presidential Commission on Good Government have
said they expect to file criminal charges against Marcos by
January. The task of the commission is to recover up to $10 billion
that Marcos and his family allegedly stole from the government or
acquired in other illegal ways during his rule.
   Commission chairman Ramon Diaz told reporters today he was
waiting for Swiss authorities to release information on Marcos'
Swiss bank accounts, which are to be used as evidence against the
deposed president. Swiss officials have said they can release the
information only after prosecution begins.
   The Philippines does not allow trial in absentia, so Marcos
would have to be allowed into the country to stand trial. Since
February 1986, he has lived in exile in Hawaii.
   ``After we receive the evidence from Swiss banks, then we will
file the case,'' Diaz said. ``When the criminal case is filed,
(Mrs. Aquino) is not going to put any obstacle to call in Marcos
home to Manila because he has to face the courts.''
   Mrs. Aquino has so far refused to allow the former president to
return for security reasons. She came to power after Marcos was
ousted during a civilian-military revolt in February 1986.
</TEXT>
