<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Asylum,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two East German Musicians Seek Asylum In West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two musicians from the East German state opera
orchestra have left Japan for asylum in West Germany, a Japanese
Foreign Ministry official said today.
   Gunther Clajus, 57, a viola player, and violinist Rainer Doll,
23, left Tuesday night aboard a Lufthansa flight bound for
Frankfurt, the official said. Both are members of East Germany's
Staatskapelle Berlin.
   Earlier Tuesday, Clajus and Doll called on the West German
Embassy in Tokyo to request asylum and were granted it. Embassy
officials notified the Japanese government.
   The ministry official said both men told Japanese officials they
did not want to return to East Germany. He said there were no
``political motives'' behind the defection, but he refused to
provide further details.
   Local news reports said that prior to Tuesday's defection, a
total of five East German musicians over the past five years have
decided to defect to West Germany while touring Japan. The most
recent case involved a guitarist with an East German circus troupe
in September 1985.
   The 112-member Staatskapelle Berlin toured Japan from June 10 to
July 5.
   The remaining members of the orchestra left for East Germany on
Tuesday afternoon on a chartered flight, according to East German
Embassy officials in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
