<HEAD>Seven Thai Villagers Killed in Cambodia Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven people, five of them children,
were killed and seven wounded when three artillery shells fired
from inside Cambodia landed in their village today, an army officer
said.
   It was not known who fired the shells into Sai Tho Kao village
of Buriram province near the Cambodian border. Fighting inside
Cambodia between the Vietnamese-backed government and a coalition
of guerrillas frequently spills into Thailand.
   The officer said Thai intelligence had recently received reports
of fighting between Vietnamese troops and Khmer Rouge guerrillas
near the village.
   The officer said Thai gunners fired warning shots into Cambodia
after the shells landed in the village. He spoke on condition he
not be identified.
   Vietnam says it is withdrawing about 50,000 of its troops from
Cambodia, which it invaded in 1978 to rout the Khmer Rouge from
power. The Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge now makes up part of the
guerrilla coalition headed by Prince Norondom Sihanouk.
   U.S. intelligence reports say Vietnam has already handed over
much of the military operations along the Thai-Cambodian border to
government troops.
