<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ali-Hatch,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Float Like A Butterfly, Sting Like A Bee, Hatch Gets Backing Of
Muhammad Ali</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muhammad Ali says he's more concerned
about character than politics and that's why he can support both
conservative Sen. Orrin Hatch and liberal Sen. Edward Kennedy.
   ``I don't judge people by their political label, just like I
don't like people to judge me,'' the three-time world heavyweight
boxing champion said. ``I have friends who are Republicans, friends
who are Democrats.''
   Ali, who will campaign for Hatch in Utah this fall, said he
doesn't always agree with Hatch's conservatism, but, ``I respect
the fact that he does what he believes in, and fights on for what
he believes in.''
   ``I think (Hatch) is a remarkable man,'' Ali said Tuesday in a
telephone interview from Charlottsville, Va. ``Man, he's one of the
most effective leaders in the U.S. Senate. Any time he wants me to
be there, I'll be there.''
   Ali said the Republican Hatch and Kennedy, D-Mass., so often at
odds in Senate debate, have in common their struggle to overcome
their environments.
   ``Orrin Hatch was very poor. He grew up on the wrong side of the
tracks,'' he said. ``Ted Kennedy was a rich boy, didn't have to do
anything ... (but) instead he dedicated himself to public life,
even though he knew it could cost him his own life, like it did
with his two brothers.''
   Hatch campaign manager Bud Scruggs said the chance to have ``The
Greatest'' campaign for his boss was too good to pass up.
   Scruggs said Ali began to admire Hatch last year when he watched
televised congressional hearings on the Iran-Contra scandal, in
which the senator repeatedly leaped to the defense of Marine Lt.
Col. Oliver North, and during the Senate hearings on the
unsuccessful nomination of Robert Bork to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Hatch later helped push through the appointment of one of Ali's
friends, Steven Saltzburg, to a Justice Department post.
</TEXT>
