<HEAD>Grosz For More Open Media Coverage of Government, Party Meetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz has
called for more openness in Hungary's media coverage of government
and party work and announced that the next meeting of the party
leadership will be broadcast live.
   In an article today in the Communist daily Nepszabadsag, Grosz
said he was ``deeply impressed'' with the openness of the Soviet
press.
   Grosz returned Tuesday from a one-day visit to Moscow where he
held talks with Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   According to Nepszabadsag, Grosz said ``the Hungarian media can
report on anything but military secrets.''
   He told the newspaper that a meeting of the party Central
Committee scheduled for July 13 would receive extensive coverage.
The official news agency MTI reported from Moscow on Tuesday that
Grosz had announced at a news conference there that the meeting
would be broadcast live on Hungarian television and radio.
   The proceedings of the party have traditionally been conducted
behind closed doors and the results of such meetings announced in
minimal communiques issued at the end of the sessions.
   Last week, the parliament discussed personnel issues for the
first time in an open session that was marked by unusually fervent
debate.
