^Cities Outside Atlanta Vying For Democratic Tourist Dollars</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an attempt to lure participants in the
Democratic National Convention to cities in the state outside
Atlanta, the Georgia Tourist Division is making sure that each
delegate is greeted with a can of state-grown popcorn with the
words ``Georgia's Popping.''
   In addition, several cities including Marietta, Warm Springs,
Gainesville and Roswell are offering tours from the convention area
to their communities hile others will host delegation parties the
Sunday before the convention begins.
   The idea is to let other cities share the spotlight _ and a
share of the dollars to be spent by the more than 5,400 delegates,
15,000 members of the press and and others attending the July 18-21
convention.
   ``If we could get three or four press people, we will have done
what we wanted to accomplish,'' said Janice Marshall, executive
director of the Macon Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Satellite News Service To Provide Additional Convention Coverage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic party officials are betting that
local television stations will want more than the two hours a night
coverage of their convention activities planned to be broadcast by
the major networks. They have set up the Convention Satellite News
Service, which will transmit 46 hours of programming during
convention week.
   The transmissions will begin July 16, two days before the
Democrats open their parley in Atlanta's Omni arena and manager
Paul Byers said the material will be available to any television
station with a satellite dish. During the four-day convention the
service will beam live and taped material from 2 p.m. to midnight.
   Byers said four mobile crews will be operating in Atlanta to
provide local stations with packaged interviews with party
officials, live coverage of convention proceedings, both on and off
the floor, and to give them opportunities to interview area
politicians attending the convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stagehands Picketed Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a stagehands unions set up an
informational picket of The Omni, site of the Democratic National
Convention, to protest the party's agreement with a non-union
lighting and sound company.
   Alfred W. DiTolla, president of the International Alliance of
Theatrical Stage Employees, said the group is protesting the
Democrats' contract with Atlanta Sound and Lighting Co., a
non-union company, to provide lighting and rigging work for the
convention July 18-21.
   To win the contract, DiTolla said, Atlanta Sound and Lighting
had been forced to appeal to the stagehands for help, through the
National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians.
   DiTolla said the Republican National Convention in New Orleans
is using strictly union labor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis And Jackson Speak Via Satellite At Teachers' Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has
gotten the endorsement of the 3,000 delegates of the American
Federation of Teachers, but it is Jesse Jackson who was able to
bring the convention crowd to its feet.
   Both presidential candidates addressed the convention via
satellite as the four-day gathering was ending on Tuesday.
   ``If we are going to take on our foreign competitors, we have to
make teaching an honored and valued profession again,'' said
Dukakis, who spoke from Boston.
   Dukakis, the likely Democratic nominee, called for an
educational venture capital fund to improve teachers' pay and
training. He said the cost would be a fraction of the budget for
the Reagan administration's Strategic Defense Initiative.
   ``If the schools give homework, the parents must have the child
home to do the homework. We must pay for better educational
services ... by doubling the pay of teachers, as our most
fundamental investment in the future of America,'' said Jackson.
   Jackson also praised teachers and said it was the ``love
triangle'' between his mother, his teacher and his principal that
helped him succeed.
