<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--TeamstersSuit     07-06 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Teamsters Suit,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Ruling Yet on Latest Round in Teamsters Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has reserved decision on the
government's latest request in its campaign to reform the Teamsters.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Randy Mastro on Tuesday sought a
preliminary injunction to ``protect the membership from their own
leadership.''
   The government wants liaison officers appointed and empowered to
``discipline Teamsters corruption'' and appoint trustees for
corrupt locals.
   But Teamsters attorney John R. Climaco asked U.S. District Judge
David Edelstein to give the union more time to counter ``what we
consider the false and shameful allegations by the government.''
   Edelstein did not indicate when he would rule on the government
request.
   Last week the government, claiming the Teamsters were dominated
by the Mafia, filed a civil racketeering lawsuit seeking to place
the 1.6 million-member union under a court-appointed trustee who
would oversee `free and fair'' elections.
   The lawsuit also sought to oust any member of the union's
18-member executive board found to have committed or aided the
commission of racketeering activities.
