<DOCNO> AP880706-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 4thLd-Writethru a0567 07-06 0953</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0567,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Rounding Out Veep Interviews, Says Meese Resignation
Overdue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Specter attacking Dukakis, Dukakis to campaign
with Bentsen, subbing 5 grafs for grafs 8-9 pvs, Dukakis was ...
Babbitt.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis interviewed Rep. Lee Hamilton of
Indiana today, rounding out two days of interviews of prospective
running mates, including two former rivals in the Democratic
presidential race _ Sen. Albert Gore and Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   Hamilton said he would accept a vice presidential nomination, as
did Gephardt. Gore declined comment.
   Hamilton met with Dukakis for about 50 minutes this morning at
the Massachusetts governor's Statehouse office. That session
brought to seven the number of potential running mates interviewed
by the nominee-to-be in the past week.
   Two of them _ Gore and Gephardt _ visited Dukakis on Tuesday.
Jesse Jackson, who technically remains in the race although Dukakis
has a mathematical lock on the nomination, spent the Fourth of July
with Dukakis.
   The Massachusetts governor interviewed Sens. John Glenn of Ohio,
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and Bob Graham of Florida in Washington last
week.
   After today's meeting, Hamilton said he disccused the vice
presidency with Dukakis and would accept the nomination if it was
offered to him. ``I would accept it, first of all, if he thought I
could be helpful,'' said Hamilton, who has been adivising Dukakis
on foreign policy and economic issues.
   While Dukakis was in Boston stepping up the search, top adviser
Paul Brountas was in Washington on related business, conducting
research on the contenders and seeking input from party leaders.
Brountas was to remain in the nation's capital for several days.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis came under attack today on his home turf.
Republican Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania called a news
conference on the Statehouse steps to criticize a Massachusetts
program that, until it was amended earlier this year, allowed
inmates serving life sentences without chance for parole to be
furloughed. One such inmate raped a Maryland woman after escaping
while on furlough.
   Specter appeared at the request of likely Republican nominee
George Bush, and said he planned a similar event Thursday in
Denver. ``I think it raises a question as to his overall
judgment,'' Specter said of Dukakis' support of the furlough
program.
   The Dukakis campaign had local law enforcement officials,
prosecutors and Sen. John F. Kerry on hand to counter Specter.
Kerry and Specter engaged in a good-natured give and take but Kerry
had harsh words for Bush, saying he has been a failure in leading
the Reagan administration's anti-drug efforts.
   Dukakis was scheduled to meet with several civil rights leaders
this afternoon and was to address the Greek Orthodox Ecumenical
Congress, which is meeting in Boston. The certain Republican
nominee, Vice President George Bush, was to visit Dukakis' home
turf Thursday to address the same group.
   Dukakis also plans to travel to Arizona Friday, during a
three-day campaign swing through the West, to meet privately with
former rival and ex-Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt. The trip will also
include campaigning in Texas with Bentsen.
   Campaign aides said Dukakis would seek Babbitt's advice but that
the former governor was not being considered for the vice
presidential nomination.
   Gore waved to reporters but declined comment when he emerged
from Dukakis' Brookline home after spending an hour with the
governor Tuesday night. The Tennessee senator was critical of
Dukakis at times during the primary season but endorsed him last
month during a Dukakis campaign swing in the South.
   Gephardt, D-Mo., spent an hour with Dukakis earlier Tuesday at
the Statehouse. He declined to discuss specifics of their
conversation but said he would accept the vice presidential
nomination if Dukakis offered it to him.
   Before leaving town on Tuesday, Jackson said he was the most
qualified of the candidates for second billing behind Dukakis, and
called other contenders ``unknown quantities.''
   Jackson left behind top aide Ron Brown, who met with Dukakis
campaign manager Susan Estrich and Democratic National Committee
Chairman Paul Kirk to discuss convention logistics.
   Democratic officials were discussing a tentative convention
framework in which Jackson would deliver a prime time television
speech on Tuesday night, the second night of the party sessions,
sources said.
   The governor has made Attorney General Edwin Meese a frequent
target during his campaign rhetoric and was quick to respond to
word that Meese was resigning.
   ``I think the Meese resignation is long overdue,'' Dukakis told
reporters as he left his office for the day. ``I never thought he
should have been appointed in the first place.''
   Dukakis said the Meese resignation would not affect his
criticism of the ethical standards of the Reagan administration and
he said Bush had to answer for those problems.
   ``The Meese resignation itself is not going to solve this
administration's problems,'' Dukakis said. ``This administration
has had one scandal after another, one resignation after another.''
   Dukakis has tried to carefully juggle his duties as governor
with his candidacy, but a new poll suggested his run for the White
House may have affected his once-overwhelming support at home.
   The poll, conducted by KRC Research of Cambridge for The Boston
Herald and WBZ-TV, found that 55 percent of the 400 likely
Massachusetts general election voters polled gave Dukakis a
favorable rating, compared to 71 percent in January 1987 _ before
he announced his presidential candidacy. The poll, which had a
margin of error of plus or minus five percentage points, said
Dukakis' unfavorability rating has jumped from 17 percent in
January 1987 to 36 percent.
   The survey indicated voters were not happy with the way Dukakis
has handled the state's recent budget problems, but still showed
him leading Bush in Massachusetts 51 percent to 37 percent.
</TEXT>
