<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietInspectors     07-06 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspectors,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Conclude Missile Site Inspections; Prepare To Depart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials have completed
inspections at two U.S. intermediate-range nuclear rocket sites in
West Germany and are preparing to return home, U.S. military
officials said today.
   U.S. Air Force officials said the teams had returned to
Rhein-Main Air Base near Frankfurt after a full day of inspections
and planned to return to the United States on Thursday.
   Nineteen Soviet specialists split into two teams on Tuesday to
carry out their first inspections under the superpower treaty
eliminating intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   The Soviet inspectors arrived in West Germany on Monday.
   Air Force spokesman Lt. Col. Pat Maloney said the inspections
took place at Wueschheim and Schwaebisch-Gmuend.
   The Wueschheim cruise missile site is 25 miles south of Koblenz.
   The Mutlangen Pershing 2 missile site at Schwaebisch-Gmuend is
27 miles east of Stuttgart.
   American inspectors have gone to the Soviet Union to examine
intermediate-range nuclear missile sites there, while another team
of Soviet experts is checking sites in the United States.
   The checks are called ``base line'' inspections in the treaty,
which was signed in December by President Reagan and Kremlin leader
Mikhail Gorbachev. Their purpose is to make sure that items found
at the missile sites correspond to what has been listed by the
superpowers in their agreement.
   There are six bases in West Germany with a total of 220
intermediate-range nuclear missiles to be inspected by the Soviets.
   The other sites include Pershing 2 bases at Neu-Ulm and
Neckarsulm.
   In addition, a Pershing 2 storage site is located at Weilerbach,
and a missile maintenance facility is located in the Frankfurt
suburb of Hausen.
   They will be inspected later, military officials said.
</TEXT>
