<DOCNO> AP880706-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Perot-Postal     07-06 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Perot-Postal,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perot Contract Suspension Recommended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing examiner is considering recommending
that a contract between the U.S. Postal Service and Texas
billionnaire H. Ross Perot be ordered suspended. It has been
challenged by would-be competitors who did not get to bid.
   Whatever recommendation is made will go before a judge at the
General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals, with a
decision likely soon, a board official said today.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
examiner is expected to recommend that the contract be suspended.
   The hearing examiner, Catherine Hyatt, declined to comment on
the matter.
   At a hearing Tuesday Perot and officials of the Postal Service
refused to comply with requests to provide documents or have
individuals testify before the board, the GSA board official said.
   Postal officials acknowledged that they declined to cooperate
with the agency, arguing that it lacks jurisdiction over the Postal
Service.
   Suspension of the Perot contract was sought by Electronic Data
Systems Corp., Perot's former company which is now a part of
General Motors, and by Planning Research Corp. of McLean,. Va.
Those firms argued that the Postal Service should have sought
competitive bids before awarding the contract to Perot.
   The contract is in two phases. The first is a $500,000 agreement
calling for Perot to analyze postal operations and recommend ways
to save money. It was announced June 2 and immediately drew
criticism from a variety of sources.
   After the first 90-day phase, there was to be a second part, in
which Perot would be paid a percentage of any savings the service
realized from implementing his recommendations.
   The Senate, meanwhile, has requested the General Accounting
Office to invesitigate terms of the deal, and directed the Postal
Service to delay phase two of the contract while that analysis is
underway.
   The Senate vote called on the GAO to look into the contract and
report to the Senate within 45 days. It also called on the Postal
Service to delay implementation of any second phase of the contract
for 45 days to give the Senate time to study the GAO report.
   Thus, if the study suggests changes in postal operations,
implementation could be delayed by at least a month by the Senate
action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
