<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MinorityStudents     07-06 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minority Students,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neurosurgeon Tells Minority Students To Be the Best</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A 36-year-old neurosurgeon who was born and grew
up in Detroit's inner city told a group of minority high school
students attending an Ivy League summer seminar to focus on
in-depth, not superficial, learning.
   ``You young people are particularly the ones who can make a
difference in American society,'' Dr. Benjamin Solomon Carson said
Tuesday. ``You are the ones who can erase some of the
misconceptions _ not just by getting in the door, but by being the
best at what you do.''
   Carson, chief of pediatric neurosurgery at Johns Hopkins
University and Hospital in Baltimore, led a 70-member medical team
in 1987 that separated 7-month-old West German twins, who were
joined at the head. The operation, over the Labor Day weekend, took
22 hours.
   The struggle for civil rights, Carson said, is now in ``phase
two.''
   ``Those blessed with intellectual gifts must use them,'' he
said. ``Set your sights on a goal and pursue it relentlessly.''
   He was the keynote speaker Tuesday night at the opening banquet
for the Leadership, Education and Development Program, at the
Wharton School at the University of Pennsylvania.
   LEAD is designed to introduce minority high school juniors to
business concepts during four-week summer sessions on several
college campuses. Thirty students from across the nation are
participating in the program at Penn.
   Carson was born and grew up in Detroit's inner city. His mother,
who married at 13, had only a third-grade education. His father
left the family when Carson was 8 years old; his mother reared two
sons alone.
   Carson said he moved from the bottom of his class in elementary
school to earning the highest academic average at his predominantly
white junior high school.
   However, even after he realized he was gifted intellectually,
his temper and peer pressure almost diverted him from his goal, he
said.
   ``I was the kind of person who got mad if you even looked at me
the wrong way,'' he said. ``When I was 14, I stabbed a boy. He was
wearing a belt with a really big buckle. The knife glanced off of
it. If it wasn't for that buckle, I wouldn't be here tonight.''
   Carson said the episode was a major turning point in his life.
   Another factor that determined his success was his mother's
insistence that he and his brother read, he said.
   ``My mother allowed us to watch only two or three hours of
television per week,'' he said. ``She required us to read at least
two books each week and submit book reviews _ to her. It wasn't
until later that we learned she couldn't read them.''
   Carson graduated from Yale in 1973, received his medical degree
from the University of Michigan in 1977 and became chief of
pediatric neurosurgery at Johns Hopkins in 1985.
   Corporate sponsors of LEAD include McNeil Consumer Products,
Scott Paper Co., and UNISYS. The program was founded at the
University of Pennsylvania in 1980.
</TEXT>
