<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0438 07-06 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decision by Longtime Friend Meese Caught Reagan Off Stride</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Meese Rdp</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 9 grafs new to UPDATE with White House statements on
search for Meese's successor, quotes on Reagan and Meese. Picks up
2nd graf pvs, The president.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman said today the
White House has begun the process of selecting someone to succeed
Attorney General Edwin Meese III at the Justice Department.
   Meese, meanwhile, arrived for a ``personal chat'' with Reagan,
and spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said that the attorney general had
resigned voluntarily.
   Asked whether Meese could have remained if he had wished,
Fitzwater replied, ``Absolutely. The president has expressed full
confidence in Ed Meese at all times.''
   Describing the attorney general's call to Reagan notifying the
president that he was stepping down, the spokesman said, ``The
president said, `OK, if that's your determination'.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan did not try to dissuade his longtime
friend, respecting Meese's wish to step aside.
   Fitzwater, holding his daily White House news briefing, said
Reagan this morning ``briefly discussed'' the search for a
successor with chief of staff Kenneth Duberstein and White House
counsel A.B. Culvahouse.
   ``We are beginning the search immediately,'' the spokesman said.
Officials are looking for someone with ``courage, strength and
integrity,'' he said.
   If a new attorney general has not been confirmed by the time
Meese leaves in late July or early August, Fitzwater said, the
administration probably would install Solicitor General Charles
Fried in the job on an acting basis. Fried is outranked by two
Justice Department newcomers, Deputy Attorney General Harold
Christensen and Associate Attorney General Francis Keating, neither
of whom has been confirmed.
   Even though Meese told Reagan ``some time ago'' that he wanted
to leave office before the end of the administration, his
resignation announcement apparently caught the White House off
guard.
   The president even admitted Tuesday, shortly after Meese made
his plans clear, that he had ``nobody in mind'' to take his
longtime friend's place at the helm of the Justice Department.
   Another indication that the White House was surprised by Meese's
announcement came late Tuesday, when it took officials 3{ hours to
prepare a three-paragraph formal statement from the president about
Meese's decision.
   Normally, when the White House is informed in advance of such a
step, the formal statements are released within short order of the
announcement.
   Some details provided by White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
about how Meese informed Reagan indicate that the president, as
well as the senior White House staff, were somewhat taken aback by
the timing of the announcement.
   Fitzwater said Reagan took Meese's call at about 4 p.m., just as
Reagan was leaving the White House for a helicopter ride to Walter
Reed Army Medical Center to visit hospitalized Salvadoran President
Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   The spokesman said Reagan spoke with Meese ``for a minute or
two'' in the White House physician's office, which is just steps
from the exit to the helicopter pad.
   ``The attorney general said he had determined that he would like
to resign and return to private life, adding that he would like to
make the announcement very soon,'' Fitzwater said.
   The spokesman quoted Reagan as telling Meese he would accept the
resignation ``if that's your determination.''
   Fitzwater added that Reagan ``later said the attorney general
had told him some time ago that he might want to leave before the
end of the administration'' and that ``the president left the
timing up to him.''
   The spokesman did not indicate when Meese first told Reagan he
might want to leave.
   Upon his return to the White House, Reagan defended his longtime
California friend as ``a darn good attorney general'' and did not
mention the controversies that have swirled about his years in
office.
   In his statement, Reagan said Meese can ``look back with
satisfaction on the contribution'' he'd made to the Department of
Justice.
   ``For more than two decades now, Ed has been a good friend and a
close adviser; his gift for developing and succinctly summarizing
policy options is one of the most unique I have encountered in my
experience in government,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan's chief of staff, Kenneth Duberstein, was besieged by
reporters, questioning him about the resignation.
   Asked if Reagan tried to talk Meese out of it, the chief of
staff said, ``It was his determination. Ed, when he called, was
determined.''
</TEXT>
