<2ND_LINE>PM-Anti-Abortion Rally, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0553,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Demonstrators Arrested Outside Philadelphia Clinic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with arrests beginning, fetus
displayed, other details, picking up 7th graf pvs, `Clinic
administrator ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today arrested scores of
anti-abortion demonstrators who blocked the doors of a women's
clinic in a protest at which they weepingly displayed a 19-week-old
fetus.
   About 400 abortion opponents gathered at the Northeast Women's
Center, the day after a previous demonstration at a clinic in Paoli
resulted in 591 arrests.
   The protesters blocked doors to the women's center in defiance
of a federal court order, and arrests began after the order was
read to them and they refused to disperse. They submitted
peacefully to officers and were carried away in sheriff's
department buses 32 at a time.
   The demonstrators were to be charged with defiant trespass, a
charge that carries a maximum penalty of a $300 fine and 90 days in
jail, police said.
   ``We're going to prevent them from doing any abortions,'' said
Juli Loesch, a spokeswoman for Operation Rescue, a coalition based
in Binghamton, N.Y., that organized the protest. ``We think that
saving one life makes thousands and thousands of sacrifices
worthwhile.''
   Seven patients were already inside the clinic before the
demonstrators began arriving, said Frances Sheehan, a pro-choice
activist.
   Randall A. Terry, national director of Operation Rescue,
displayed the fetus in a box, draped with cloth.
   ``It is an aborted baby,'' said Lowell Patterson, an Operation
Rescue spokesman. ``We are challenging the media to show it. ... We
believe if we could get that in print, the attitudes toward
abortion would change. We believe the pictures are what upset
people so much.''
   Patterson said he did not know the source of the fetus or
whether it had been purchased.
   The demonstrators, gathering here for three days, blockaded the
Women's Suburban Clinic on Tuesday in violation of two court
orders. Demonstrators who refused to leave surrendered quietly to
deputies who carried them away on stretchers.
   Ms. Loesch declared the demonstration ``mission accomplished''
Tuesday evening.
   ``When the government has to choose between jailing tens of
thousands of good, decent citizens or making child killing illegal,
they'll make child killing illegal,'' said Terry.
   Clinic administrator Shelley Miller said the protest would not
stop abortions.
   ``We know abortions will always exist,'' she said. ``I don't
think this protest will change that.''
   The Philadelphia-based Women's Law Project returned to federal
court Tuesday to request fines of up to $25,000 for the violation
of an order barring protesters from blocking clinic entrances, said
attorney Susan Cary Nicholas.
   U.S. District Judge Clarence C. Newcomer, who issued the order
Thursday, denied the request pending further motions, but left his
order unchanged, Ms. Nicholas said.
   Newcomer's order and a Chester County order were read to
protesters before arrests began. Deputies transported the
protesters by bus to nearby Conestoga Senior High School, where
they were videotaped and charged with defiant trespassing.
   The charge carries a maximum penalty of a $300 fine and 90 days
in jail, said Chester County District Attorney James P. MacElree
II. Plans to press more serious misdemeanor charges were dropped in
return for an agreement by protesters not to return to the clinic
after their arrests, Baynard said.
   Protesters had gathered from about 20 states, and all were
prepared to go to jail, Terry said.
   Banners hanging from the clinic roof read, ``Fund Abortions for
Women in Need'' and ``Pledge-a-Picket,'' references to attempts by
pro-abortion groups to turn the demonstration into a fund-raising
vehicle for their cause.
   The pledge drive was started to put a damper on the protesters'
enthusiasm, since pro-choice supporters were asked to pledge money
based on the number of demonstrators, said Frances Sheehan,
executive director of the Clara Bell Duvall Education Fund.
   The money will go to the Greater Philadelphia Women's Medical
Fund, which pays abortion costs for low-income women, she said.
   The total amount pledged per head as of Tuesday was $3.50, with
a nickel per person as the average pledge, she said.
</TEXT>
