<DOCNO> AP880706-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan     07-06 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lee Urges Open Debate at Party Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui on Wednesday
welcomed delegates to a congress of the ruling Nationalist Party
with a call for open debate in this nation emerging from its
authoritarian past.
   The 13th congress of the Nationalist Party, or Kuomintang, opens
Thursday at a suburban Taipei stadium and then moves to a hillside
convention hall to chart the party's future after six decades of
leadership from the Chiang Kai-shek dynasty.
   Lee, acting chairman of the 2.4-million-member party, is
expected to be elected chairman Friday by the congress' 1,209
delegates. He has vowed to continue the political and social
liberalization begun by Chiang Ching-kuo, the son of Chiang
Kai-shek, who led the island until his death in January.
   His success could depend on the new party and government lineup,
which will determine how fast the Kuomintang moves forward with
political, economic and social change.
   The congress will elect a 180-member party Central Committee
that will name a policy-making Central Standing Committee. A
Cabinet overhaul is likely after the meeting.
   Old-guard conservatives who fled to Taiwan in 1949 with Chiang
Kai-shek after losing a civil war to the Communists on the Chinese
mainland dominate both party committees. Many are expected to step
down to make way for a new generation of leaders more sensitive to
public opinion in Taiwan.
   Lee, 65, said he hoped the delegates would be ``expressing and
stating in full during the meeting whatever opinion they may have.
Only in this way can they convey fully the wishes of the public
(and) set a truly democratic example for our party.''
   Since its founding on mainland China in 1894 by Sun Yat-sen, the
father of modern China, power in the Kuomintang has flowed from the
top down while the party exercised authoritarian rule.
   But Chiang Ching-kuo in the years before his death lifted
38-year-old martial law, allowed the formation of opposition
parties and sought to increase the power of native Taiwanese, who
constitute about 85 percent of the island's nearly 20 million
people.
   This is the first party congress in which delegates were not
handpicked by top officials and in which a Central Committee
election was not restricted to candidates proposed by the party
leader.
   Lu Kuo-ming, 36 and an electronics engineer from San Jose,
Calif., was among the 180 delegates from overseas. He acknowledged
the congress would be ``a turning point,'' but said it wasn't
likely all party elders would retire.
   The congress will take up party policy toward Communist China.
   Both the Nationalists and Communists claim to be the legitimate
government of both the Chinese mainland and Taiwan. The
Nationalists reject all official contacts with Beijing and have no
plans to drop their stated goal of national reunification.
   Last year, Chiang Ching-kuo ended a 38-year-old ban on travel to
mainland China to allow family reunions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandela     07-06 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pop Concert Planned to Mark Jailed Leader's Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid activists
Wednesday announced plans for an open-air concert near Soweto to
celebrate Nelson Mandela's 70th birthday.
   The ``Concert for Peace,'' to feature some of South Africa's top
black musicians, is scheduled to run for nine hours on July 17, the
day before the jailed black leader's birthday.
   One of the scheduled performers is guitarist-singer Ray Phiri,
who performed with Paul Simon on the hit album ``Graceland.''
   Mandela was a leader of the African National Congress before his
arrest in 1962. The outlawed ANC has been waging a guerrilla
campaign to topple the white-dominated government in Pretoria.
   Organizers expressed hope that the government, which prohibits
unauthorized outdoor political meetings and has restricted groups
sympathetic to the ANC, would allow the concert to take place.
   ``If you put your foot in it, you'll be in trouble,'' said
Aubrey Mokoena, head of the organizing committee, addressing
himself to any officials who might consider halting the event.
   Plans for the concert were announced at a news conference
attended by Mandela's wife, Winnie, and youngest daughter, Zindzi.
The government has given them permission for a six-hour birthday
reunion with Mandela at Cape Town's Pollsmoor Prison, the longest
such meeting allowed since Mandela has been in jail.
   Asked how she felt about the impending reunion, Zindzi replied:
``I'd like to see my father under normal circumstances, at home.
   ``I wouldn't like to pat the government on the back,'' she
added. ``International pressure forced them to take a lenient
step.''
   Mandela's approaching birthday has intensified the international
campaign for his release. Last month, more than 70,000 people
gathered in London for a concert honoring Mandela that was
broadcast to about 60 countries.
   Mandela is widely considered the most popular leader among South
Africa's disenfranchised black majority.
   While serving a five-year sentence for incitement and leaving
the country illegally, he was charged with sabotage and conspiracy
to topple the government. He and seven colleagues were sentenced in
1964 to life imprisonment.
   Relatives of several of Mandela's co-defendants attended the
news conference and greeted the gathering with clenched-fist
salutes.
   Mokoena said organizers felt it was important to honor Mandela
despite state-of-emergency restrictions on many groups and
individuals espousing the ANC's goals of a one-man, one-vote system
and abolition of the apartheid laws which create a racially
segregated society.
   ``Even if we are operating in diminishing legal space, we feel
as a people we've got to come out and honor this great man,''
Mokoena said.
   Organizers said 14 well-known entertainers would perform free of
charge, along with amateur black performers. They said 25,000 to
30,000 people were expected to attend, and proceeds from the $2.50
tickets would go to charity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
