<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Proxmire-Moody     07-06 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Proxmire-Moody,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Withdraws From Senate Race for Proxmire Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Jim Moody withdrew today from the
Democratic primary for the Senate seat being vacated by William
Proxmire, saying he couldn't raise enough money to compete with
millionaire opponent Herbert Kohl.
   Moody said he would run in the Sept. 13 primary in an attempt to
gain re-election to the House seat he has held since 1982.
   The 52-year-old congressman said he had considered withdrawing
from the Senate race after a newspaper poll published Sunday showed
Kohl, owner of the Milwaukee Bucks basketball team, had made
substantial gains since he unexpectedly entered the race.
   ``Events of the last week made it clear I cannot succeed no
matter what I did,'' Moody said at a news conference. ``Money is
now determining this Senate race. ... I cannot compete with
millions of dollars even though every fiber of my body wants to
run.''
   Moody's withdrawal reduced the number of major Democratic
candidates to five; two Republicans have declared their candidacy
for their party's nomination.
   The general election gives state Republicans the opportunity to
fill both Senate seats. Republican Robert W. Kasten Jr. was elected
to his second term in 1986. Proxmire, who is retiring, has held his
seat for 20 years.
   Moody's decision caused some confusion in the 5th Congressional
District race; two of the other five candidates said they wouldn't
have run if Moody hadn't assured them that he had decided to give
up his seat.
   Other Democrats in the Senate primary said Moody was pressured
to quit because Kohl, who is from Milwaukee, had undermined Moody's
electoral base with an unprecedented two-month bombardment of
television commercials.
   The poll published Sunday in the Milwaukee Journal showed former
Gov. Anthony S. Earl leading the Democratic field among likely
voters with 31 percent while Kohl was in second place with 28
percent. Moody was third with 12 percent.
   Former deputy Wisconsin attorney general Edward R. Garvey also
had 12 percent while Secretary of State Douglas J. La Follette had
8 percent.
   La Follette said Kohl's television budget has disrupted
political tradition in the state.
   ``I feel badly that big money, TV hype are determining who the
candidates will be in this race,'' La Follette said.
   Kohl, 53, dismissed the notion that his wealth had forced Moody
from the race. ``To say that people of Wisconsin can be bought is
something that I've never considered. A messenger without a message
can't win.''
   Kohl, heir to a supermarket fortune and owner of the National
Basketball Association's Bucks since 1985, is a former state
Democratic chairman. He has never held elective public office.
</TEXT>
