<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--HungerStrike     07-06 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hunger Strike,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conscientious Objectors End Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two conscientious objectors have ended
their hunger strike after the government pledged to change the law
on non-combatant military service, their support committee said
Wednesday.
   The government announced on July 1 that alternative civilian
service had been provided for in a law to be proposed to parliament
this week.
   Mihalis Marangakis, 31, and Thanassis Makris, 23, both jailed
Greek Orthodox pacifists, were ``in bad shape'' after the fasting,
the committee said.
   Makris, a student, has been hospitalized, according to Mary
Kostidou, the committee secretary. She did not know how much weight
he had lost.
   He began fasting May 8 after a military court sentenced him to
five years in prison for resisting military service.
   Marangakis, 31, a woodcarver, started his fast May 30 to protest
Makris' sentence. Marangakis is serving a 26-month prison term for
refusing to be drafted.
   The new bill includes a provision under which the time
conscientious objectors have served in jail will be counted as
social service.
</TEXT>
