<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Teachers-FuneralMarch     07-06 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teachers-Funeral March,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers Stage Mock Funeral to Symbolize Louisiana School Neglect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Led by a jazz band, 400 teachers from 50
states staged a mock funeral procession through the streets of New
Orleans today to symbolize Louisiana's ``historic neglect of
education.''
   The four-block long procession featured teachers singing ``When
the schools are fully funded,'' to the tune of ``When the Saints Go
Marching In.''
   Following a 1.75-mile march from Jackson Square to the
Superdome, where the National Education Association is holding its
annual convention, the marchers planned to form a 50-car motorcade
to take their case for more education dollars to the state
Legislature in Baton Rouge.
   The march coincided with a showdown debate in the state Senate
on ways to finance the state budget, which includes a 5 percent
teacher pay raise. Gov. Buddy Roemer's plan to extend a 2-cent
sales tax to food, drugs, gasoline and utilities has run into stiff
opposition, raising the prospect of more budget cuts instead of pay
raises.
   At the head of the procession, just behind a hearse and the
10-member Young Tuxedo Marching Band, was NEA vice president Keith
Geiger, and Virginia Budd, president of the Louisiana Association
of Educators, the local NEA affiliate. She wore a black veil, as if
she were a grieving widow.
   ``Jazz funerals celebrate life,'' said Budd. ``This funeral
celebrates the efforts of LAE members to bring new life to our
state's educational system.''
   ``NEA members are showing support for Louisiana, to put in the
past the neglect of this state's educational system and move
forward,'' said Geiger.
   They carried a blue and white sign: ``Let's Bury Educational
Neglect.''
   One of the marchers, Sylvia Carter who teaches at Hearndon
Magnet School in Shreveport, said she had been teaching for 20
years and earns only $22,000 annually.
   Olive Hansen, a homebound teacher in Calcasieu Parish, said she
has a master's degree and 21 years' experience, yet is paid $24,000.
   ``We're ready to move forward,'' Hansen said.
   According to NEA figures, Louisiana ranks 43rd in the percentage
of total expenditures invested in education. Its 37 percent dropout
rate is the nation's worst. And it ranks 48th in average teacher
salaries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
