<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   07-06 1083</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,1125</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: next time.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 5
   Los Angeles Times on the shooting down of the Iran airliner:
   First came shock at the news that a U.S. warship in the Persian
Gulf had shot down an Iranian airliner, with the apparent loss of
all 290 people aboard. Then came bewilderment over how such an
appalling mistake could be made. The guided-missile cruiser
Vincennes has been advertised as the latest in high-tech surface
vessels, a $1 billion dollar weapons platform that supposedly can
identify hundreds of targets at once and simultaneously engage in
anti-air, anti-submarine and anti-ship warfare.
   ...Radar, we are told, cannot distinguish between a plane the
size of an F-14 and a plane, like the Airbus, that is nearly three
times as large; both show up as identical blips on the radar
screen... Italy says that one of it naval ships in the area
confirmed through its own radar scans the U.S. account that the
Airbus was flying at least four miles outside the corridor reserved
for commercial traffic. The Italian ship also heard radio warnings
from the Vincennes to the airliner. The unanswered question is
whether the airliner heard them.
   ...Many questions about this terrible event remain to be
answered... The biggest and most overdue is what has been the point
and what if anything has been gained by the Reagan administration's
increasingly one-sided intervention in the Persian Gulf war, which
has seen it militarily confronting Iran even as it ignores Iraq's
attacks of third-country ships and its indiscriminate use of poison
gas on land... Against this background Iran is now able to allege
that the shooting down of its airliner was deliberate, and to know
that many in the world will believe the claim.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 5
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune editorial on the Iran-Iraq war:
   The downing of an Iranian civilian airliner with 290 persons
aboard by an American warship in the Persian Gulf Sunday was a
dreadful tragedy that underscores the need to end the senseless
Iran-Iraq war.
   President Reagan was right to express promptly his deep regret
over the shooting down of the Iran Air jetliner by commanders of
the cruiser Vincennes, who believed it was an Iranian F-14 warplane
about to attack their ship.
   The United States should offer compensation to the Tehran regime
and to the families of the victims aboard the ill-fated Airbus.
   The deplorable error should convince the religious fanatics
ruling Iran that it is time to settle the eight-year bloodletting
with Iraq. Continuing the war will merely add thousands of young
corpses to the hundreds of thousands who have died uselessly before
them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 4
   Milwaukee Sentinel on the court martial in the Navy drowning
case:
   The decision to recommend a general court-martial for one of the
men allegedly involved in the death of Appleton, Wis., Airman
Recruit Lee W. Mirecki is an appropriate and necessary action to
establish a clear record on his ghastly demise.
   Five others charged in the drowning have been offered the option
``non-judicial'' punishment. But that hardly offsets the crimes of
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy to commit battery that
allegedly occurred.
   Information given by others in the rescue swimming class in
which Mirecki was participating when he died suggest this was not a
mere case of overzealousness on the part of the instructors.
   Petty Officer Michael W. Combe, who has been recommended for
court-martial, was said to have held the recruit's head under water
after Mirecki panicked and asked to quit the course.
   Other recruits were ordered to turn their backs and sing the
national anthem during the incident.
   The full truth must be known.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 4
   The Honolulu Advertiser on the shooting down of the Iranian
airliner:
   The shooting down of an Iranian commercial jetliner by a U.S.
Navy warship in the Persian Gulf is a tragic mistake that darkens
more than just America's Independence Day weekend.
   Most Americans will set their reaction by President Reagan's
statement calling the incident ``a terrible human tragedy,'' but
that it resulted from ``proper defensive action'' by a warship that
believed it was facing an attacking Iranian fighter during a
running sea battle.
   Still, the president was also putting the best possible face on
a bad situation where the United States will pay a price of
uncertain kind and dimensions.
   Besides the formal apology, there must be compensation for
families of the 290 people killed aboard the Iran Air jetliner.
That is a decent minimum.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 3
   Spartanburg (S.C.) Herald-Journal on Angola:
   Angola's offer to negotiate withdrawal of Cuban troops from its
territory is a significant change of stance that could signal
increased stability in the whole of strife-torn southern Africa.
   For the first time, the Marxist-oriented Angolan government's
offer to repatriate its Cuban mercenaries is not linked to a demand
that the United States halt its support for the anti-government
guerrillas led by Jonas Savimbi.
   ... Angola's new offer confirms that the Soviet Union, which has
provided funds and arms for the Cubans, is weary of the 13-year-old
civil war and is anxious to withdraw as soon as possible.
   Pragmatically, Angolan officials are still demanding three
concessions from South Africa: that South African troops be
withdrawn from Angola, that South Africa stop giving aid to Savimbi
and that South-West Africa (Namibia) be granted independence.
   (South Africa's) minister of foreign affairs, Pik Botha,
startled political observers by declaring that South Africa was
ready to grant independence to South-West Africa if Cuban troops
were removed from Angola.
   ... With the scenario for southern Africa looking more hopeful
than it has for years, the United States must continue to press for
national reconciliation in Angola as the first step toward
stabilization of the whole region.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 3
   The Ponca City (Okla.) News on arms reduction:
   Once again as party platforms are being discussed, there are
those advocating all kinds of unilateral disarmament on the part of
the United States.
   The theory expressed is that if the United States leads the way
by reducing its weapons, Russia and the other countries will follow
suit.
   That's a beautiful thought, but there is no evidence in ...
history to suggest that it would work that way.
   Unilateral disarmament should not be a part of any party's
platform, lest it should suggest a weakness to those who seek power
over us. Costly as it is, we must continue to maintain defenses
that can stand up if called on against any offense the world has to
offer.
</TEXT>
