<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hemingway'sCaptain Bjt   07-06 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hemingway's Captain, Bjt,0871</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Recalls Life as Captain of Hemingway Yacht</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COJIMAR, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The old man looked out at the sea and began
the story of how he came to be skipper of Ernest Hemingway's yacht
for more than 20 years.
   ``There was a storm and I heard someone yelling for help,''
Gregorio Fuentes said. ``It was 1928 on Dry Tortugas. It was
Hemingway, and he and his companions were out of food.''
   Gregorio Fuentes, who is 90 now, pointed a wrinkled finger at a
picture of the famous writer on the wall, and glanced at it from
time to time as he told his tale.
   The old sailor sat on a shabby, flowered overstuffed chair in
the living room of his cottage in this pastel-washed fishing
village. His wife of 67 years, Dolores, was in the kitchen nearby.
   He said he gave the novelist two bottles of rum and arranged for
the yacht to be towed back to Key West, then ``We waved goodbye and
he said he we'd see each other in Cuba.''
   Fuentes went to work on merchant ships in Europe after that, and
when he returned home a decade later was told an American had been
looking for him.
   It was Hemingway, with the offer to be captain of the Pilar.
Fuentes held the job until the author's suicide in 1961.
   When that happened, Fuentes was on a warship for the Cuban
government. Fidel Castro had gained control of the island 90 miles
from Florida in 1959, and Cubans were on alert for an American
invasion.
   ``I read in the newspaper that he died,'' Fuentes said, reaching
for a large Cuban cigar. ``He was a friend. I understood. He had a
disease. ... He couldn't live with that. It's better what he did.''
   His former association with the famous writer has made Fuentes a
minor celebrity in Cuba, where Hemingway's home in San Francisco de
Paulo is a museum. Hemingway's favorite hangouts in Havana, La
Floridita and Bodeguita del Medio, are popular tourist attractions.
   A new harbor for visiting yachts has been named ``Hemingway
Marina.'' A hotel near the docks is called ``El Viejo y el Mar,''
Spanish for ``The Old Man and the Sea.''
   ``Everyone adored him,'' Fuentes said. Asked about Hemingway's
reputation for womanizing, he laughed and said: ``A man who doesn't
love women is not a man.
   Fuentes remembers the day, but not the date, the writer began
work on the ``The Old Man and the Sea,'' which was published in
1952 and made into a movie in 1957.
   ``We were sailing and he was reading,'' Fuentes said. ``He would
read and then look at me. Then he said, `Did you see a boat?'
   ``It was a small skiff and he told me to see if it needed help.
There was an old man pulling in a marlin, and a young boy. The man
yelled for us to get away but the boy was nice. Hemingway told me
to give them supplies _ milk, pineapples, oranges and crackers.''
   He said the novelist knew it would take time to reel in the
fighting marlin and offering help was typical of Hemingway, whom he
described as generous and courageous, with a fine sense of humor.
   The writer's portrait of Santiago, the main character in ``The
Old Man and the Sea,'' could be that of Fuentes today.
   ``The old man was thin and gaunt with deep wrinkles in the back
of his neck,'' Heningway wrote. ``The brown blotches of the
benevolent skin cancer the sun brings from its reflection on the
tropic sea were on his cheeks. Everything about him was old except
his eyes and they were the same color as the sea and were cheerful
and undefeated.''
   Fuentes brushed back a strand of white hair and said Hemingway
went to work on the book immediately, writing on the yacht for 28
days and nights.
   Then the constant clatter of the typewriter stopped because, the
author said, he had to return to shore to pay the people who worked
for him.
   ``He always thought of other people,'' Fuentes said.
   Cojimar was the setting of the movie, which starred Spencer
Tracy.
   Fuentes has spent nearly 70 years in the fishing village beside
the ruins of Spanish colonial fort. About 70,000 people live here
now, but he recalls when there were only 200 families.
   A bust of Hemingway is in a gazebo by the ocean, cast from the
bronze fittings of fishing boats and donated by local fishermen.
Youngsters hurl out lines from the wharf nearby.
   Hemingway's former captain was born in the Canaries, the Spanish
islands off the hump of Africa, and left home at age 11 on a ship
that eventually reached Cuba.
   ``It was my dream to see the world,'' he said, and he did.
   He still enjoys a cigar and a glass of rum, and tells a visitor
of the lesson life has taught him: ``We live in the same world. We
can all get along.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
