<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush     07-06 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 2:15 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 13 grafs new with Bush speech text, EMBARGOED for release
at 2:15 p.m. EDT; pick up 2nd graf pvs bgng ``Bush spoke...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush promised today to name
a Hispanic to his Cabinet if elected president, saying ``It's time.
It's long overdue.''
   The certain Republican nominee said he wanted to make a pledge,
``a pledge that I have never made before, to anyone, to any group.''
   He noted that women, blacks and other minorities have been named
to Cabinet positions.
   ``If I become president, my Cabinet will be composed of the very
best men and women _ at least one of whom, finally, will be a
Hispanic American.
   ``It's time. It's time. It's long overdue,'' Bush said in a
speech prepared for delivery to the League of United Latin American
Citizens.
   Bush was greeted on his arrival at the airport by a marachi band
and the leadership of LULAC, an umbrella organization of Hispanic
groups.
   Bush jokingly said ``they do have a terrible mistake _ they have
a few Democrats that are members of LULAC.''
   In his speech, Bush made clear that he wants to recruit
Hispanics away from the Democratic Party.
   ``I truly feel that a lot of you in this audience ought to
consider joining the party I represent this year,'' Bush said. ``I
think you belong with us. And don't let anyone take you, or your
support, for granted.''
   Trying to draw a contrast, Bush said, ``It's fair to say that
the other party has a tendency to take those actions that slow or
stop growth. They tend to increase taxes, while my party tends to
resist.
   ``They tend to increase regulation, while my party tilts toward
greater regulatory freedom.
   ``The other party has a recent tendency to pursue foreign policy
goals in a manner that encourages the more troubling impulses of
our adversaries,'' the vice president said. ``My party has a
tendency to deal with communism and other destabilizing forces in a
manner that combines sophistication with strength.''
   Earlier today, Bush said he would not apologize to Iran for the
shooting down of a civilian airliner and he said it was too early
to decide whether the United States should pay compensation to the
victims' families.
   Bush spoke with reporters as his plane, Air Force Two, taxied
for takeoff from Andrews Air Force Base on a campaign trip to
Dallas. Asked if the United States should apologize, he said, ``No,
but we probably ought to do what we did, which is to officially
express regret, which I guess should happen when you have the loss
of innocent life.''
   But as for an apology, Bush said, ``I wouldn't. Because of the
facts, what happened.''
   President Reagan sent a diplomatic message Sunday to Iran's
leaders expressing ``deep regret'' for the military action that
brought down a civilian plane, killing all aboard. Reagan was asked
Tuesday if he ha apologized sufficiently to Iran and he responded,
``Yes.''
   Bush said it was ``too early to consider'' reparations to the
victims' families. ``Wait til we know all the facts,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
