<DOCNO> AP880706-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   07-06 1134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,1175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: whole region.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   July 2
   Dallas Morning News on White House cocaine use:
   The news ... that several White House staffers had been
disciplined for cocaine use brought some jibes that first lady
Nancy Reagan needs to implement the ``just say no'' program in her
own backyard.
   But the continuing Washington investigation demonstrated how
pervasive the drug abuse problem is in this country. Three members
of the Secret Service's uniformed division at the White House were
placed on administrative leave, and two National Security Council
employees were fired in the drug investigation.
   Evidence continues to mount that no segment of the population is
exempt from the substance abuse problem. A federal call for drug
testing of interstate truck drivers in June was accompanied by some
hair-raising information about research in several states: One test
in Tennessee showed that 15 percent of the drivers tested positive
for marijuana, cocaine or prescription stimulants; 36 percent of
1,300 truckers surveyed in Florida said they sometimes drove under
the influence of drugs.
   The sobering thought is how much worse it might be if the drugs
in question were legalized.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 1
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on using blimps to hunt drug smugglers:
   Air Force surveillance planes designed to find and track
high-speed military aircraft have not been of much use against the
slow-moving, low-altitude planes used by drug traffickers. Better
performance can reasonably be expected from a balloon newly
tethered near the Mexican border in southern Arizona.
   The blimp's radar range is about 160 miles, permitting detection
of aircraft in an 80,000 square-mile area.
   The goal of Customs officials is to deploy six such balloons
along the Southwest border. Even when they are all fully
operational, that will be no guarantee against low-flying smuggler
aircraft ... This new approach does promise, however, to make
things considerably more difficult for the traffickers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 1
   The Jersey Journal of Jersey City, N.J., on increased federal
funding for drug treatment:
   One of the latest to call for expanded drug abuse treatment is
the board of directors of the American Medical Association... .
   The board also urged a change in the rules to make it easier for
drug users to get on methadone programs. Increased funding would be
needed to make a change in the rules effective.
   While a prosperous state like New Jersey, which suffers
especially hard from AIDS among drug users, must not shirk its
share of the additional burden, it's important to see expanded
federal funding for treatment as well. There are some congressional
proposals for such an expansion and they deserve very high priority.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 1
   Journal-American, Bellevue, Wash., on special prosecutors:
   The Supreme Court's decision upholding the law on independent
prosecutors has been characterized as a defeat for the Reagan
administration, which it is, but it will surely have a more
important effect in the long run.
   In a 7-1 decision, the court held that a 1978 law providing for
appointment by judges of special prosecutors to investigate
suspected crimes does not violate the Constitution's provision for
separation of the executive and legislative branches of government.
That law was enacted in the wake of the Watergate scandal, to
prevent any future president from copying President Nixon, who
tried to halt the breakdown of his administration by ordering the
special prosecutor's dismissal. ...
   The ruling vindicates the Ethics in Government Act _ both in
purpose and legality _ and leaves the nation with assurance that
justice at the highest levels of government need not be tainted by
politics.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 1
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer on the Environmental Protection
Agency:
   A group of Republican senators is sponsoring a bill to elevate
the Environmental Protection Agency to a Cabinet-level department.
   The threat to the biosphere is such, regrettably, that it's an
idea whose time has come.
   The president must have more direct involvement in environmental
issues than has been the case, argues Sen. David Durenberger,
R-Minn., a prime sponsor of the bill. Cabinet officers help set
broad policies for the nation. As is, the agency does not have a
close, direct relationship with the president nor does the head of
the agency have the access to the president that a Cabinet member
would have.
   But with such threats looming as severe damage to the planet
caused by burning fossil fuels, environmental concerns must be made
a top governmental and presidential priority. Damage from the
greenhouse effect will touch on nearly every aspect of human life.
That makes it imperative that those responsible for overseeing the
nation's environmental affairs be part of the Cabinet's policy
discussions on energy, agriculture, transportation, commerce, and
health and human services, to name some key Cabinet departments
that will have to cope with the creeping crisis.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 30
   The Dallas Times Herald on Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the party
congress:
   Communist orthodoxy has been taken to the woodshed. In a
remarkable speech before a special party conclave in Moscow,
Mikhail Gorbachev said many of the Marxist concepts of the past,
such as a strong central government and tightly controlled
production of consumer goods, must be trashed.
   The Soviet leader called for a new system that draws on Western
models. He wants a ``president'' to head the Soviet government _
one that is more answerable to the public and less to the Communist
Party (whose membership includes only 20 million of the country's
270 million people).
   He advocates a ``Congress of USSR People's Deputies'' that is
reflective of people's concerns. And he envisions local governments
that have powers to tax businesses to provide services. ...
   Blasting past Soviet regimes, he declared, ``The tendency to
encompass every nook of life with detailed centralized planning and
control literally strait-jacketed society.'' ...
   Like Humpty-Dumpty, Mr. Gorbachev may yet take a great fall.
Many Soviet ``conservatives'' are totally opposed to his reforms.
But if he succeeds even partially, the world should be a more
peaceful palce. Soviet citizens who can demand and get good shoes
are less likely to be thinking about fomenting revolution elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 29
   The Houston Post on the selection of Ann Richards as Democratic
keynote speaker:
   Democratic presidential hopeful Michael Dukakis said he wanted a
female to deliver the keynote address at the national convention.
And the party preferred someone who could appeal to Southern
voters, particularly in Texas.
   State Treasurer Ann Richards certainly meets those
qualifications. But in naming her as the keynote speaker, the
Democrats are getting more than a gender and a geographic locale.
Richards is a dedicated public servant, an accomplished orator,
and, as one Democratic official accurately described her, ``a fiery
populist.'' Her speech promises to be an old-fashioned stem-winder
and calls to mind the success of the only woman who's given the
keynote address, Texas' Barbara Jordan in 1976.
</TEXT>
