<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Germans,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three West Germans Freed by Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday freed three West
German television journalists detained for two days after a tribal
chief objected to their filming a traditional burial rite, a
colleague said.
   It was unclear whether they faced any charges.
   ``They phoned to say they have been released with their car,
passports and equipment and are returning to Nairobi,'' said a
spokeswoman for ARD-German Television. The spokeswoman, based in
Nairobi, spoke on condition that she not be identified.
   Correspondent Helmut Grosses, 49, of Hamburg; cameraman Thomas
Mittelstenscheld, 39, of West Berlin; and Bernd Longree, 48, of
Bonn, a television journalist traveling with them, were detained
Monday in the western town of Kisumu on Lake Victoria for filming
without a license, the colleague said.
   Kenyan law requires licenses for filming of commercial movies,
but television journalists are usually exempted.
   The crew drove to a village near Kisumu on Sunday to film a
traditional Luo tribal funeral at the invitation of relatives. A
local chief objected and they stopped filming, the colleague said.
   Police detained them and impounded their car, equipment and
passports in Kisumu the next day while they were en route back to
Nairobi, she said. They were held under a form of house arrest at a
Kisumu hotel.
</TEXT>
