<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TurtleExcluders     07-06 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turtle Excluders,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Urge Immediate Enforcement of TEDs Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the Justice Department and an
environmental group urged a federal appeals court Wednesday to
dissolve an injunction that has let Louisiana shrimpers avoid using
Turtle Excluder Devices in their nets.
   The injunction was issued by U.S. District Judge Patrick Carr in
April, just as Louisiana was getting ready to open its waters for
the spring season. Carr forbade enforcement of the federal
regulation until courts ruled on an appeal by the state attorney
general and the Concerned Shrimpers of Louisiana.
   Turtle excluders, installed where a trawl narrows down to a
pocket, provide a trap door through which turtles are ejected.
Shrimpers contend shrimp also escape through the trap door, when
the device isn't blocked by debris that prevents anything entering
the pocket.
   ``It's in the middle of the shrimp season, and you are asking us
to lift the injunction so that literally overnight they would have
to start using Turtle Excluder Devices?'' asked Judge Jerry E.
Smith, one of three judges who heard the plea in the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   ``There is no surprise for them,'' responded attorney David
Hayes, representing the Center for Environmental Education. Hayes
said that with the on-again, off-again history of the federal
regulation, shrimpers have TEDs ready for installation.
   Although the turtle excluders protect all sea turtles, the main
concern is the disappearing Kemp Ridley.
   John Sheppard of the Louisiana attorney general's office argued
that the TEDs reduce the shrimp catch and do little to protect
endangered sea turtles.
   He said dredging and development of beachfront property kill far
more turtles than shrimp nets.
   ``There are all sorts of depredations on the turtle population.
Why discriminate against the shrimper?'' he said.
   The court gave no indication when it would rule.
</TEXT>
