<HEAD>Bomb Blast in Afghan Market; Up to Seven Reported Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Radio Kabul report,
conflicting casualty count. Picks up 4th pvs, `Soviet Foreign...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vehicle packed with explosives blew
up today in a busy market near Communist Party headquarters in the
Afghan capital, and media reports said up to seven people were
killed.
   Also today, Radio Kabul said rockets blasted a residential
section of the capital and killed seven people and injured 19.
   The state-run radio said six people died in the car bombing and
16 were injured.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass reported in a dispatch from
Kabul that seven people were killed and 26 injured by the car bomb.
Tass said the blast demolished 16 stores and burned five cars. It
provided no other information on the explosion.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, said the blast rocked
Kabul's central market as people were returning from early morning
prayers. It did not provide any additional information on the
rocket attack.
   The car bomb exploded about 250 yards from the headquarters of
the governing People's Democratic Party in Kabul.
   A Western diplomatic source in Islamabad said the blast damaged
the building, which houses government executive offices,
Afghanistan's national bank, and the ministries of education,
planning, and mines and industry.
   Tass quoted the Afghan news agency Bakhtar as saying an
anti-Marxist rebel group shelled the city of Gardez, capital of
Paktia province, killing two civilians, wounding three and
destroying 22 houses.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfilyev denied reports
by Western diplomats in Pakistan that Soviet advisers had ordered
bombing of a provincial capital to keep guerrillas out.
   The diplomats said Tuesday that the Wardak provincial capital
Maidan Shahr, 15 miles southwest of Kabul, had been bombed after
guerrillas occupied the town for 24 hours late last month.
   He said rebels tried to seize the city but were repelled by the
Afghan army.
   ``The city is under government control, and there is no
destruction in Maidan Shahr,'' he said.
   Western diplomats also said guerrillas are massing around the
city of Paghman, 20 miles from Kabul.
   ``There is a military confrontation between government troops
and rebel units but no populated locality, as of today, has been
surrendered to the rebels,'' Perfilyev said.
