<HEAD>Bullets Hit Philadelphia Commuter Train</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with passenger quote, details
on injured passengers; Revises number of passengers to 200, sted
600, in 8th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five shots were fired at a train loaded with
rush-hour commuters this morning, causing slight injuries to two
passengers, a spokesman for the regional transit agency said.
   Initial reports indicated one bullet went through a window and
another pierced the stainless steel side of the four-car
Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority train, said
SEPTA spokesman Dave Murdock. Three others bounced off the top of
the train, he said.
   ``It missed me by two inches,'' passenger Darlene Stack said of
one bullet. ``It sounded like firecrackers, but it wasn't
firecrackers, it was gunshots.''
   Clarence Savage, 61, of Dover, Del., was treated at Hahnemann
University Hospital for a scratched forehead and released. ``He was
leaning against the window when the window shattered,'' said police
Detective Gerald Whartenby.
   A second passenger apparently was hit in the arm by debris but
left the scene without seeking medical treatment, SEPTA spokesman
Jim Whitaker said.
   ``At the time of the incident, I understand they were
questioning two homeless people who lived in the area. At this
time, I understand there was no reason to believe they were
involved,'' said police Sgt. Anthony Boyle.
   The sniping occurred at 7:38 a.m. as the train approached
Suburban Station in the city's central business district, Murdock
said. There were about 200 people on the train, which had stopped
at 30th Street Station a few minutes earlier and let off half the
estimated 400 passengers, Whitaker said.
   The shots apparently were fired from overhead as the train
traveled through a culvert-type right of way, Murdock said.
</TEXT>
