<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConfidentialSource     07-06 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Confidential Source,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State's Largest Newspapers On Trial For Revealing Source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnesota's two largest newspapers are on
trial for revealing the identity of a man who leaked court
documents in 1982 about the 12-year-old shoplifting conviction of a
candidate for lieutenant governor.
   In his opening statement Tuesday, an attorney for Dan Cohen said
he would put the day-to-day decision-making at the Minneapolis Star
and Tribune and the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch on trial before
a jury.
   Cohen is ``being punished for revealing factual information
about a powerful political candidate,'' said attorney Elliot
Rothenberg. ``All he did was turn over authentic court records.''
   Attorneys for the newspapers were scheduled to make their
opening statements Wednesday in Hennepin County District Court.
   Cohen, in his breach-of-contract lawsuit, claims the newspapers
violated agreements not to identify him as the source of
information about Marlene Johnson's record for shoplifting $6 worth
of merchandise.
   Johnson was the DFL candidate for lieutenant governor on a
ticket led by Rudy Perpich. She and Perpich won the 1982 election
and have held the offices since 1983.
   On Oct. 27, 1982, reporters Lori Sturdevant of the Minneapolis
newspaper and Bill Salisbury of the St. Paul newspaper separately
accepted court documents from Cohen about the 1970 shoplifing
conviction _ which was vacated in 1971 with no sentence _ on
condition that Cohen's identity would not be revealed.
   Later that day, editors of both newspapers overruled their
reporters and decided to name Cohen as the source. Two other news
organizations _ The Associated Press and WCCO-TV _ received the
same information from Cohen but did not identify him.
   The day the stories appeared, Cohen was fired from his
$35,000-a-year job as a public relations executive with an
advertising agency, Rothenberg said.
   Editors at both papers have said Cohen's name was revealed
because the importance of keeping readers fully informed of
election developments outweighed continuing his confidentiality.
Attorneys for the papers have argued that the newspapers did not
have a viable oral contract with Cohen.
   The Minneapolis newspaper has since changed its name to the Star
Tribune.
   Rothenberg said Cohen was a good friend of
Independent-Republican gubernatorial candidate Wheelock Whitney who
had helped write position papers in his official capacity at the
advertising agency.
   The trial is expected to last two weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
