<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--AmnestyDeadline     07-06 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Amnesty Deadline,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Apply For Amnesty On Second Of Three Deadlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Applications from thousands of illegal aliens
who filed for amnesty with the help of social agencies have been
delivered to federal officials to meet the second of three amnesty
deadlines.
   Officials of the Immigration and Naturalization Service's
Western Region offices said Tuesday they expected to receive a
total of about 7,000 applications.
   The deadline applied to aliens who applied for amnesty through
charitable organizations, social service agencies and other groups
designated by the INS.
   Under a federal law that took effect in 1986, illegal aliens who
entered the country before Jan. 1, 1982, could file for temporary
citizenship and qualify for permanent residency within 2{ years.
   The first deadline was May 4. Illegal aliens working through
agencies received an extra 60 days. The third deadline of Nov. 30
applies to agricultural workers.
</TEXT>
