<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrossBurning     07-06 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cross Burning,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burning Cross On Front Yard Of Belleville Prompts Moving Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black family that moved into a
predominantly white subdivision two weeks ago is preparing for
another move after a cross was burned in its front yard.
   ``This is something out of the pages of the Old South,'' said
Willie Carter, a retired Air Force staff sergeant.
   Carter said he threw the remnants of a charred cross and its
sawhorse base into a drainage ditch before going to church Sunday
morning.
   ``I'm not a violent person, but when I saw the cross, I felt
upset... . I wanted to know who did it, so I could choke him,
although I'm not that type of person,'' Carter said Tuesday.
   Carter said his family will move as soon as their real estate
agent finds a comparable home.
   ``We just want a nice place to live,'' said Carter's wife, Elsie
Carter. ``I have small children and we just don't have time for
this.''
   Police in Belleville, about 10 miles southeast of St. Louis,
said Tuesday that officers were dispatched to the Carters' home
Monday night but would not release any more information.
   Carter said he did not call police until Monday evening, after
the family returned from spending the holiday with relatives. He
didn't call Sunday morning, he said, because the family was late to
church.
   Neighbors said the Carters seemed to be a nice family but they
had little chance to get to know them.
   ``Nothing like this has ever happened,'' said Lisa Molitor, who
said her son, Greg, 5, sometimes played with one of Carter children.
   ``I think this is terrible,'' said Aurile Johnson, another
neighbor. ``If I would have seen the cross burning, I would have
called the police. We're scared. What's next, shooting?''
</TEXT>
