<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HaitianPermits     07-06 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Haitian Permits,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Haitians Show Up For Federal Permit Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Haitians gathered at a federal
courthouse today as a judge opened a hearing on the fate of 14,000
farm laborers facing expulsion from the United States because they
lack work permits.
   Senior U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins ordered the hearing
moved to a larger courtroom to accommodate the crowd.
   A request for an injunction against the Immigration and
Naturalization Service was filed by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese
of Palm Beach, the Haitian Refugee Center and individual
farmworkers.
   The case directly affects an estimated 14,000 Haitians, Mexicans
and other foreign workers in Florida, Alabama and Georgia,
attorneys in the case said, and could apply across the country.
   At issue is the INS' refusal to accept affidavits from the
farmworkers and their employers swearing they have worked the 90
hours required to receive a special agricultural work permit under
the new immigration law.
   Without the permits, they cannot legally remain in the United
States, and many are already under expulsion orders.
   Ira Kurzban, attorney for the farmworkers, said the INS is
defying Congress' wishes by demanding documentary proof of
employment which farmworkers do not have because many had been in
the country illegally.
   ``The government has imposed an impossible burden of proof,''
said the complaint. Kurzban said the burden of proof should be on
the INS to disprove the affidavits.
   The INS has also held hearings on the permits without
translators present, Kurzban said, and is not granting required
temporary work permits during the appeal process.
   INS attorney David Bernal said the rigorous proof is necessary
to support the affidavits because ``it has been determined there
was fraud in this area.''
   Bernal told Atkins that the burden of providing a translator was
not the government's responsibility, and that most farmworkers
brought someone with them to the INS hearings in any case.
   The INS also argued that the district court had no jurisdiction
because Congress specifically said only federal appeals courts
could hear challenges to the law, but Kurzban said the suit is
challenging only INS procedures, not the law itself.
</TEXT>
