<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RajneeshProperty     07-06 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rajneesh Property,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Guard Considers Guru's Land for Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE DALLES, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oregon National Guard has inquired
into the possibility of converting the former commune of Indian
guru Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh into a training facility.
   Col. Gary Lockwood, executive officer for the state's Military
Department, said the Guard must study the 64,000-acre Rancho
Rajneesh before it is considered for any military use.
   ``Any discussion we would have is academic,'' Lockwood said
earlier this week. ``We're not in a position to be looking at the
financing and purchase.''
   But the Guard's interest in the site could change if the
property should come into public ownership, he said.
   The central Oregon ranch is for sale for $28 million.
   Meanwhile, Lawrence B. Rew, a Pendleton attorney representing
Connecticut General Life Insurance Co., said the company expects a
summary judgment in Wasco County Circuit Court on a request for
foreclosure against the ranch. The insurance company holds the
principal mortgage on the property.
   If the judgment is granted, Rew said, the foreclosure action
would proceed to a sheriff's sale. If the motion is denied, the
matter would be set for trial, he said.
   The ranch served as a commune and world headquarters for
Rajneesh and his followers for 4{ years. The commune disbanded in
1985 after criminal charges were filed against the sect's top
leaders and the guru was ordered to leave the country.
   Connecticut General is trying to recover $3.76 million through
its foreclosure lawsuit, including more than $828,000 in accrued
interest on the property.
   The company's lawsuit says no payments on the property have been
made since Aug. 1, 1986.
   The lawsuit asks that the ranch be sold as a single parcel by
the Wasco County sheriff, with the proceeds used to pay first the
foreclosure judgment, then other lienholders.
   This week, Wasco County Circuit Judge John Kelly signed an order
declaring several of the defendants in the foreclosure suit to be
in default because they had not responded to defend their interests
in the property.
</TEXT>
