<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FirefightersFired     07-06 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firefighters Fired,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Township Discharges Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWTONSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A full-time fire chief and his
25-member volunteer force have been fired by township trustees,
climaxing a dispute over working conditions and other demands.
   The Wayne Township trustees surprised spectators and
firefighters at a public meeting Tuesday night by announcing the
mass firings. In addition to Fire Chief Charles Nause, the only
full-time, paid department member, about 25 volunteer firefighters
and emergency medical technicians were discharged.
   The volunteers had walked off the job briefly more than a month
ago and expected the trustees to announce a settlement of the
dispute at the meeting.
   Patricia Pack, a spokeswoman for the firefighters who was among
those fired, said Wednesday the trustees are gambling with the
township's 5,000 residents. The firefighters, she said, plan to
challenge the firings.
   ``We will get a lawyer,'' said Ms. Pack, an emergency medical
technician. ``I'm a little shocked. It seems to me the trustees of
Wayne Township are playing Russian roulette with the lives of the
people of the township.''
   The trustees said Clermont County and surrounding towns would
provide emergency services in the meantime.
   The firefighters comprise a corporation that contracts with the
township to provide emergency services, in return for insurance and
workmen's compensation coverage. No contract had been agreed to
this year.
   The trustees, who own the firefighters' equipment and emergency
services building, forbade the firefighters to return to the
building or remove personal belongings, Ms. Pack said.
   The township is located 20 miles east of Cincinnati.
   The trustees said in a letter that the firefighters were fired
because of unreasonable demands and failure to get along with the
trustees. They gave no reason for firing Nause, Ms. Pack said.
   The firefighters had demanded a full-time paid chief, insurance
coverage for supervising emergency medical technicians and a new
emergency vehicle to replace an old, deteriorating one.
   The firefighters returned to work after Nause was restored to a
full-time chief. He had been cut to part-time status last January.
</TEXT>
