<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-06 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes Near Communist Party Headquarters,</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car loaded with explosives blew up
in a busy market near Communist Party headquarters in the Afghan
capital of Kabul on Wednesday. Reports said up to seven people were
killed and 26 injured.
   The blast damaged the party building, which houses government
executive offices, Afghanistan's national bank, and the ministries
of education, planning and mines and industry, a Western diplomatic
source said.
   Radio Kabul said six people died and 16 were injured. The blast
rocked the city's central market as people were returning from
early morning Moslem prayers, the state-run radio reported.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported from Kabul that seven
people were killed and 26 injured in the explosion. The car bombing
demolished 16 stores and burned five cars, Tass said.
   Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad, also said rockets blasted a
residential section of the capital, killing seven people and
injuring 19. No other details were given.
   The car bomb exploded about 250 yards from the Central Committee
building of the ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
site of the explosion clearly indicated it was directed at party
and government offices.
   Tass also quoted the Afghan news agency Bakhtar as saying an
anti-Marxist guerrilla group shelled the city of Gardez, capital of
Paktia province, killing two civilians, wounding three and
destroying 22 houses.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim Perfilyev denied reports
by Western diplomats in Pakistan that Soviet advisers had ordered
bombing of a provincial capital to keep guerrillas out.
   The diplomats said Tuesday the Wardak provincial capital Maidan
Shahr, 15 miles southwest of Kabul, had been bombed after
guerrillas occupied the town for 24 hours last month.
   He said guerrillas tried to seize the city but were repulsed by
the Afghan army.
   ``The city is under government control, and there is no
destruction in Maidan Shahr,'' he said.
   Western diplomats also said guerrillas are massing around the
city of Paghman, 20 miles from Kabul.
   ``There is a military confrontation between government troops
and rebel units but no populated locality, as of today, has been
surrendered to the rebels,'' Perfilyev said.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of an Afghan guerrilla group, told
reporters the guerrillas are building strength around Kabul, and
the resistance will move on the capital ``in the very near future.''
   The Soviet Union, which sent troops into Afghanistan in December
1979, has begun withdrawing them from the country. Under an
agreement signed in Geneva in April, the Soviets agreed to have
half their estimated 115,000 soldiers out by Aug. 15 and the rest
by Feb. 15.
   The Soviets entered Afghanistan to prop up a Marxist government
and help it fight the Islamic guerrillas.
   The guerrillas have not agreed to stop fighting the government
of President Najib.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
