<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Church-State     07-06 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church-State,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Deletes Religious Group From Tax Credits List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A religious group which helps youngsters
with drug problems should not receive state financial aid because
it limits membership to those who accept Jesus Christ, a town
meeting has decided.
   The meeting voted 20-5 Tuesday night to delete Connecticut Youth
for Christ from a list of 24 municipally approved, non-profit
agencies eligible for donations under the state's Neighborhood
Assistance Act.
   ``The organization should be of service to the entire community
as a whole because that is the purpose of the act. With this one,
those who do not accept Jesus Christ do not qualify,'' said Penny
Lind, chairwoman of the meeting's social services committee.
   The list will be sent to the state Department of Revenue
Services, which will determine whether the organization should be
included in a master list to be mailed to Connecticut businesses
and corporations. A contribution to any of these organizations
brings 50 percent to 60 percent credits on the Connecticut
corporate business tax.
   Lind said $3 million in tax credits are available statewide this
year.
   Stephen J. Hall, executive director of Youth for Christ, said
the town of Thomastown has submitted the name of the group on its
state list for the last two years. The action by Westport would
penalize the group, he said.
</TEXT>
