<1ST_LINE>u a PM-VesselSeized 1stLd-Writethru a0673 07-06 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vessel Seized, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marijuana Ship Arrives in Seattle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to CORRECT that flag was on Coast Guard
vessel, sted seized ship, picking up 4th graf pvs, `Allison said
....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship carrying more than 70 tons of
well-packaged marijuana arrived in port today after being seized on
the high seas by a Coast Guard cutter for not flying a flag and
refusing orders to stop.
   The Coast Guard cutter Boutwell, sporting a makeshift flag
showing a marijuana leaf with a red line diagonally across it,
towed the Panamanian-registered Encounter Bay to a Seattle pier.
   ``Our best estimate is there is somewhere in excess of 72 tons''
of marijuana on board, said the Boutwell's captain, Cecil Allison.
He described the drug as ``very high grade with very few stems and
very few seeds.''
   Allison said the marijuana, with a street value estimated at
about $280 million, consisted of about 8,000 bales packed in four
large shipping containers. Each bale, in a blue nylon sack,
contained eight packets of marijuana vacuum-sealed in double
plastic wrappings.
   ``You would like to get some of your freeze-dried food packed
this well,'' the captain said.
   The marijuana vessel, a 180-foot converted offshore oil rig
supply ship, was under tight security as agents of the U.S. Drug
Enforcment Administration secured the ship's cargo and the
18-member crew.
   Crew members were being fingerprinted aboard the Boutwell before
a scheduled appearance before a U.S. magistrate this afternoon.
   Thirteen of the crew were from Indonesia, Thailand and
Singapore. The other five included three from the United States and
one each from Britain and New Zealand, the Coast Guard said.
   The crew members were cooperative, but all refused to talk about
the drug shipment, Allison said.
   If it can be proved the ship was bound for the United States,
they could face felony charges of a few years to life in prison,
depending on prior convictions and sentencing guidelines, said Gary
Liming, special agent-in-charge of the Drug Enforcement
Administration in Seattle.
   The owner of the Encounter Bay was listed as Countess Shipping
Corp. of Panama.
   Liming said the pot was probably from the Far East, possibly
Thailand, with California the eventual destination.
   With an estimated street value of $2,000 per pound, the
marijuana is worth about $280 million, making it one of the largest
drug seizures in maritime history and the biggest on the West
Coast, said Coast Guard Lt. Eldo DeLong.
   Sixty rounds were fired from a .50-caliber machine gun aboard
the 378-foot Boutwell into the Encounter Bay's engine room after
the vessel refused to stop.
   Permission to board the ship was obtained from the Panamanian
embassy after suspicions were raised when it was spotted in
international waters off the central Washington coast from a Coast
Guard C-130 aircraft, DeLong said.
   ``It wasn't flying a flag, the name and home port weren't
readily visible, and it's kind of unusual to see this type of
vessel in this area,'' he explained.
   Authorities had no idea about the vessel's cargo before
boarding, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MexicoElection-Glance     07-06 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico Election-Glance,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Brief Look at the Mexico Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some facts and figures
about Wednesday's election in Mexico:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PRESIDENCY _ Four men and one woman are running for a
single, six-year term that begins Dec. 1. The three major
candidates are Carlos Salinas de Gortari of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI; Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front coalition; and
Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative National Action Party. Also
running are Rosario Ibarra de Piedra of the radical Revolutionary
Workers Party and Gumersindo Magana Negrete of the tiny Mexican
Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE SENATE _ Voters elect 64 senators, two from each of Mexico's
31 states and two from the federal district. Like presidents,
senators serve six years and cannot be re-elected. Mexico has had
only one opposition senator under PRI rule.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CHAMBER of DEPUTIES _ 500 members of the lower house will be
elected for three-year terms, expanding the size of the current
chamber by 100. The ruling party has 289 seats. The rest are spread
among nine opposition parties.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ISSUES _ Election fraud, a stagnating economy hobbled by
inflation and a massive foreign debt.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE VOTERS _ About 38 million out of an estimated 80 million
population are registered. More than 10 percent have five years or
less education, more than 61 percent are under 40. The electorate
is about evenly split between men and women.
</TEXT>
