<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     07-06 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharon Edges Out Arens In Herut Elections For Knesset Slate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERZLIYA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates of the right-wing Herut Party
chose top candidates Wednesday for November's election, and former
Defense Minister Ariel Sharon edged out a rival backed by Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   A dozen riot police guarded the convention at this seaside
resort, apparently to prevent clashes among Herut's three camps
headed by Sharon, Cabinet Minister Moshe Arens and Deputy Prime
Minister David Levy. A convention two years ago was aborted after
fistfights between party members.
   More than 2,000 party delegates chose among 35 candidates for
the second through eighth slots on the party slate. First place is
reserved for Shamir, leader of Herut, the senior partner in the
Likud bloc.
   Likud and its main rival, the left-of-center Labor Party, are
running neck-and-neck in polls.
   To prevent fighting among the three camps, Shamir recommended
Levy for second place, Arens for third and Sharon for fourth. Arens
is a Shamir ally, while Sharon and Levy have sought to wrest party
leadership from Shamir.
   The delegates gave Levy the second spot, but Sharon came in
third ahead of Arens, a former ambassador to the United States.
   Shamir denied the results were a personal setback. ``There was
no disloyalty by anyone,'' he told Israel army radio. He also noted
that placement on the slate would not affect candidates' future
Cabinet posts.
   Arens said the vote ``went against our agreement,'' noting that
he voted according to Shamir's recommendations. But Arens told
reporters he was ``not bitter.''
   Sharon, who is trade and industry minister, played down the
importance of the results. ``These are not votes that will
determine the future leader of the party,'' he told Israel
television. ``There is no reason to create unnecessary tension.''
   Levy, who made his political fortune as an advocate of the once
underprivileged North African-born Israelis, was thronged by
supporters who showered him with kisses.
   He criticized Shamir for trying to influence the vote, saying:
``I'm sorry the prime minister saw the need to make
recommendations.''
   The delegates also gave top slots to two newcomers to party
politics, former U.N. Ambassador Binyamin Netanyahu and former
Prime Minister Menachem Begin's son, Benjamin. Netanyahu came in
sixth and Begin was ranked eighth.
   The poolside convention was held in a carnival-like atmosphere.
   The rank-and-file showered voting delegates with buttons and
stickers bearing the names of candidates. North African-style music
blasted from an open-sided tent staked by Levy backers. Sharon
supporters walking by the pool shouted slogans through megaphones.
   The balloting was part of a complicated selection process to put
together a slate for the parliamentary elections.
   Israeli voters choose a party, not individual candidates, and
each party is apportioned Parliament seats according to the number
of votes it wins.
   Last week, Herut chose 35 candidates, and in Wednesday's vote,
those candidates were ranked. Based on 1984 election results, the
top 30 candidates have a realistic chance of winning a seat.
   Two more rounds of voting were to follow to determine slots nine
through 22.
   The remaining candidates will be ranked according to the number
of votes they got in last week's balloting.
   The Liberal Party, the junior partner in Likud, has already
selected its 12 parliamentary candidates who, according to an
agreement with Herut, will be given roughly every third slot on the
Likud list.
</TEXT>
