<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Specter     07-06 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Specter,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Surrogate Gets Ambushed In Dukakis Territory</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. Arlen Specter invaded Michael
Dukakis' home turf Wednesday to criticize the likely Democratic
presidential nominee's record on crime, but Specter was in turn
ambushed by Dukakis allies.
   The Pennsylvania senator, appearing at the Massachusetts
Statehouse at the request of likely Republican nominee George Bush,
arrived to find Dukakis supporters including the state's current
and former attorneys general, several county prosecutors and police
chiefs, and state officials involved in anti-crime and anti-drug
programs.
   Also, Specter didn't travel up from Washington alone. Democratic
Sen. John F. Kerry, who also served under Dukakis as lieutenant
governor, took the same flight to Boston so he could be on hand to
defend Dukakis.
   Specter's main target was Dukakis' support of a state program
that allowed inmates sentenced to life in prison without parole to
be released on furloughs.
   One such inmate raped a Maryland woman, leading to tighter
eligibility standards that Dukakis originally opposed but later
signed into law after they were given overwhelming approval by the
Legislature.
   Bush has made the Maryland incident a staple in his pitch to
portray Dukakis as soft on crime, and Specter was here to continue
that effort, saying Dukakis' support for giving furloughs to
no-parole inmates ``raises a question as to his overall judgment.''
   Kerry, standing close by, would have none of that.
   He moved up to the microphone, exchanged pleasantries with
Specter and proceeded to denounce Bush as a do-nothing vice
president who failed as the leader of Reagan administration
anti-drug efforts.
   ``Cocaine is more readily available on the streets of America
today than at any time in history,'' Kerry told reporters. ``This
nation does not need a silent leader in the war on drugs and the
fight against crime,'' Kerry said to cheers from partisan onlookers.
   Kerry then defended the Massachusetts furlough program, saying
its eligibility standards were stricter than many state programs
and the federal prison system.
   It was Specter's turn to steal back the microphone that was
supposed to be his to begin with.
   ``Governor Dukakis' furlough system is indefensible,'' he said.
   Kerry said, ``The furlough program in Massachusetts is tougher
than the federal program.''
   He also contended Specter's appearance was designed to draw
attention from the resignation of embattled Attorney General Edwin
Meese III and called it ``an effort to obfuscate, to try to hide
this administration's failures in law enforcement.''
   Specter kept his cool though visibly annoyed that the Dukakis
allies had imposed on his show.
   State Attorney General James Shannon introduced Specter but also
made sure to refer to the declining crime rate in Massachusetts.
When Shannon, a Democrat, had gone on long enough for Specter, the
senator tried to pry away the microphone and a Specter aide reached
out for Shannon.
   ``That's not necessary,'' Specter told the aide before turning
to Shannon. ``But this is my news conference.''
</TEXT>
