<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HaitianPermits     07-06 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haitian Permits,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Complaint Charges INS With Denying 14,000 Work Permits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing on the fate of 14,000 farmworkers facing
expulsion from the United States opened Wednesday with a farm owner
saying the government acted arbitrarily in granting work permits to
Haitians and other foreigners.
   Martha Taylor, a cherry tomato and pepper farmer from Hendry
County, said she employs 80 to 120 mostly Mexican farmworkers, and
at one point provided affidavits for some of them.
   ``Of 18 workers during that particular period, 11 got their
green cards and there were seven denials,'' Mrs. Taylor said. ``All
had the same proof.''
   Mrs. Taylor testified before Senior U.S. District Judge C. Clyde
Atkins, who moved the hearing to a larger courtroom to accommodate
hundreds of Haitians who gathered peacefully outside the courthouse.
   The suit filed by the Roman Catholic Diocese of Palm Beach
County, the Haitian Refugee Center and individual migrant workers
accuses immigration authorities of improperly refusing agricultural
work permits to foreigners.
   Without the permits, which can be granted only to laborers who
worked at least 90 hours in the fields within a certain period,
they can be expelled from the country.
   The case directly affects an estimated 14,000 Haitians, Mexicans
and other foreign workers in Florida, Alabama and Georgia,
attorneys in the case say, and could apply across the country.
   Attorneys for the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
say they have refused to issue permits on the basis of sworn
affidavits alone because the program is rife with fraud.
   However, Ira Kurzban, an attorney for the laborers, argued that
the INS stand violates Congress' intentions in passing the new
immigration law.
   Kurzban said the INS is requiring documentary evidence such as
pay stubs or employment records even though Congress stated
affidavits would be sufficient.
   ``The government has imposed an impossible burden of proof,'' on
the farm workers, many of whom were paid without tax deductions, he
said.
   Garry Leffert, an attorney from Martinsburg, W.Va., who has
represented many farm workers, testified that crew chiefs often
failed to keep records of payments.
   Along with the refusal to accept the affidavits, the suit
charges that the INS has held hearings on the permits without
translators present, and is not granting required temporary work
permits during the appeal process.
   The hearing was adjourned until Thursday.
</TEXT>
