<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Movies     07-06 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Movies,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Considers Rating Movies Unfit For Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The increasing frankness of Chinese filmmakers in
showing sex and violence has led the government to consider rating
movies unsuitable for children, an official report said Wednesday.
   The China Youth News quoted Film Bureau chief Teng Jinxian as
saying some modern movies contain scenes that are unhealthy for
children but vital to the plot or development of character.
   One example is ``Red Sorghum,'' which shared 1988 best-picture
honors in China's Golden Rooster Awards announced Tuesday. The
story includes a rape, although it is not shown explicitly, and
shows a man being skinned to death at the order of Japanese
soldiers during World War II.
   Rather than cut the scenes, Teng said, the bureau may label the
movie unsuitable for children. He did not say if theaters would be
required to bar children from attending such films.
   Only in recent years have Chinese films contained strong sexual
elements. The strong streak of puritanism in China's Communist
rulers long required all movies to show only wholesome characters
loyally serving the nation.
</TEXT>
