<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Abortion Billboard,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Halted From Removing Anti-Abortion Sign From Church Property</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOTSWOOD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not what you say but how big you say
it, Spotswood officials told a church group that put up an
anti-abortion billboard.
   But a church attorney looked at the billboard another way, and a
judge agreed.
   Superior Court Judge John C. Bachman issued a temporary
restraining order Tuesday, forbidding the borough from acting
against Immaculate Conception Church or the sign. He set a Sept. 6
hearing on the matter.
   The Knights of Columbus Council 4907 put up the sign on the
Roman Catholic church's lawn in June. It shows a baby and says
``Kill Her Now ... It's Murder. Kill Her Before Birth ... It's
Abortion.''
   ``It's a freedom-of-speech issue,'' Robert Rafano, the attorney
representing the church and council, said Wednesday.
   Borough zoning officer Jack McDonald said he doesn't care what
message is on the sign as long as the sign is legal. Now, he said,
the 72-square-foot billboard exceeds the size limit of 25 square
feet.
   But Rafano argued the ordinance does not mention signs with a
``public message'' and the law does not apply.
   ``How can we exercize freedom of speech if people can't read our
message?'' he said.
   McDonald acknowledged that borough officials began to look into
the billboard after someone complained anonymously to police.
   ``The complainant said the anti-abortion message is distasteful
and offensive and the picture of the baby on the sign is
distraction to traffic,'' he said. ``But the size is in violation
of the zoning ordinance.
   ``The content has nothing to do with anything as far as I'm
concerned.''
   On June 14, the borough issued a notice to the church that said
the billboard's size violated the zoning ordinance. Facing a
summons, the church sued.
</TEXT>
