<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Funerals     07-06 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Funerals,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Bury 24 Killed on Airliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Gulf Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranians shouting ``Death to America!''
and waving banners vowing revenge held funerals Wednesday for 24 of
the 290 people killed when a U.S. warship shot down an Iranian
airliner.
   Fourteen were buried in Bandar Abbas, starting point for the
short flight over the Strait of Hormuz to Dubai, and the others
were buried at Zahedan, in southeastern Iran, Iranian television
reported.
   Iran said 200 bodies had been recovered from the gulf since
missiles fired by the USS Vincennes destroyed the plane Sunday. All
but 38 of those on the plane were Iranians.
   The television broadcast 15 minutes of scenes from the funerals
in Bandar Abbas and Zahedan. It said hundreds of thousands of
Iranians joined the processions to mourn the victims and
demonstrate solidarity with leaders who have called for revenge.
   Women clad in head-to-toe black chadors marched silently behind
the coffins carrying banners, some of which read: ``America: You
fight with weapons and we with our belief in God, and your defeat
is imminent,'' ``Revenge Revenge,'' ``War until victory.''
   Men waved their fists, shouting ``Death to America!'' and ``Down
with Reagan!''
   Coffins were draped with Iranian flags: green, white and red
with ``Allah'' or ``God,'' written in the middle.
   Several jeeps carrying Revolutionary Guards drove behind the
marchers, using loudspeakers to blare revolutionary songs and
verses from the Koran, the holy book of Islam.
   A larger ceremony and march is scheduled for Thursday in Tehran
for the other victims whose bodies have been recovered, the
television said.
</TEXT>
