<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     07-06 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge, Provisional Government Emerge As Trouble Points</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Optimism over upcoming Cambodian peace
talks has been overshadowed by a lack of compromise on two key
issues: the future of the Khmer Rouge and the formation of a new
government.
   Foreign ministers of Southeast Asian countries said a trend
toward dialogue has created more optimism than ever before about
ending the 9-year-old war between Cambodian guerrillas and the
Vietnamese occupying the country.
   Thailand's Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda told the annual
conference of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations that
``peace ... is at hand.'' He said the region soon can focus on
economic development and usher in ``a new era of peace and
prosperity.''
   The ministers ended the conference Tuesday and are to start
talks Thursday with Western leaders, including Secretary of State
George Shultz. They're expected to ask for help in guaranteeing a
settlement in Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 after bloody border
clashes with the communist Khmer Rouge regime, which killed
hundreds of thousands of its people from 1975-78. Vietnamese forces
installed a sympathetic government and are battling a guerrilla
coalition of the Khmer Rouge and forces of former Cambodian leaders
Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Son Sann.
   The Cambodian factions, Vietnam, Laos, and ASEAN countries are
to attend informal peace talks in Indonesia on July 25. But they
face the same hurdles that abruptly halted earlier talks between
Sihanouk and Hun Sen, prime minister of the pro-Vietnam Cambodian
government.
   Indonesia's Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, organizer of the talks,
told The Associated Press Monday that ``many obstacles'' to an
agreement remain. Although the parties agree on the final outcome,
they differ widely on how to get there, he said.
   One problem is the Khmer Rouge.
   The pro-Vietnamese government's SPK news agency on Wednesday
called the group ``the greatest obstacle'' to a settlement. Worries
of a return of the Khmer Rouge, the strongest guerrilla force, have
intensified with Vietnam's pullout of 50,000 troops this year and
stated plans to withdraw the remaining 50,000 by 1990.
   Some diplomats say the Khmer Rouge is storing arms, avoiding
direct military clashes and infiltrating villages to prepare
all-out attacks in 1990.
   Vietnam and the Hun Sen government insist that the Khmer Rouge
be dismantled as a military and political organization and that
leader Pol Pot and his top aides not be allowed any role in
Cambodia's future because of their ``genocide'' and threat to
Vietnam's security.
   Official Vietnamese radio said Tuesday the troop pullout opened
the door to a negotiated settlement, but the second key problem,
Pol Pot, remains. It quoted Vietnam's Foreign Minister Nguyen Co
Thach as saying the world community has a responsibility to ensure
the Khmer Rouge does not return to power.
   The Khmer Rouge, armed mainly by China, has remained silent on
the demands regarding its leadership.
   But China recently called for formation of a coalition
government and a freeze on all force levels until elections are
held.
   Sihanouk told the ASEAN ministers the Khmer Rouge has agreed to
his proposal to dissolve the resistance coalition and the
pro-Vietnamese government at the same time. In Sihanouk's scheme,
the four factions would form a provisional government after
Vietnam's complete pullout and organize general elections leading
to a neutral nation.
   Hun Sen has flatly rejected dissolution of his government and
said the guerrilla factions must instead join his regime.
   The SPK commentary said the Hun Sen government has controlled
all the country's territory since 1979 and its dissolution would
mean the return of the Khmer Rouge regime.
   A resistance radio broadcast Tuesday said free elections could
not be held under the auspices of the Hun Sen government.
   The radio said Hun Sen's refusal to budge on this point showed
it wanted to impose the communist regime and also ``that Vietnam
does not yet have the good will to find a solution to the Cambodian
problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
