<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PalestinianAid     07-06 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palestinian Aid,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Probes Whether UN Agency Funneling Aid To
Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a secret exchange with United Nations
officials, the State Department has explored reports that rioting
Palestinian Arabs on the Israeli-held West Bank and in Gaza were
financed through a U.N. agency, but the reports were denied ``and
the case is closed,'' two U.S. officials said Wednesday.
   While channeling aid to the Palestinians who began their
uprising last December may not be illegal, allowing the U.N. Relief
Works Agency to be used that way would upset Israel, the officials
said in separate interviews.
   ``We didn't like it, either,'' one of the officials said.
``UNRWA is not supposed to be a conduit for funds, legal or
illegal. It's not what UNRWA is about.''
   But the other official said the U.S. concern was based entirely
on Israeli ``sensitivity.''
   The officials discussed the secret inquiry only on condition
they would not be identified.
   THe U.N. agency distributes assistance to tens of thousands of
Palestinian refugees who live in camps on the West Bank and in
Gaza. More than 17,000 Palestinians work for UNRWA in the
territories.
   The reports reached the State Department about a month ago, and
prompted cabled inquires to the U.N. agency's headquarters in
Vienna where they were flatly denied. ``We don't have a problem,''
a U.S. official said. ``But it doesn't mean it can't happen again.''
   With Israel's implicit approval, an Arab fund supervised by
Jordan and the Palestine Liberation Organization had provided aid
to Palestinians in the Israeli-held territories apart from U.N.
assistance. But after the outbreak of violence last December,
Israel sought to impose controls on the assistance.
   The Arab League, meeting last month in Algeria, responded by
deciding to provide $129 million to the Palestinians, including
demonstrators and rioters, to support the uprising. Some 200
Palestinians and 3 Israelis have died in clashes that some Israeli
officials say were ordered by the PLO in an attempt to destabilize
the Jewish state.
   In asking UNRWA authorities for an explanation, ``we went in not
with a reprimand but with a question,'' one of the officials said.
``The reports were denied. We accepted it.''
   He added: ``It's an issue Israelis are very sensitive about.''
   The official said the report did not specify the amount of money
said to be passing to the Palestinians through the U.N. agency.
   He said the State Department inquiry ``was handled in a pretty
restricted channel,'' but was now becoming known because of the
cable traffic between Washington and Vienna.
</TEXT>
