<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VincennesDonations     07-06 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes Donations,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Donations Soar For USS Vincennes Memorial Following Gulf Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VINCENNES, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donations for construction of a $37,000
monument honoring the USS Vincennes have spurted since the warship
downed an Iranian passenger jetliner, according to the chairman of
the fund-raising committee.
   More than $500 in donations arrived in Wednesday's mail, said
James Funk, fund-raising chairman of the monument project. Last
week, the first week of the drive, only $161 was donated, he said.
   ``I believe the increase came from both exposure to the facts
about the four ships named Vincennes and as an expression of the
people's support of the present situation the current ship is in,''
Funk said.
   Fund-raisers already have collected about two-thirds of the
money needed to build a $37,000 monument honoring the USS Vincennes
and three other Navy ships of the same name.
   The USS Vincennes Association, which includes veterans of the
four ships, will pay half of that cost and has already raised more
than $14,000. Local businesses have donated more than $10,000
toward the city's half, Funk said.
   Officials say 290 civilians died Sunday when the Vincennes, an
Aegis-class guided missile cruiser, shot down the commercial
airliner. The action came after the pilot failed to respond to
several radio challenges on civilian and military frequencies.
   The warship is the fourth to bear the Vincennes name. The
southwestern Indiana city plans to construct a pyramid of granite
to commemorate the four ships. Each side of the pyramid will bear a
silhouette and history of one of the ships.
   The first ship, a wooden sloop-of-war, was launched in 1826 and
was the first Navy ship to circumnavigate the globe. During a
four-year worldwide voyage that began in 1838, artifacts were
gathered that became the foundation of the Smithsonian Institution.
   The second ship, a heavy cruiser, CA-44, was commissioned in
1937 and sunk by Japanese gunfire Aug. 9, 1942 off Savo Island
during the battle for Guadalcanal.
   The third ship, a light cruiser, CL-64, was commissioned Jan.
21, 1944 and served in the Pacific. The ship received six battle
stars and was decommissioned in 1946. It was sunk for use as a
target ship, but the bell was salvaged and is on display at
Vincennes City Hall.
   The current ship, the first Aegis-class cruiser to join the
Pacific fleet, was commissioned July 6, 1985.
</TEXT>
