<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     07-06 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closed Hearing Held on North Request to Use Classified Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fired White House aide Oliver L. North and his
defense lawyers attended a closed hearing Wednesday to argue their
requests to use secret documents as evidence in the Iran-Contra
conspiracy case.
   The hearing before U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell was
closed both to the public and to prosecutors, to protect the
secrecy of the documents and North's defense strategy.
   Gesell convened the hearing to begin the process of reviewing
North's requests and determine if the material culled from the mass
of secret documents collected by prosecutors is relevant to the
case.
   North has been given until July 11 to file a list of secret
documents he proposes to use in defending charges he conspired to
illegally divert profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   After the judge determines which, if any, of the documents may
be used as evidence, Gesell will conduct closed proceedings with
government attorneys present to determine whether the material can
be released at a public trial.
   Separate trials have been ordered for North, former national
security adviser John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim
and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord.
   The judge has not set a trial date for North, saying the case is
not ready to be tried because of the lack of progress in
declassifying the 200,000 pages of classified documents collected
by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh.
   In a brief filing, Walsh reported no further progress in
discussions with government agencies about ways to delete sensitive
portions of documents he intends to introduce into evidence.
   ``A number of the issues raised by those documents, particularly
those that relate to geographical locations, are under ongoing
consideration at high levels at those agencies,'' Walsh said in the
filing.
   But, he said, ``no matter how those issues are resolved, we
believe that the case can proceed'' with appropriate editing of
classified material or ``in a few cases, substitutions for the
documents'' with statements of what they would prove.
   Fewer than 10 documents contain material so sensitive that Walsh
said he would ask the judge to allow prosecutors to show them only
to the court and jury.
   Walsh said most of the problems relate to the use of symbols to
protect names, places and countries. ``The more difficult problem
arising from the protection of sources and intelligence activities
can for the most part be solved'' by editing of material that is
irrelevant to the case, he said.
   Walsh also reported that Edward S.G. Dennis, acting assistant
attorney general in charge of the Justice Department's criminal
division, has been designated to speak for the Reagan
administration on issues dealing with classified material.
   The task should be made easier because Walsh has withdrawn 226
of the 628 classified documents he originally planned to use as
evidence, according to court papers.
   The original list of 628 documents was submitted to the court
before Gesell ordered four separate trials.
</TEXT>
