<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Paisley 1stLd-Writethru a0715 07-06 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paisley, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0715,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Investigation in Death of Wife of Key Figure in Pentagon Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Melvyn in lead and 11th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police reopened an investigation into the 1968
death of the second wife of Melvyn Paisley, a central figure in the
Pentagon procurement investigation, because of discrepancies
between his story and an autopsy report, authorities said Wednesday.
   The autopsy and a separate medical investigator's report that
contains Paisley's account include ``inconsistencies,'' said Maj.
Terry Allman, head of the King County Police criminal investigation
division.
   The May 7, 1968, death of 30-year-old Mary Lou Paisley was ruled
accidental at the time.
   Allman would not detail any discrepancies, but said: ``The fact
that a woman had taken a drink along with two sleeping pills _ and
a woman of fairly small stature _ and then gotten up in the middle
of the night to paint and was found facedown in a rag ... seemed
rather odd.''
   Medical examiner records from 1968 show Paisley told
investigators his wife had an alcoholic drink and took two of his
Doriden sleeping pills before going to bed the night of her death.
   Several hours later, the records quote him as saying, he awoke
to find his wife face down in the bathroom on a towel containing
carbon tetrachloride, a cleaning solvent for paintbrushes.
   ``He said she apparently had gotten restless and got up and was
painting pictures and was cleaning up her brushes when she
apparently was overcome by the fumes,'' the medical examiner's
report said.
   The autopsy report is confidential. But King County Medical
Examiner Dr. Donald Reay said there was no trace of sleeping pills,
alcohol or carbon tetrachloride in the dead woman's blood. Lab
tests may not have been sensitive enough to detect small amounts,
but there is no way of knowing now for sure, he said.
   Next to cause of death, the coroner's report has a question
mark, followed by ``drug hypersensitivity.''
   ``There is nothing in there that indicates violence ... chemical
violence or physical violence,'' Reay told The Seattle Times.
``It's the absence of findings that would allow one to draw
conclusions. ... That's what makes this a puzzling case.''
   Melvyn Paisley is a former assistant Navy secretary and
ex-Boeing Co. executive, who has been accused of bribing Pentagon
officials and steering military contracts to companies he later
served as a private consultant.
   ``I think the general publicity about the man piqued our
interest and we went back and looked at the limited information in
the case,'' County police spokesman Dick Larson said Wednesday.
   Lack of police records, however, could stymie investigators, he
said.
   ``That's one of the problems _ the documents were destroyed,''
he said.
   Officers would be questioned who investigated the case and are
no longer with the department but still alive.
   Paisley's attorney, Lawrence Barcella of Washington, D.C., did
not immediately return a phone call from The Associated Press on
Wednesday, but told Seattle newspapers police ``are going to waste
valuable time and resources.''
   Since the death of Mrs. Paisley, Paisley's second wife, Paisley
has married and divorced a third wife and now is married a fourth
time.
   ``(Paisley) told me the police tried to pin it on him,'' said
James Durst of Bellevue, who worked with Paisley at Boeing. ``He
said they gave him a bad time for several months but let him go
because there was nothing wrong.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
