<DOCNO> AP880706-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1915EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     07-06 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed Tightening Of Racial Segregation Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed bill to increase
penalties for violation of segregation laws and to facilitate
evictions and confiscation of property came under criticism
Wednesday.
   The pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, called on Parliament
to reconsider the Group Areas Amendment proposed last week. ``Its
penalties are excessively harsh, it is open to abuse, it is harmful
to race relations, and it is bound to cause further damage to the
country's image abroad,'' said an editorial in the English-language
paper.
   The bill would allow inspectors to search for violators of the
racial segregation laws and magistrates to penalize people for not
appearing in court when accused by anyone of a violation. It would
require eviction even when there was no housing available in the
violator's own ``group area.'' The law provides no appeal of a
magistrate's decision and allows the government to confiscate
houses and apartments that are rented to people in the wrong race
classification.
   The bill also increases the penalties for violation of racial
segregation laws from $250 fines or three months in jail to $5,000
fines or five years in prison.
   It ``contains some fearsome provisions, hardly distinguishable
from the Nazi treatment of Jews,'' said Business Day, a daily
newspaper that generally reflects the views of the business
community.
   ``One explanation for the latest official policy on group areas
is that government has lost its wits, which is a possibility ...
For the moment, we assume they are sane, but wrong,'' the paper
said.
   Both papers suggested that the government was trying to put up a
tough image to win conservative, right-wing votes in the October
municipal elections.
   The proposed legislation on segregation was accompanied by
another bill that would allow for the first time the mixing of
races in designated residential areas.
   Some white neighborhoods in major South African cities have over
the years become illegally mixed as whites moved to the suburbs,
while blacks, ``Coloreds'' and Indians, moved into the city.
   Newspapers, politicans and lawyers predicted increased tension
and bad publicity if the government tried to reverse the tide in
such entrenched mixed areas by enforcing the proposed law.
   The proposed bill is to be debated in the next session of
Parliament, beginning Aug. 22. Business Day predicted neither the
mixed-race nor the Indian chambers of Parliament would approve it.
   But the ruling Nationalist Party has a majority in the white
chamber of Parliament and controls the President's Council, which
can pass legislation opposed by the two smaller, non-white chambers.
   In the southern port city of Durban, which has large Indian
population, two groups opposing the bill set the stage for major
civil confrontations and court actions.
   The White Liberation Movement, a suprematist group, said, ``If
the proper powers do not take the necessary steps themselves to
enforce the laws, we will ensure that the offenders are removed.''
   It said there were 9,000 people living illegally in Durban. But
the local branch of Lawyers for Human Rights said 150 attorneys in
the area would provide free legal representation to fight every
case.
   ``These people have nowhere to go,'' the lawyers said. ``There
is no room in black areas and flats are lying vacant in white
areas.''
   The government said it will take decades to construct homes for
the concentration of blacks in urban areas, where a now-disavowed
government policy once limited the availability of housing to keep
them away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
