<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Airliner-StarkCaptain     07-06 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Stark Captain,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stark Commander Says Two Gulf Incidents Not Necessarily Similar</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former commander of the USS Stark said
Wednesday that the downing of an Iranian commercial jet by a Navy
warship was not necessarily similar to the Iraqi jet attack on his
ship that killed 37 sailors and forced him out of the service.
   ``The CO (commanding officer) had a hard time,'' said Glenn R.
Brindel of the decision by Capt. Will C. Rogers III of the USS
Vincennes to shoot down the oncoming Iranian Air Airbus A-300. ``He
called the shots the way he had to.
   ``Some people are trying to draw parallels between the two
incidents. I don't necessarily concur with that.''
   Brindel said he did not wish to comment further.
   Brindel's ship was hit in the Persian Gulf by two Exocet
missiles fired from an Iraqi jet 12 miles away. The frigate had
little warning before the missiles struck. The ship's Phalanx
anti-aircraft system was not engaged at the time of the attack.
   The Vincennes, a sophisticated Aegis-class cruiser, was
receiving confusing radio signals from the Airbus, making
identification of the craft difficult. At the same time, the
Vincennes and another Navy warship were engaging several Iranian
gunboats that had fired on one of the Vincennes' helicopters.
   When the aircraft did not respond to several warnings from the
Vincennes, Navy officials said Rogers ordered two missiles launched
at the plane. Based on the information available, the captain said
he believed the plane to be an F-14.
   Iranian authorities said 290 people were aboard; there were no
survivors.
   In the 1987 attack on the Stark, a Navy investigation found that
the ship was never ready or capable of repelling an attack and
recommended that Brindel, then a captain, be court-martialed.
   Instead, the Navy allowed Brindel to retire at the rank of
commander after he was given a letter of reprimand.
   Adm. Frank B. Kelso, commander-in-chief of the Atlantic Fleet,
said the decision not to follow the recommendation of investigators
was based in part on the surprise nature of the attack and the
heroic response of Brindel and his crew in saving the ship.
   Brindel now sells real estate in Virginia Beach, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
