<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SBABill     07-06 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SBA Bill,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes SBA Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday passed 342-40 a bill
continuing the Small Business Administration's subsidy programs and
rejecting President Reagan's call to end SBA direct loans.
   The measure includes provisions giving aid to firms seeking to
sell overseas, and banning SBA assistance for firms engaging in
business with South Africa.
   The bill, which goes next to the Senate, authorizes $470 million
in SBA spending next year, $514 million in fiscal 1990 and $566 in
fiscal 1991. It also authorizes spending as necessary for disaster
assistance loans.
   Total SBA-supported loans would reach $3.7 billion next year,
under the bill, up from about $3.2 billion this year.
   Under Congress' multi-step spending process, the final levels
for the SBA and its programs will be set later in appropriations
bills.
</TEXT>
