<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bartok     07-06 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bartok,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 Pay Last Respects To Hungarian Composer's Mortal Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 Hungarians and
hundreds of foreign visitors gathered Wednesday to pay their last
respects to composer Bela Bartok, whose remains were returned to
his homeland from the United States.
   People filed past the coffin in the Academy of Science building
to the strains of ``Concerto,'' one of Bartok's most famous
orchestral compositions. A military honor guard stood at attention.
   The bier was draped with a black shroud and a carpet of wreaths
and flowers surrounded the coffin in the academy's columned
entrance hall.
   Bartok's remains returned Tuesday to Hungary 43 years after his
death in New York, following a journey through five nations, where
officials and musicians paid tribute to one the greatest composers
of this century.
   At the decision of his two sons, Bartok's remains were removed
from his grave at the cemetery of Ferncliff, N.Y., and returned
home.
   The ceremony laying Bartok to rest in Budapest's Farkasret
cemetery was scheduled for Thursday. Bartok will be buried in the
family tomb, close to his greatest friend and collaborator, Zoltan
Kodaly.
</TEXT>
