<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0682 07-06 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Interviews Hamilton In Veep Search, Meets Black Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with civil rights meeting, subbing 2nd graf and
inserting 3 grafs after 10th graf pvs, Paul Brountas</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, meeting with his fourth
prospective running mate in three days, interviewed Indiana Rep.
Lee Hamilton Wednesday in what Hamilton called a ``very relaxed''
session. The congressman said he'd accept if asked.
   Dukakis also met with civil rights leaders as part of his
continuing effort to expand his support among blacks. Among 20
national and local black leaders at the meeting were NAACP
executive director Benjamin Hooks, National Urban League President
John Jacob, the Rev. Joseph Lowery of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference and Coretta Scott King, the widow of Martin
Luther King Jr.
   Still later, Dukakis was to address the Greek Orthodox
Ecumenical Congress, which was holding its convention in Boston.
The likely Republican nominee, Vice President George Bush, was to
address the same group on Thursday.
   Hamilton was the eighth man interviewed by the all-but-certain
Democratic nominee as part of the search for a vice presidential
running mate. One of the eight, Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn, has said he
is not interested.
   After a 50-minute meeting with Dukakis at the Massachusetts
Statehouse, Hamilton fired back a quick ``Yes'' when asked if he
would accept the vice presidential nomination.
   ``I would accept it, first of all, if he thinks I can be
helpful,'' the Indiana Democrat added.
   Hamilton said he had a ``very relaxed and wide-ranging
discussion'' with Dukakis, with the main topics being the vice
presidency and foreign policy.
   Others being considered for the No. 2 spot on the ticket are
Jesse Jackson, Sens. Albert Gore of Tennessee, John Glenn of Ohio,
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas and Bob Graham of Florida, and Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri.
   Dukakis dined with Jackson Monday night and met with Gore and
Gephardt on Tuesday. He interviewed the others in Washington last
week.
   Paul Brountas, Dukakis' campaign chairman, was to remain in
Washington through Friday, gathering information on the contenders
and talking with party leaders.
   The meeting with the civil rights leaders was described by
participants as upbeat and more substantive than a recent session
the same group had with Bush. Members of the black delegation said
they were particularly pleased with Dukakis' pledge to make full
employment a priority.
   ``I cannot recall an issue he disagreed with us on,'' Hooks said.
   Whether blacks will support Dukakis without Jackson on the
ticket is largely up to Jackson. Hooks said. ``I think that they
basically will follow, though some will be disappointed, (they)
will follow his leadership,'' he said.
   Dukakis, in addition to his political chores, also had several
meetings Wednesday on state-related business, including his effort
to balance the budget for the fiscal year that ended last week and
to draft a balanced budget for the new fiscal year.
   Bush had a surrogate invade Dukakis' home turf Wednesday to
criticize a Massachusetts furlough program that allowed the release
of a first-degree murderer who then escaped and raped a Maryland
woman.
   But the surrogate, Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Specter, was ambushed
by Dukakis supporters, including Sen. John F. Kerry, the state's
current and former attorney general, several county prosecutors and
several police chiefs.
   Specter said Bush was a tougher crimefighter than Dukakis and
said the governor's support of the furlough program even after the
Maryland incident ``raises a question as to his overall judgment.''
   However, Kerry stepped in to defend Dukakis and said Bush has
been a failure as the leader of the Reagan administration's
anti-crime and anti-drug efforts.
   Kerry, D-Mass., said the Specter appearance in Boston the day
after Attorney General Edwin Meese III announced he was resigning
was designed to ``hide the reality of what the Justice Department
of Ronald Reagan and George Bush has not done, or what they have
done.''
</TEXT>
