<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-LegalFees     07-06 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Legal Fees,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Legal Fees Could Hit $250,000, Government Could Pay</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III says his
legal fees for the first 7{ months of an independent counsel's
investigation may run as high as $250,000, an amount which the
government may have to pay.
   On his financial disclosure form for 1987, issued this week,
Meese listed his legal fees to the Washington law firm of Miller,
Cassidy, Larroca & Lewin as a liability in the range of $100,000 to
$250,000. Two lawyers in the firm continue to represent Meese, who
was under investigation from May 11, 1987 until Tuesday by
independent counsel James McKay.
   McKay ended his probe by filing an 830-page report with the
panel of federal appeals court judges which appointed him, an act
which signifies that Meese won't be indicted. Meese announced
Tuesday that he was resigning, effective later this summer.
   Under the Ethics in Government Act, Meese may apply for federal
payment of his legal fees, and Meese did so in a previous
independent counsel investigation of his activities in 1984. The
law provides for reimbursement of fees incurred by public officials
who aren't indicted in criminal investigations conducted by an
independent counsel.
   It is unclear whether Meese has been making payments to his
lawyers, Nathan Lewin and James Rocap.
   Rocap declined to discuss the financial arrangements in his and
Lewin's representation of Meese.
   Three years ago, the appeals court judges awarded Meese almost
two-thirds of the $720,824 he sought to pay his legal bills in the
investigation of his activities by independent counsel Jacob Stein,
who determined that Meese had committed no indictable offenses
while he was President Reagan's counselor.
   Of the $472,190 award, $357,515 represented legal fees for
services provided by Leonard Garment, who is with the firm of
Dickstein, Shapiro & Morin.
   A total of $37,805 was awarded in expenses incurred by Garment's
firm, and $76,870 was determined as the total of legal fees to be
paid to the other lawyer in the case, longtime Meese friend E.
Robert Wallach. Wallach is now under indictment in the Wedtech
scandal and it was Wallach's close ties to Meese that triggered the
latest independent counsel probe.
</TEXT>
