<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WisSenate     07-06 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wis Senate,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moody Pulls From Senate Race; Angers Some Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Jim Moody withdrew from the Democratic
primary for U.S. Senate on Wednesday, saying he could not compete
against millionaire Herbert Kohl to be the successor to William
Proxmire, who is retiring.
   The deicison by Moody, who said he would seek re-election to his
5th District seat, angered some fellow Democrats who had planned
their political futures based on his Senate candidacy.
   Former state Democratic Party Chairman Matthew J. Flynn said he
would stay in the congressional race despite Moody's decision. At
least four other Democrats had entered the race, but some said they
might now reconsider.
   Moody's announcement came three days after a Milwaukee Journal
poll showed him well behind former Gov. Anthony Earl and Kohl in
the race for the Democratic nomination, to be decided at a primary
election Sept. 13.
   The survey showed Earl leading among likely voters with 31
percent, while Kohl had 28 percent and Moody 12 percent. Former
deputy Wisconsin Attorney General Edward R. Garvey also had 12
percent while Secretary of State Douglas J. La Follette had 8
percent.
   ``Money is now determining this Senate race. I was faced with
the reality of wiping out my life savings and going deeply into
debt and that would still not be enough,'' Moody said.
   Kohl, who owns professional basketball's Milwaukee Bucks,
dismissed the notion that his wealth had forced Moody from the
race. ``To say that people of Wisconsin can be bought is something
that I've never considered,'' Kohl said. ``A messenger without a
message can't win.''
   Kohl, heir to a supermarket fortune, is a former state
Democratic chairman but has never held elective public office.
   Moody should have little difficulty getting the necessary
signatures on petitions to qualify for a House candidacy by the
July 12 deadline, said campaign manager Michael Elconin.
</TEXT>
