<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MTMSale 1stLd-Writethru a0660 07-06 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MTM Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0564</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Miss Moore;
deletes outdated material; PICKS up 8th graf pvs, bgng, TVS says
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small British television production firm said
Wednesday it is buying MTM, the production company co-founded by
actress Mary Tyler Moore, in what both described as a move to tune
into each other's markets.
   The independent Television South PLC will pay $320 million for
the U.S. firm known for quality series such as ``St. Elsewhere''
and ``Hill Street Blues,'' which have large followings in Europe
although they are out of production.
   TVS Chief Executive James Gatward told reporters that MTM ``had
a very long desire to come to Europe ... I needed to create an
entity in the States, so we came together.''
   MTM, founded in 1970, takes its name from Miss Moore's initials.
   ``I'm very excited about it. I think it's a great opportunity
for MTM to grow, especially in the European market,'' Miss Moore
told a news conference in Beverly Hills, Calif.
   ``I'm thrilled with the kind of production TVS has given us in
the past and I think it's just a natural coupling of these two
companies,'' she said.
   Executives from both firms denied the purchase meant the end of
MTM Entertainment Inc.'s creative heyday, saying the British firm
won't interfere with MTM's award-winning style.
   ``We don't look on this as an acquisition, we see it as a
merger,'' Bob Klosterman, financial vice president of the private
Los Angeles-based MTM, told The Associated Press after a news
conference to announce the purchase.
   ``They don't intend to come over and tell us how to do it, no
more than we intend to do the same,'' he said.
   TVS says it is Britain's fourth-largest independent company in
terms of advertising revenue, and fifth-largest in population
reached. However, although it blankets southern England, the most
prosperous area of Britain, it is not among the top five companies
that dictate commercial network schedules.
   It says buying MTM will make it Britain's largest independent TV
company.
   TVS productions are aired by Independent Television and Channel
4, Britain's two national commercial channels. The non-commercial
British Broadcasting Corp. runs the other two channels.
   TVS said it will finance the deal by issuing $77.7 million in
shares, then raising $242 million in cash by offering $82 million
in convertible preference shares and borrowing $65 million.
   Two French companies, the Canal and S.A. pay television firm,
and the Generale D'Images S.A. communications group, will pay a
total of $99 million for shares in return for a 10 percent stake
each.
   Through the purchase, TVS becomes TVS Entertainment PLC and
gains MTM's library of productions worth $310 million, along with
its U.S. distribution network.
   MTM's pre-tax profits for the year ending in May were $43
million, up from $41 million the previous year.
   Klosterman said the purchase arose after MTM planned a share
flotation last year ``to get our feet wet and then come into the
foreign market'' but was withdrawn after the October crash.
   Gatward said TVS plans to co-produce one series a year, such as
a proposed project to be set in France starring British and
American actors. Most programs will be produced separately, he said.
</TEXT>
