<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Airliner-Pentagon     07-06 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Pentagon,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Data Analysis Changed Officials' Minds About Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>rWith AM-Airline Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military leaders changed their minds and
decided the downed Iranian aircraft was a jetliner rather than an
F-14 fighter because an analysis of intelligence data showed an
A300 Airbus was in the water and no Iranian warplanes were aloft at
the time, sources said Wednesday.
   Immediately after the Persian Gulf incident, which took place on
Sunday at 2:51 a.m. EDT, Iran claimed that the United States had
shot down Iran Air flight 655 with 290 people aboard.
   Within hours, the Pentagon issued a statement saying that the
``USS Vincennes ... reported it downed an Iranian F-14 aircraft
that was approaching in a hostile manner'' after the Vincennes and
another American warship had fought off an attack by Iranian
gunboats.
   As the rest of the world grappled to make sense of these
conflicting assessments Sunday morning, the Joint Chiefs of Staff
assembled in the Pentagon and sifted through the evidence.
   ``Intelligence data was coming in and it showed that there were
no F-14s operating in the area,'' said one source, who like others
demanded anonymity.
   The biggest piece of evidence was the wreckage of the Airbus and
efforts by Iranian vessels, aircraft and divers to recover the
bodies, according to public statements released since the incident
and interviews with administration sources.
   Additionally, U.S. military officials determined that no Iranian
F-14s had been operating in the area. This led the Pentagon to
conclude that the downed aircraft was the airliner, as claimed by
Iran.
   This new conclusion was announced by the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs, Adm. William Crowe, who appeared at a hastily called
Pentagon news conference at 1:30 p.m. EDT Sunday. Crowe announced
that the Vincennes had indeed shot down a civilian airliner rather
than an F-14 fighter.
   Six investigators, headed by Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty,
arrived in the gulf on Wednesday to interview the skipper of the
Vincennes, Capt. Will C. Rogers III, and plumb the electronic
innards of the ship's sophisticated Aegis radar and tracking system.
   Much of the intelligence that led the Pentagon and field
commanders to determine that the plane was an airliner and not a
fighter was not available to Rogers when he fired two SM-2 Standard
missiles at the Iranian aircraft, officials said.
   The intelligence collected after the incident included radio
signals from airplanes and ground stations plus a limited and not
always reliable network of informers on the ground, said one source.
   ``This type of information takes a little time to decode and
sift through, and was not immediately available to Rogers'' or
other American commanders in the gulf, said the source.
   In the hours after the airliner went down, that information was
fed to the local commander of U.S. forces in the gulf, Rear Adm.
Anthony Less, aboard his flagship, the USS Coronado, which is based
at Bahrain in the gulf.
   Less was in radio contact with Rogers aboard the Vincennes, and
authorized him to fire the Standards when the Airbus was 20 miles
away. Rogers waited until the plane was nine miles away, officials
said.
   During the incident and afterward, Less was in radio contact
with headquarters for American forces in the Persian Gulf, the U.S.
Central Command at MacDill Air Force Base in Tampa, Fla., which in
turn was in radio contact with the Pentagon.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard told reporters Tuesday that the
conclusion that the plane was an airliner ``was reached in concert.
Communications were back and forth through Centcom (Central
Command) and it was reached in concert and conjunction with Centcom
and with the information we were receiving from the area.''
   The process of sifting through the information and determining
exactly what happened will be the responsibility primarily of the
investigating team headed by Fogarty. It is expected to complete
its report in two or three weeks, Howard said.
</TEXT>
