<DOCNO> AP880706-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Women-Appointees     07-06 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Appointees,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coalition to Press Presidential Candidates to Appoint More Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of women activists on Wednesday
said they will press the presidential candidates to appoint more
women to executive positions in the new administration.
   Although not an echo of the 1984 clamor for a woman vice
presidential candidate, the Coalition for Women's Appointments will
conduct a bipartisan effort to recruit and recommend qualified
women for presidential appointments, said Irene Natividad,
chairwoman of the National Women's Political Caucus.
   Too often, men have voiced a ``we-can't-find-any syndrome,''
said Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., co-chairman of Vice President George
Bush's presidential campaign.
   She and other participants in a news conference said the goal of
about 50 women's groups in the coalition is to counter that
syndrome by making known the names and resumes of women who have
qualifications for high government posts.
   Others who spoke at the news conference were Rep. Barbara
Kennelly, D-Conn., representing the campaign of Democrat Michael
Dukakis; Eleanor Holmes Norton, a key adviser in the campaign of
Jesse Jackson, who finished second to Dukakis in the Democratic
primaries; and Barbara Blum, former Environmental Protection Agency
official under President Carter.
   The women spoke about the much touted ``gender gap'' showing
that women increasingly have provided a margin of victory for
Democrats in key races, and, according to recent polls, support
Bush in far fewer numbers than men.
   ``We're looking beyond the campaign to show the next
administration that the gender gap does more than deliver votes;
it's also bulging with talent,'' said Natividad.
   Natividad said the Reagan years have seen a slowdown in
appointments of women to key posts. He appointed 54 during his
first term, two of them to cabinet-level posts, compared to 72
appointed by President Carter, with four cabinet members.
   ``This slowdown during the Reagan administration has occurred
despite continuing gains by women in both the private sector and in
elective office ... On the state level, the number of women
appointed to high level positions nearly doubled between 1981 and
1987.''
   The women noted the drumbeat for a woman running mate has been
muted this year compared to 1984 when Democrat Walter Mondale was
nudged into choosing a woman running mate in part by the sheer
fervor in favor of such a move.
   Martin said that the first woman elected president or vice
president will have to be ``perfect or pretty doggone close''
because of the grilling she will undergo.
   Kennelly said many feminists agreed that a woman selected for
vice president should have been a presidential candidate first.
Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., abandoned this year's
presidential race before formally entering it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
