<DOCNO> AP880706-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Pollster     07-06 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Pollster,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Sleaze Factor'' Less for Bush After Meese Resigns, Pollster Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House pollster Richard Wirthlin said
Wednesday the resignation of Attorney General Edwin Meese III
doesn't erase the ``sleaze factor'' for Vice President George Bush
in the fall presidential campaign, but makes it easier for him to
deal with it.
   During a luncheon session with reporters, Wirthlin said only
about 3 percent of the voters he has surveyed cite ethics in
government as the most important issue, a figure that is no higher
than a year earlier.
   The issue that outstrips all others in importance in the minds
of voters is drugs, said the pollster.
   ``There are now 21 percent who tag drugs as the single most
important problem facing the nation,'' he said. No other issue was
named by more than 10 percent of people interviewed.
   ``I think Bush is still going to have to address the `sleaze
factor,''' said Wirthlin when asked about the impact of Meese's
decision to leave the Cabinet.
   For months, while Meese was under investigation by independent
counsel James McKay, Bush was peppered with questions about whether
he thought the attorney general should resign. Bush aides, at one
point, described Meese as a ``liability,'' a description the vice
president disavowed.
   Wirthlin said the departure of Meese would put the ethics issue
``in a different context'' and would ``enable Bush to talk about
ethics without implicitly criticizing Ed Meese.''
   For more than 20 years, Wirthlin has done polling for Ronald
Reagan, beginning when Reagan was governor of California and
continuing through three presidential campaigns.
   During the 1988 primaries, Wirthlin polled for Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas during his unsuccessful race against Bush for the GOP
presidential nomination.
   Wirthlin said that Democrat Michael Dukakis will have an
opportunity to open a wide lead right after the Democratic National
Convention in July and that the Republicans should plan ``some kind
of major event'' to gain attention.
   He suggested the best Bush tactic would be to name his running
mate during the week following the Democratic convention.
   On the question of running mates, Wirthlin said Sen. John Glenn
of Ohio would be ``far and away the best pick on the Democratic
side.'' He said the picture wasn't clear on the Republican side,
but he named Dole and his wife, Elizabeth, as bringing strength to
the ticket as well as Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois and former Gov.
Richard Thornburgh of Pennsylvania.
   Wirthlin also said he thought it would be a mistake to have
President Reagan on the stump attacking Dukakis.
   ``People do not approve of an incumbent president attacking a
candidate trying to succeed him,'' he said.
   In addition, he said, Reagan ``is not a good attack candidate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
