<HEAD>28-Story Plunge Termed Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Wednesday they had no
motive for the death of a businessman in a plunge from the roof of
the 28-story Gulf Life Tower into its lobby.
   Investigators considered the Tuesday afternoon death of a man
they identified as Russell Paul Ginch, 31, a suicide, said police
spokesman Asa Higgs.
   Ginch, dressed in a business suit, apparently jumped from the
roof, fell through a second-floor lobby roof, landed on an
escalator and rolled onto the floor near the building's main
entrance.
   Ed Nichols, a trainer at a gym on the tower's top floor, said he
became suspicious after seeing the man walk through a weight room
onto a sundeck. Nichols followed the man a short time later, but
couldn't find him.
   ``I was up there in a few minutes ... and he was gone,'' Nichols
said.
   Investigators said the man apparently used electrical boxes to
climb 20 feet up from the deck. He then walked along a beam on the
roof to the front of the building and jumped.
   No one else was injured, although several people were nearby,
Higgs said.
   Building officials said they didn't recognize the man as a
tenant or employee in the building, headquarters for an insurance
holding company. Police were trying to find his relatives, friends
or employers, Higgs said.
</TEXT>
