<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iran     07-06 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Says Compensation Agreed with Iran, But No Hostage Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Wednesday announced an agreement with
Iran to pay for damage to each other's embassies in violent
incidents, but insisted it made no ``sordid deal'' to secure the
release of Britons held hostage in Lebanon.
   David Mellor, a junior minister at the Foreign Office, also said
Britain was ``more than willing'' to improve its chilly elations
with Iran, but added ``it has to be in relation to legitimate
things.''
   ``What we are not prepared to do is get involved in any sort of
sordid deal _ trading for hostages, that sort of thing,'' Mellor
said in a radio interview after the announcement.
   ``But if they want to do business of the kind we've just
concluded today, then I think that is in everybody's interest. ...
We would like to have sensible relations with Iran.''
   Iran's sole diplomat in London said the agreement was a
``technical matter.''
   ``We are following a principled position that we are accepting a
kind of normal, businesslike relationship,'' Charge d'Affaires
Mohammed Basti told reporters.
   Britain seeks the release of three of its nationals believed
held by pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists in Beirut. They are
Anglican church envoy Terry Waite, journalist John McCarthy and
teacher Brian Keenan. Keenan holds both British and Irish
nationality and the Irish government also seeks his release.
   The Foreign Office says it also seeks word on Alec Collett, a
New York-based British journalist whose Palestinian abductors claim
they killed him. His body was never found.
   They are among 18 foreign hostages held in Beirut, including
nine Americans. Longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was abducted March 16,
1985.
   Wednesday's agreement followed several weeks of negotiations
that Britain says Iran initiated ``out of the blue'' on a
compensation offer first made in 1984.
   The agreement came just two days after Basti protested to the
Foreign Office about Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's refusal to
condemn the U.S. downing of an Iranian passenger jet on Sunday in
the Persian Gulf.
   The U.S. Navy said it mistook the civilian Airbus A300 for an
Iranian F-14 fighter. All 290 people aboard the plane died.
   Wednesday's agreement calls for Britain to pay Iran $3 million
in three installments to fix the Iranian Embassy in west London's
Kensington district. Britain also will settle a $340,000 bill from
the local municipal authority for shoring up the building.
   British commandos stormed the Iranian Embassy in 1980 to rescue
hostages held by opponents of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Iran will pay Britain $1.67 million for damage to the British
Embassy and affiliated buildings in Tehran after the U.S. Embassy
and its staff were seized in November 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
