<DOCNO> AP880706-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Productivity     07-06 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Productivity,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Productivity Up 2.8 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only Japan among the world's industrial powers
bested the United States in reducing manufacturing labor costs in
absolute terms last year, the government said Wednesday.
   But measured in devalued U.S. dollars, labor costs in Japan
soared 13.5 percent campared with a 1.5 percent decline in the
United States, which had lower hourly increases in wages and
benefits than any of its nine largest industrial competitors, the
Labor Department said.
   ``Our competitiveness vis-a-vis our foreign trading partners is
definitely improving, especially after taking into account the
changes in exchange rates,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist for
the Boston Co., a New York consulting house. ``It's a step in the
right direction but we still have a long way to go.''
   U.S. manufacturers held hourly wage and benefit increases last
year to just 1.3 percent, compared with boosts of 1.4 percent in
Japan, 4.5 percent in Candada, 3.4 percent n France, 4 percent in
West Germany and 8.2 percent in Great Britain.
   But Japan improved its manufacturing productivity _ its
efficiency in churning out goods _ by 4.1 percent last year
compared with a 2.8 percent improvement in the United States, the
department's Bureau of Labor Statistics said.
   The higher Japanese productivity improvements combined with
relatively the same wage gains as in the United States reduced
Japanese labor costs for each product 2.5 percent, compared to the
1.5 percent decline in U.S. labor costs.
   France was the only other nation to reduce those labor costs in
absolute terms, by 0.2 percent. Unit labor costs all climbed in
Canada, Korea, Denmark, West Germany, Italy, Norway, Sweeden and
Great Britain.
   But after taking into account the 4.8 percent to 20.5 percent
increase in the value of foreign currencies agains the dollar, the
contrast in labor costs between the United States and its
competitors was much more dramatic.
   ``Adjusted for the sharp 1987 appreciations in foreign currency
values relative to the U.S. dollar, Japanese and European labor
costs rose about 13 percent to 25 percent,'' the Labor Department
said.
   Measured in dollars, labor costs rose 7.7 percent in Canada, 7.5
percent in Korea, 27.4 percent in Denmark, 14.9 percent in France,
23.9 percent in West Germany, 18 percent in Italy, 19 percent in
Norway, 17 percent in Sweeden and 13 percent in Great Britain.
   ``Thanks to our rising currency, many countries had to reduce
their output as a response to the tremendous rebound in our
manufacturing last year,'' said Sinai.
   ``But the decline in the industrial sectors of Japan, Great
Britain and West Germany has bottomed out and so has the dollar.
This year will not be a repeat of last,'' he warned.
   The Labor Department figures, in fact, showed that manufacturing
growth last year was slower in the United States than in Canada,
Korea, Italy and Great Britain.
   U.S. productivity improvements also were smaller than 4 percent
gains of Japan, France and Italy, 7 percent increase in Great
Britain and nearly 8 percent improvement in Norway.
   While five of the nine countries had larger 1987 productivity
increases than the United States, only Great Britain and Norway
exceeded the U.S. rate of improvement over the past two years, the
BLS said.
   However, only the United States and Canada experienced any
employment growth in manufacturing last year. The U.S. increase was
only one-half of 1 percent, but it reversed two straight years of
declines.
   Factory jobs remained abut the same in Germany and Sweeden and
fell by 1 percent to 2.5 percent in the other countries.
   For France, 1987 was the 13th consecutive year of manufacturing
employment declines and in Great Britain factory jobs have been
falling in number for the past 10 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
