<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CruisePreemie     07-06 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cruise Preemie,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Chopper Rescues Preemie From Cruise Ship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby born seven weeks prematurely aboard a cruise
ship in the Bahamas was picked up by a Coast Guard helicopter and
rushed to a hospital Wednesday, officials said.
   The 2-pound, 11-ounce girl was in serious but stable condition
at Miami Children's Hospital on Wednesday afternoon, said spokesman
Omar Montejo.
   ``All things considered, she's not doing badly,'' he said.
   The mother, Wylene McCollum, 23, was taken to Broward General
Medical Center in good condition, said that hospital's spokeswoman
Shana Safer.
   Mrs. McCollum, of Atlanta, was on a vacation cruise with her
husband, Spencer, also 23, when she went into labor, said Ms. Safer.
   The still unnamed baby was born aboard the Emerald Seas off
Little Stirrup Cay just after 10 a.m. The cruise liner makes a
regular run from Miami to the Bahamas.
   The Coast Guard in Miami rushed two H-65 Dolphin helicopters to
Children's Hospital, one to pick up the incubator and the second to
carry the medical team. The helicopters were met on Little Stirrup
Cay by a larger H-3 Pelican helicopter temporarily stationed by the
Coast Guard in the Bahamas.
   ``The baby was critical when we first arrived, but she improved
with the incubator,'' said Coast Guard spokesman Lt. Jim Mazzonna.
   The mother and baby were taken by boat from the ship to the
island, and everyone was put aboard the larger chopper, which flew
directly to Children's Hospital.
   Montejo said the baby's small size did not appear to be a
problem.
</TEXT>
