<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Iran 1stLd-Writethru a0763 07-06 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0763,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Incident Set Back Moves for Improved Ties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Deletes phrase regarding positive response from 5th graf,
``Secretary of''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. downing of an Iranian passenger plane
last Sunday seems certain to set back tentative efforts by the two
countries to have a more normal relationship, according to U.S.
officials and independent experts.
   Robin Wright, an associate at the Carnegie Endowment of
International Peace who recently visited Iran, said in an interview
Wednesday that Iran wants an opening to the West because of
economic hardship brought on by the prolonged war against Iraq as
well as declining oil prices.
   ``Iran clearly needs to open the door again,'' Wright said,
adding that after Iran's recent normalization of relations with
France, ``Britain is going to be next and then Canada.''
   She said that before last Sunday's incident, Iranian officials
sounded hopeful about the possibility of an eventual accommodation
with the United States.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said earlier this week that
before the airliner was shot down, Iranian officials had sent
messages through third parties indicating a desire to open a direct
dialogue with the United States.
   But Shultz said it is not clear whether the messages were sent
by officials in positions of authority.
   U.S. officials believe that the Iranian government may be
divided on the question of improved relations, with a some
supporting Iran's anti-U.S. Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi
and others rallying behind more moderate elements.
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
Wednesday the United States is willing to open an ``authoritative
dialogue'' with Iran but U.S. efforts to explore this possibility
``have not borne fruit.''
   This has been a long-standing U.S. position, but received little
attention until the U.S. Navy warship Vincennes shot down the
Iranian passenger plane, killing all 290 persons aboard.
   In any case, Mrs. Oakley said there can be no normal
relationship with Iran so long as the Iran-Iraq war does not end,
American hostages continue to be held by pro-Iranian militants in
Lebanon, and Iran does not halt what she described as international
terrorist activities. For its part, Iran has called Sunday's
incident ``cold-blooded murder'' and an act of international
terrorism by the United States.
   Wright said that military incidents have repeatedly thwarted
fledgling efforts by the United States and Iran to improve
relations.
   As an example, she said that Iranian officials told her that
President Carter in the spring of 1980 expressed a willingness to
recognize Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution but shortly thereafter
approved a military mission to rescue the American hostages in
Tehran. The mission ended in failure.
   There have been reports that administration officials believed
that Iran might attempt to take advantage of the current U.S.
presidential campaign to advance its diplomatic goals.
   The Wall Street Journal reported on June 10 that Robert Oakley,
the National Security Council's Middle East expert, had written an
internal memo warning of that possibility.
   The article said that Oakley was concerned that Iran might try
to entice Vice President George Bush, the presumed Republican
candidate, into a deal involving the release of nine American
hostages in return for a less hostile stance toward Iran.
   There also has been speculation that Iran may be attempting to
spread word of its interest in improved ties with the United States
as a means of shaking the confidence of Iraq and its Arab allies in
the gulf.
   One of the prime purposes of the U.S. military deployment in the
gulf is to provide reassurance to Iran's neighbors, many of which
look upon Iran as an expansionist power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
