<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0753 07-06 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0753,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Promises Hispanic in Cabinet; Dukakis Presses VP Search</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS date in 10th graf, The poll, adding ``1987;''
updates with Bush not making Cabinet promise to other groups,
subbing 2 grafs for 13th graf pvs, ``If I; updates with Jackson
comment and black leaders meeting Dukakis, subbing 3 grafs for
grafs 19-20 pvs, Jackson who ... Thursday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush promised he would name a
Hispanic-American to his Cabinet Wednesday as he sought minority
votes in Texas. Democrat Michael Dukakis searched for a running
mate and dealt with state budget deficits and other homefront
headaches.
   Bush also declared he would not apologize to Iran for the
shooting down of a jumbo jet with 290 people aboard.
   ``We probably ought to do what we did, which is to officially
express regret, which I guess should happen when you have the loss
of innocent life,'' the vice president told reporters.
   Dukakis, two weeks away from the Democratic presidential
nomination, continued to check out vice presidential prospects. He
interviewed Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana, a respected but
little-known congressman who was chairman of the House committee
that led the Iran-Contra investigation.
   Hamilton, the eighth man Dukakis has interviewed in his search,
said he would accept the No. 2 spot if offered.
   Dukakis senior aide Paul Brountas was in Washington through
Friday researching the contenders and talking to party leaders _
fueling speculation that a decision on a running mate would not
come until next week. Dukakis is to be in Washington next Wednesday
for more meetings.
   While attention focused on his search for a running mate, the
Massachusetts governor was plagued with an increasingly frustrating
budget dilemma and a new poll showing his popularity dropping at
home.
   The state government's new fiscal year began last Friday, and
Dukakis has yet to close a $450 million deficit for fiscal 1988 or
to sign a budget for the new year. He asked the Legislature for $81
million in emergency spending authority to cover state payroll and
welfare checks.
   A poll last week for WBZ-TV and The Boston Herald found Dukakis
leading Bush in the state by 14 percentage points. But it also
found 56 percent saying Dukakis has not been an effective governor
while campaigning for president and 47 percent saying he should
resign after the convention to devote his full time to the race.
   The poll, a survey of 400 Massachusetts voters conducted last
week by telephone, found Dukakis' unfavorable rating has more than
doubled, to 36 percent from 17 percent, since January 1987.
   Dukakis has already signed a new $40 million tax on cigarettes,
and more than $200 million in other new taxes are moving toward his
desk.
   Bush, preceding Dukakis by a day before a major Hispanic group
in Dallas, made the promise to name a Hispanic-American to his
Cabinet, calling it ``a pledge that I have never made before, to
anyone, to any group.''
   But he refused to make the same commitment to blacks, women or
other groups. ``Other groups have been represented in the Cabinet
and Hispanics have not. ... I'm addressing myself to righting a
wrong that has been out there for many years,'' he said.
   ``It is time. It is time and it's long overdue, and that is a
solemn pledge,'' Bush said.
   Bush addressed the annual convention of the League of United
Latin American Citizens, or LULAC, an umbrella organization of
Hispanic groups.
   Dukakis will speak to the group Thursday night at the first stop
on a swing that will take him to five Western states. He planned
appearances with one of his potential vice presidential candidates,
Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, in Texarkana, and with a former
presidential candidate, former Gov. Bruce Babbitt, in Arizona.
   Bush, talking to reporters aboard Air Force II on the way to
Texas, said it was too early to decide whether the United States
should pay compensation to the families of passengers killed in
Sunday's shooting down of an Iranian civilian jetliner.
   He said ``I wouldn't, because of the facts,'' offer an apology
to the Iranians _ even though President Reagan agreed that his own
statement of regret amounted to an apology.
   Jesse Jackson, still technically a presidential candidate
although Dukakis' nomination is assured, renewed his call for more
money to battle drugs while at an appearance in New York. He
stopped at a Harlem center providing treatment for infants born
addicted to heroin or other drugs.
   Jackson renewed his call for the United States to pay
compensation to the Iranian airliner victims and said there should
be a period of mourning showing ``sincere and clear and
unequivocal'' regret.
   Dukakis, in Boston, met with civil rights leaders including
NAACP executive director Benjamin Hooks and Coretta Scott King,
widow of Martin Luther King Jr.
   ``I cannot recall an issue he disagreed with us on,'' Hooks said.
   Dukakis also was addressing the Greek Orthodox Ecumenical
Congress, which was holding its convention in Boston. Dukakis is a
member of the Greek Orthodox church. Bush was planning to address
the group on Thursday.
   A surrogate campaigner for Bush, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., held
a news conference at the Statehouse in Boston to attack Dukakis on
his home turf. He criticized as ``indefensible'' a Massachusetts
furlough program _ later amended _ that allowed the release of a
first-degree murderer who escaped and raped a Maryland woman.
   But Specter was upstaged by local supporters of Dukakis,
including Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, who stepped in to
defend Dukakis at the news conference and to say Bush had been a
failure in leading the Reagan administration's anti-drug efforts.
</TEXT>
