<HEAD>Administration Planning To Sell Stinger Missiles To Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has notified
Congress of its intention to sell Greece 1,000 Stinger
anti-aircraft missiles worth $124 million, the Pentagon said
Wednesday.
   The prime contractor for the handheld Stinger missiles will be
the General Dynamics Corp. Valley Systems Division of Rancho
Cucamonga, Calif.
   In addition to the missiles, the sale will include training and
training equipment, and devices known as ``identify friend or foe''
components to discern friendly from enemy aircraft, the
announcement said.
   Greece, a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, will
``have no difficulty absorbing these systems into its armed
forces'' and the sale ``will have no adverse impact on U.S. defense
readiness,'' the Pentagon said in its announcement.
