<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan-Hijack     07-06 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Hijack,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Palestinians Sentenced To Hang, Convicted In Pan Am Hijacking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADIYALA, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Palestinians were convicted and
sentenced to death Wednesday in the 1986 hijacking of a Pan Am
jetliner that left 21 people dead, including an Indian-American, a
local government official said.
   Judge Mohammad Zafar Barbar sentenced the defendants in a
makeshift courtroom in a prison in this town 30 miles west of
Islamabad. He blamed lax airport security in part for the
hijacking, in which four of the Palestinians entered the plane
dressed as security guards.
   The Boeing 747 on a stopover between Bombay, India, and New
York, was seized on the ground Sept. 5, 1986, in Pakistan's
southern port of Karachi with 400 people aboard, including 44
Americans.
   It sat on the tarmac for 17 hours before the Palestinians,
fearing an attack when an onboard generator ran out, sprayed the
cabin with bullets and Pakistani troops stormed the plane.
   The defendants contended they were innocent in the murders and
blamed Pakistani commandos for the killings. Two hundred others
were injured.
   ``We don't care about the sentence,'' said Mohammad Hafiz Turk,
32, the only one of the five who was not on the hijacked plane. He
was sentenced to hang for his part in planning the hijacking. ``We
care only about the millions of Arabs and Islamic countries.''
   The other four _ Mohammad Ahmed Munawar, Khalil Hussain Rahayyal
and Saeed Abdul Rahim of Lebanon, and Abdul Latif Sairfani of Syria
_ were sentenced to hang for their role in the hijacking. They also
were sentenced to 10 consecutive life sentences or 250 years in
prison for the deaths of 10 of the 21 passengers. Three of the four
men received an additional life sentence in an 11th death, that of
the Indian-American.
   The four men, ranging in age from 18-24, also were fined nearly
$2,800 in each murder conviction. Half the money will be given to
relatives of the hijack victims.
   In Washington, the State Department welcomed the convictions.
   ``The Pakistan court decision is an important action in bringing
the rule of law to bear against terrorists,'' said a statement read
by spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
   The five said they will appeal their convictions and sentences
within the 30-day deadline.
   Libya and the Palestine Liberation Organization both denied any
involvement in the hijacking.
   In an interview following the sentencing, Turk, ringleader of
the group, said if free ``we would hijack another plane.''
   Pan Am was targeted because it is a U.S. carrier, he said.
   ``By using Pan American it was a strike against America,'' Turk
said.
   But he explained ``we are friends to American people. We are
against the administration and the crazy man in New York or
Washington, wherever he is.'' He was referring to President Reagan.
   During sentencing, Barbar said ``security (at the airport)
seemed to be extremely lax.'' The judge questioned how the four men
dressed as security guards could board the Pan Am flight weighed
down with weapons and ammunition.
   The hijackers, he said, ``were able to collect huge caches of
ammunition unnoticed and unhindered.''
   As a result of the sentencings authorities tightened security in
Karachi.
   ``The Karachi administration along with the airport authorities
have increased the security staff at the Karachi airport, Pan Am
office and the United States Consulate,'' said Commissioner Shahid
Aziz Siddiqui.
   ``More armed police (are) posted around the American cultural
center and (we are) more vigilant of Arab students living in
Karachi,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
