<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Blind-Airlines     07-06 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blind-Airlines,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blind Humiliated By Airlines, Advocate Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blind people face harassment, humiliation and
possible arrest on airplanes, and proposed federal rules may fail
to protect them against discrimination, the executive director of
the National Federation of the Blind said Wednesday.
   Kenneth Jernigan told more than 2,500 people attending the
annual meeting of the federation that proposed U.S. Department of
Transportation regulations would allow the Federal Aviation
Administration to treat blind people differently from other
passengers.
   Each airline has its own rules about where blind and other
disabled passengers should sit, how they should board and whether
they can keep their guide dogs and canes with them.
   ``Today, the situation is such that no blind person anywhere in
the country can board a plane without fear of harassment, public
humiliation and possibly arrest and bodily injury,'' Jernigan said.
   The Transportation Department last week published nine proposed
rules to govern all airlines' policies, said Matthew Scocozza,
assistant transportation secretary for policy.
   The federation has long argued that a policy held by many
airlines that restricts blind passengers from sitting in emergency
exit rows is discriminatory.
   Scocozza said in a speech to the convention that he agreed with
the federation's position that many blind people are capable of
sitting in an exit row and handling an emergency situation.
   Under one of the proposed rules, no passenger could be required
to sit in a certain area of the plane, ``except where required by
an FAA safety rule,'' Scocozza told a predominantly blind audience
of more than a thousand.
   Jernigan suggested the proposed rule may fail to stop the
humiliations some members of his federation have experienced on
airlines.
   But Scocozza said, ``If nothing else, it's (the rule) a start
that's 30 years too late.''
   In April, James Gashel, an officer of the federation, was taken
into custody on a charge of criminal trespass after he refused to
leave his seat in an emergency exit row of a United Airlines flight.
   United spokesman Joe Hopkins said Wednesday that the airline has
a policy against seating blind passengers in an exit row because in
an emergency, a blind person could not assess the situation on the
other side of the door as well as a sighted person could.
   ``Let's say there's a fire on the other side, a blind person
wouldn't be able to see that,'' Hopkins said.
   Scocozza said the proposed regulations also would:
   _Allow airlines to refuse service only upon a showing that a
patron couldn't be carried safely.
   _Bar single-flight limits on the number of disabled passengers.
   _Bar requirements for disabled people to travel with an
attendant.
   _Bar requirements of advance notice for flights by the
handicapped unless special equipment is needed.
   _Allow guide dogs to travel with their masters, instead of in
baggage holds.
   _Allow the disabled to reject services they don't want, such as
preboarding and safety explanations in Braille.
   Scocozza estimated the overall cost to the airlines of
implementing the rules at $750 million.
   He said the rules were open for comment and could be implemented
by the end of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
