<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Airliner-Gulf 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 07-06 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Gulf, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,0867</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Team Begins Probe of Airbus Downing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th pvs, `Javier Perez ...' to UPDATE
with announcements of U.N. meetings; DELETES superseded 16th graf
pvs, `Iran has...' PICKS up 17th pvs bgng, `An unanswered question
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American investigators began their
inquiry Wednesday into the shooting down of an Iranian airliner by
questioning senior officers of the cruiser that fired the fatal
missiles, U.S. sources said.
   The six-member military team of experts arrived from the United
States late Tuesday and began their confidential task under a
15-day deadline, which U.S. officers said could be extended.
   Leading the group is Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty, a senior
staff officer at U.S. Central Command headquarters in Tampa, Fla.
It includes a lawyer and technical experts who will analyze
computer tapes, communications records and other data that could
explain the tragedy.
   Iran says the USS Vincennes, a billion-dollar Aegis cruiser with
computerized radar and weapons systems, intentionally shot down the
Iran Air Airbus A300 over the Strait of Hormuz on Sunday. All 290
people aboard were killed.
   It has accused the United States of premeditated mass murder and
pledged revenge in ``the same blood-spattered skies'' over the
Persian Gulf, where Iran and Iraq have been at war since September
1980.
   The United States says the Vincennes fired because signals sent
by one of two airliner's transponders were were analyzed in its
combat information center as being from an F-14 fighter on an
attack bearing.
   Iranians shouting ``Death to America!'' and waving banners
vowing revenge held funerals Wednesday for 24 of the victims at
Bandar Abbas, where the flight originated, and in Zahedan.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar, U.N. secretary-general, spent an hour
in Geneva with Mohammed Javad Larijani, deputy foreign minister of
Iran. Neither side would comment about the meeting.
   In New York, the United Nations announced Wednesday that the
Security Council will convene on the issue July 12, at Iran's
request. It said the Montreal-based International Civil Aviation
Organization will meet the following day on Iran's demand for an
inquiry. American officials said the United States would cooperate
with an investigation by the U.N. agency.
   U.S. military sources said the team's first order of business
was to interview Capt. Will C. Rogers III, skipper of the
Vincennes, and other officers who were present as he watched the
crisis develop on a huge blue video screen and gave the order to
shoot.
   American officials said earlier the officers would be under
oath. They said the investigators' mandate does not exclude
recommending disciplinary action if there appears to be grounds for
it.
   Navy officials would not divulge the whereabouts of the
9,600-ton cruiser, but one said privately it was ``a reasonable
assumption'' the Vincennes had anchored off Bahrain overnight. If
so, it was far enough out to be invisible from shore through the
haze.
   All aspects of the investigation will remain secret while it is
in progress, U.S. officials said.
   Fogarty, who once commanded the battleship New Jersey, is
director of plans and policy for the Central Command,
administrative headquarters for U.S. military affairs in 19
countries of the Middle East and North Africa.
   His team was met in Bahrain by Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less,
commander of the U.S. Joint Task Force Middle East, which includes
the approximately 29 U.S. warships opeating in the gulf and Arabian
Sea.
   A senior U.S. officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
it was ``highly doubtful'' investigators would be able to talk to
Iranian officials.
   An unanswered question is why the Airbus was not diverted from
the area of a skirmish involving the Vincennes, the frigate Elmer
Montgomery and several armed Iranian speedboats.
   Initially, the U.S. Navy report said two speedboats were sunk, a
third was damaged and The Vincennes shot down an Iranian F-14
fighter. The plane later proved to be the Iran Air jet, which was
on a scheduled flight to Dubai from a combined military-civilian
airport at Bandar Abbas.
   The battle was the first direct encounter between U.S. warships
and Iranian armed craft since April 18, when U.S. attacks on two
Iranian oil platforms in reprisal for the mining of a Navy frigate
started a day of combat in which six Iranian craft were sunk or
disabled.
   One theory in gulf diplomatic and aviation circles is that an
Iranian F-14 was using the Airbus as radar ``cover'' to approach
the American ships.
   A U.S. official, also speaking privately, said he had no
evidence for the speculation, which is expected to be among
questions the U.S. investigators will try to resolve.
   In Washington, Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., said Pentagon officials
were examining ``the possibility'' of a second plane, but a Navy
spokesman, Lt. Brian Cullin, said: ``We do not believe there was
another aircraft in the area.''
   Aspin, chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, said
Defense Department officials told a closed briefing a ``wide range
of possibilities'' was under study, including the possibility of
``a military plane that was somehow masked'' by the airliner.
</TEXT>
