<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Caricom     07-06 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caricom,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caribbean Leaders Draft Letter To Protest U.S. Interference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caribbean leaders were preparing a
letter to President Reagan on Wednesday accusing his administration
of impinging on the sovereignty of other nations in anti-drug
campaign in order to attract votes in an election year.
   A draft letter protesting U.S. drug policy in the Caribbean was
circulated among leaders of 13 member nations of the Carribean
Common Market and Commmunity, or Caricom, holding a five-day annual
summit meeting in St. John's.
   Lester Bird, deputy prime minister of Antigua and Barbuda,
acting as spokesman for the group, said a second draft of the
letter accused the United States of ``derogation'' of the Caribbean
nations' laws.
   ``They feel that the domestic imperatives of an election year in
America have forced certain people in certain parts of the American
process to step beyond what is acceptable in terms of ... the
sovereignty of a country,'' Bird said after the closed-door morning
session. He gave no specific examples.
   The U.S. attempt to stop the flow of drugs into the United
States through the Caribbean has become a key issue at the summit.
   At opening ceremonies Monday, Prime Minister Lynden Pindling of
the Bahamas denounced the United States for what he called
politically motivated intervention in certain countries. He
suggested he was made a ``scapegoat'' for failing to stop drugs
from reaching the United States through his archipelago of more
than 700 islands.
   For years, Pindling has been the target of allegations that he
personally benefited from the drug trade.
   On Tuesday, the leaders unanimously agreed to condemn the United
States for what they considered interference in their countries and
in Panama. The Reagan administration sought the ouster of Panama's
de facto ruler, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, after his indictment
in Florida on federal drug charges.
   Bird said Wednesday the prime ministers' stance was not meant to
protect any one government, although it might have the ``spinoff''
effect of doing so.
   He said Caribbean leaders condemn the drug trade and in many
cases are working directly with U.S. drug enforcement authorities,
but cooperation should not be abused by interfering with their
rights to run their own affairs.
   ``There are agreements which lay out the procedure in which
working closely can be achieved without affecting the integrity of
your own institutions,'' he said. ``That's the issue that's at
point here _ the whole question of extraterritorial jurisdiction.''
   It remained unclear whether the Caricom leaders would take a
position on the Haitian government of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, who
seized power in a military coup June 19. Haiti has observer status
in Caricom.
   The 13 Caricom nations are Antigua-Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados,
Belize, Dominica, Grenada, Guyana, Jamaica, Montserrat, St.
Kitts-Nevis, St. Lucia, St. Vincent and Trinidad-Tobago.
</TEXT>
