<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Shooting,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Rejects Official Explanation For Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Elections Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas challenged the government's claim that one of his key
strategists and an aide were killed by the criminal underworld, not
political assassins.
   He said Wednesday he still believes Francisco Ovando Hernandez
and Ovando's aide, Roman Gil Heraldez, were victims of
``reactionary elements'' bent on provoking election violence.
   Cardenas, candidate of the leftist National Democratic Front
coalition, spoke with reporters while waiting to vote in the
national election.
   Hours before the polls opened for the most hotly contested race
in decades, federal district police officials said they had
discarded a political motive for the slayings Saturday night.
   They blamed criminals seeking revenge for Ovando's work as
Michoacan state attorney general when Cardenas, then still a member
of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, was governor of
the state.
   ``I don't consider that to be the truth,'' Cardenas said
Wednesday.
   Opposition parties claim the ruling party, known as the PRI for
its initials in spanish, has used intimidation, voter manipulation
and fraud to stay in power since it was founded in 1929.
   President Miguel de la Madrid promised the nation the murder
case would be solved quickly.
   Jorge Obrador Capellini, director of the Federal District
Judicial Police, went on national television Tuesday night to
announce the results of the 3-day-old investigation.
   He said police had more than a dozen suspects, none of whom had
been arrested. He named three people, two of them prison inmates,
as the masterminds.
   Cardenas said Wednesday there was ``no reason to believe that
these people he is naming could have been the ones'' who ordered
the killings.
   Ovando, 41, and Heraldez, 28, were shot to death while driving
home from a political meeting. Party officials have said
confidential documents outlining the Cardenas coalition's plans to
monitor the voting were missing from their car.
   Obrador Capellini said the murders were timed to make them look
like a political crime.
   He said several Michoacan law enforcement officials had been
murdered by the same criminal gang and outlined criminal
prosecutions in the state that he said provided motives for the
slayings.
   Cardenas rejected this theory. He said Ovando had little to do
with the cases mentioned when he was attorney general from
September 1980 to June 1981.
   The murders showed voters how far ``some of the most reactionary
sectors'' are willing to go to stop the opposition, he said. Most
polls have shown Cardenas running a strong second to the PRI
candidate, Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   Ovando, a longtime friend and political associate of Cardenas,
was in charge of the coalition plan for monitoring the election for
fraud. He was buried Tuesday in Michoacan state.
</TEXT>
