<HEAD>Secretary of State to Discuss Cambodia, Refugees</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Two grafs SUB for 10th graf pvs, ``In our ... UPDATING with
Japanese arrival. Picks up 11th graf pvs, At their ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
begins talks Thursday with Southeast Asian leaders on Cambodia's
future, the Vietnamese boat people and U.S.-Asian trade problems.
   Shultz arrived in the Thai capital Wednesday at the start of a
nine-country trip through Asia and the Pacific. He was greeted by
tight security, expected to be a feature of his entire stay.
   Also on Shultz's Asian agenda are the fate of U.S. military
bases in the Philippines, security at the upcoming Olympics in
Seoul and development of democracy in South Korea.
   A senior Thai military officer said special precautions were
being taken because of Sunday's shooting down of an Iranian
airliner by U.S. missiles in the Persian Gulf. Iran has threatened
revenge, and Asian officials and journalists are likely to ask
Shultz for explanations of the incident.
   The Malaysian Foreign Ministry Tuesday said it deplored the
American action, adding it was difficult to believe or accept U.S.
claims that its forces mistook the large civilian aircraft for a
military one.
   The Thai officer, who requested anonymity, said sharpshooters
were included in a security task force which includes police, air
force and army personnel. Reporters were barred from the military
section of Bangkok's international airport where the secretary's
official aircraft landed.
   Shultz's two-week journey will be his last and longest to Asia
as secretary of state. After Thailand, he goes to Malaysia,
Indonesia, the Philippines, Hong Kong, China, South Korea, Japan
and the new Marshall Islands Republic in the Pacific.
   On Thursday, Shultz will take part in a dialogue among the six
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and
Japan, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, Australia and the European
Economic Community.
   He is expected to stress that the United States adamantly
rejects a return to power in Cambodia by the Khmer Rouge, a message
that will be repeated in Beijing, which supplies the guerrillas
with weapons.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno of Japan also arrived in Bangkok on
Wednesday.
   Japanese Foreign Ministry officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, say Uno will tell the SEATO foreign ministers Japan will
do more to expand trade and investment in the region. He also is
expected to express support for peace efforts in Cambodia by ASEAN.
   At their annual conference here earlier this week, the ASEAN
ministers sidestepped the Khmer Rouge problem, focusing instead on
a total withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and plans for
a politial settlement of the war.
   Fear of a return by the Khmer Rouge, who turned Cambodia into a
killing field during their 1975-78 rule, has been sparked by an
ongoing partial Vietnamese troop withdrawal and Hanoi's pledge to
end its military presence in Cambodia by 1990.
   Vietnam drove the Khmer Rouge from power in 1979.
   Shultz will be meeting here with Prince Norodom Sihanouk, whom
the United States supports but who leads a three-party
anti-Vietnamese resistance which also includes the Khmer Rouge.
   The ASEAN ministers have said they would ask the United States
and other countries to accept more Indochinese refugees who
continue to flee to Southeast Asia from Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos.
   Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia and Hong Kong have recently
toughened their policies on providing Vietnamese ``boat people''
with temporary asylum. Washington has criticized the moves.
   The U.S. government says it is committed to accepting 29,500
Indochinese refugees from first asylum countries for resettlement
this fiscal year. It has accepted more than 900,000 since 1975,
including 32,000 last year.
   In China, Shultz will express American concern about a reported
flow of Chinese missiles to ``hot spots'' in the Middle East,
sources in Washington said.
   Shultz expects to deliver a major speech in Seoul July 18 on
expanding democracy and human rights in South Korea. There also
will be discussions on the running of a trouble-free Olympics,
which begin in the South Korean capital Sept. 17.
   American use of Philippine military bases will probably be aired
in Bangkok as well as Manila, where negotiations over their future
is continuing. As a bloc, ASEAN has refused to take a stand on the
issue but most individual members want a solid U.S. military
presence in the region to offset Soviet power.
   Trade issues and Japan's emerging role as both a political and
economic force in Asia are likely to feature in discussions in
Tokyo, Shultz's last stop on the Asian continent.
</TEXT>
