<HEAD>OPEC, Non-Members Discuss Oil Output Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday that
OPEC and non-member oil producers are discussing ways to reduce
world output in an effort to boost depressed prices.
   Venezuela's delegate to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, Felix Rossi Guerrero, said the possibility of a special
OPEC meeting ``cannot be discounted.''
   ``We are worried by the situation and we are sure the other OPEC
members are too, so consultations and the exchange of opinions
between OPEC and non-OPEC members to find a solution should not
seem surprising,'' he said. ``If this situation is not modified the
outlook will be very negative.''
   A regular OPEC ministerial meeting is scheduled for November.
The last regular conference was held last month in Vienna.
