<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teachers-GayCounseling     07-06 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teachers-Gay Counseling,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEA Backs School Counseling For Gay Students</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the National Education
Association's annual convention approved a resolution Wednesday
urging all school districts to provide counseling for students
struggling with their sexual identities.
   The resolution was adopted after a stormy debate by a standing
vote of the 8,227 delegates attending the NEA's annual convention
here.
   The two-sentence measure put the 1.9-million member teacher
union on record in favor of all persons, regardless of sexual
orientation, having equal opportunity within the public school
system.
   It added: ``The Association further believes that every school
district should provide counseling for students who are struggling
with their sexual-gender orientation.''
   John Walters, chief of staff to U.S. Education Secretary William
J. Bennett said the resolution neglected the primary role of
parents in guiding children in such sensitive matters.
   ``Schools have a big enough job teaching basics like reading and
math and character,'' he said.
   Speaking in favor of the measure, NEA Secretary-Treasurer
Roxanne Bradshaw said she knew a young girl who attempted suicide
and wound up in a comma because of her distress over her sexual
identity.
   Indiana teacher-delegate Art Daniel said, ``It is not the intent
of this resolution to encourage a gay or lesbian orientation, but
to help children accept and deal with their orientation whatever it
may be.''
   Those who spoke against the measure argued that existing union
positions on civil rights, counseling and other matters adequately
covered the concerns raised in the resolution.
</TEXT>
