<DOCNO> AP880706-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Namibia-Bombing     07-06 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia-Bombing,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode in Windhoek</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ A bomb killed a black man and
wounded 18 people at a butcher shop in an affluent white area
Wednesday and a second bomb wrecked an army truck in a black
township 11 hours later, police reported.
   Police said no one was hurt at Katatura black township, on the
outskirts of Windhoek, when an explosive device was thrown under a
parked army truck at about 10:20 p.m.
   Col. Jumbo Smith, a police spokesman, said the explosion blew
out house windows and shock waves woke people miles away.
   Two victims of the first bomb were in critical condition and
four were hurt badly, including a woman who lost a leg, police
spokesman Kierie du Rand said.
   He said it appeared the bomb was inside a parcel left in the
shop. Du Rand said most of the wounded were black, although the
shop is in a white area.
   Witnesses said an adjoining store was damaged and broken glass
and other debris littered the street.
   No group claimed responsibility for either explosion but police
blamed the South West African People's Organization, a guerrilla
group that began fighting 21 years ago for independence in the
territory, also known as Namibia.
   ``I have no doubt in my mind that SWAPO is responsible,'' du
Rand said.
   South Africa captured the territory from Germany in World War I
and was given a League of Nations mandate over it. The United
Nations abrogated the mandate more than 20 years ago, but the South
Africans have refused to leave.
   The deadliest bombing in the guerrilla war occurred Feb. 19,
when an explosion at a bank in the north-central town of Oshakati
killed 27 people.
</TEXT>
