   Under federal rules, Jennifer cannot fly solo until she is 16
and cannot receive a pilot's license until age 17, her father said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oat bran can't boast the glamour of sushi, the
glitz of kiwi fruit or the rich taste of gelato. But oat bran does
reduce blood cholesterol, a fact that has produced a sevenfold boom
in sales.
   The Home Economist, a bulk food store in suburban Arlington
Heights, has been out of oat bran for a month and manager Karen
Shinville doesn't know when she will get more.
   ``We'd sell 50 to 75 pounds a day. People would buy huge bags of
it,'' said Shinville. ``It's phenomenal.''
   That comes as little surprise to Quaker Oats Co., the
Chicago-based food conglomerate that is the world's biggest
commercial oat bran producer.
   ``Between March 1987 and March 1988, sales shot up 784
percent,'' said company spokeswoman Cheryl Halloran. Oat bran can
be used as a cereal or as an ingredient in muffins, cakes, breads
or other foods, she said.
   Studies show that a daily bowl of bran cereal or a bran muffin
can reduce the risk of heart attack by nearly 40 percent in people
with high blood cholesterol levels. And oat bran, made from the
outer covering of oats, is one of the most efficient of the
water-soluble fibers.
   ``The last two or three weeks it's been a particularly strong
seller,'' said David Savage, manager of the Bread Shop in Chicago.
   ``I think the cholesterol thing was the topic on the `Oprah
Winfrey' (television) show recently,'' he added. ``And then, people
figure the drought might drive prices way up.''
   Despite its health aspect, Shinville says she's not likely to
join the fad.
   ``I've tasted it,'' she said. ``It tastes like real bland
cereal.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GOSHEN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indiana company is making a new type of
trash bag that won't last long _ and that should be good news for
the environment.
   Gary Weaver, vice president of Rollpak Corp., said his company
makes plastic trash bags made of 7 percent corn starch. The corn
starch is bonded with the complex plastic compound polyethylene.
When soil bacteria and fungi consume the starch, the polyethylene
crumbles into dust that the organisms can break down readily.
   The new bags degrade in two to three years, Weaver said.
Conventional plastic bags may last 100 years or more, and some
plastics take 300 to 400 years to degrade, he said.
   Several communities nationwide have passed ordinances forbidding
the use of plastic trash bags that are not biodegradable, Weaver
said. Nevertheless, Rollpak, a subsidiary of a Swedish company,
doesn't expect big orders soon because the new bags cost 10 percent
to 10 percent more than other bags, he said.
   Ramani Narayan, a chemical engineer at Purdue University, says
research there may produce plastics containing 30 percent corn
starch that break down in 15 months.
   The technology can be applied to a broad range of plastics and
conserve municipal landfill space, he said. Conventional plastics
accounts for about 30 percent of landfill volume and could rise to
40 percent by the year 2000, he said.
</TEXT>
