<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     07-06 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grosz Calls For Openness In Media; Poverty Statistics Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz
called for more openness in news media Wednesday as newspapers for
the first time bared statistical data showing more than 2.5 million
Hungarians lived in virtual poverty last year.
   Grosz said in an article Wednesday in the communist daily
Nepszabadsag that he was ``deeply impressed'' while visiting Moscow
with the openness of the Soviet press and said ``the Hungarian
media can report on anything but military secrets.''
   He told the newspaper that a meeting of the party Central
Committee set for July 13 would receive extensive coverage. The
official news agency MTI reported from Moscow on Tuesday that Grosz
announced at a news conference there that the meeting would be
broadcast live on Hungarian television and radio.
   Party proceedings have traditionally been conducted behind
closed doors.
   In other stories, Nepszabadsag and the trade union daily
Nepszava said 18 percent of the population lived below ``the social
minimum income level'' in 1987, and 6 percent below ``the living
minimum level.''
   Nepszava noted that ``for a long time, a certain `official
shyness' prevented even the idea of a `minimum wage' to appear
publicly in the media. Also for a long time, there was no such
thing as `poor people' in this country, while there were many who
knew it from experience.''
   ``Social minimum'' was defined as an income level that, in
addition to the most basic needs, allows very modest spending on
some goods and services that are considered requirements ``of the
masses.'' ``Living standard minimum'' only allows paying for bare
necessities.
   In 1987, 1.9 million Hungarians lived beneath the first and
660,000 below the second minimum living standard.
</TEXT>
