<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Norway-Woerner     07-06 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Norway-Woerner,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Chief Says Alliance Should Agree Soon on Negotiating Position</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO's new secretary-general, Manfred
Woerner, said Wednesday he hoped the alliance would soon agree on a
negotiating position for talks on conventional weapons with Warsaw
Pact countries.
   As soon as the 16-member North Atlantic Treaty Organization has
agreed on a position, efforts should begin to get talks started, he
told a news conference.
   The former West German defense minister spoke during a one-day
trip to Norway, his first visit to a NATO country since he took
over the top civilian post in the alliance last Friday.
   He said talks with states of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact should
focus on erasing the weapons imbalance and then seeking cuts. NATO
claims Warsaw Pact countries have an advantage over the alliance in
conventional weapons.
   Woerner said the next step should be for the Soviet Union to
structure its forces so it would be incapable of a surpise attack
or a large-scale offensive against the West.
   Woerner said his most important task as secretary-general would
be to foster coherence, unity and strength in NATO.
   He returned to Brussels later Wednesday.
</TEXT>
