<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-06 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midwest Bakes, Gulf Coast Soaks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hot weather baked the Midwest and set records from Pennsylvania
to Wisconsin Wednesday while thunderstorms soaked parts of the Gulf
Coast.
   The heaviest storms hit the Texas Gulf Coast and Florida. Storms
dumped more than 2\ inches of rain on Vero Beach, Fla., in the six
hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT, while Galveston, Texas, received over an
inch.
   Rain also was scattered over the Rockies, western Minnesota and
northern New England.
   The rest of the country stayed dry and temperatures soared into
the 90s and low 100s from the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper
Ohio Valley.
   The mercury hit 101 degrees in Flint, Mich., breaking the old
record for the date and equalling the city's all-time high
established on Aug. 24, 1947, and tied recently on June 25.
   Other highs for the date included 101 degrees in Williamsport,
Pa.; 100 in Grand Rapids, Mich. and South Bend, Ind.; 99 in Fort
Wayne, Ind.; and 98 in Milwaukee.
   The desert Southwest also baked with temperatures in the 100s
while the Pacific Northwest stayed cool in the 60s.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 55 degrees at Everett,
Wash., to 102 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz. The nation's low Wednesday
morning was 29 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   Several overnight lows were set in the Southeast and the
Northwest, including 36 degrees in Yakima, Wash.; 45 in Lewiston,
Idaho, and Pendleton, Ore.; and 52 in Asheville, N.C.
   Thursday's forecast included scattered showers and thunderstorms
over the Great Plains, the southern Rockies, the lower Mississippi
Valley, Florida and the Northern Atlantic Coast states. Rain is
expected to be heaviest in Louisiana and extreme eastern Texas and
across southern Florida. Sunny skies were predicted for the rest of
the nation, with windy conditions in the northern Plains.
   Highs were expected to be in the upper 80s and 90s across much
of the nation, with temperatures reaching 100 degrees in parts of
the middle Mississippi Valley and soaring to as high as 110 in the
desert Southwest. Highs were forecast to be in the 70s from Montana
to Washington and along the Pacific Coast.
</TEXT>
