<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LockheedFraud 1stLd-Writethru a0765 07-06 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lockheed Fraud, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0765,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Charges Lockheed Workers Abused Government Contracts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with plaintiffs' news conference, Lockheed
comment. Adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Lockheed Missiles & Space Co.
used government computers to run a football pool, built a private
airplane at public expense and billed the government for the time
it took to write the entire Bible into a computer, according to a
lawsuit unsealed Wednesday.
   ``I think we're looking at the tip of an iceberg as far as
secret and top-secret programs go,'' said Margaret A. Newsham, 45,
a former employee of Lockheed and one of the plaintiffs. ``As we
delve into this, I believe we'll find a lot more.''
   ``We expect additional people to step forward and disclose
additional examples of waste and fraud,'' said Guy T. Saperstein,
the Oakland-based lawyer for the plaintiffs.
   The violations that the suit says occurred at one California
plant cost the government more than $10 million, Saperstein said.
   If proven, the charges could result in suspension of defense
contracts to Lockheed Missiles & Space, which employs 23,700
workers in Sunnyvale developing spacecraft, satellite systems and
submarine-launched missiles. It is a subsidiary of Lockheed Corp.,
one of the nation's largest defense contractors.
   Newsham, who appeared at a news conference Wednesday to discuss
the suit, was fired as a computer software analyst by Lockheed
Missiles in 1984 for allegedly padding her time card. The dismissal
is the subject of another suit that is expected to come to trial
this year.
   She was joined in the current suit by Martin Overbeek Bloem, 34,
an engineer who still works for the company.
   The suit charged that some employees skipped work, partied and
ran their own businesses at government expense while waiting for
security clearances for top secret contracts.
   Lockheed spokesman George Mulhern said company officials will
comment on the individual allegations when they receive a copy of
the suit.
   ``But we very vigorously deny that false claims have been or are
made or condoned by the company,'' Mulhern said. ``In fact, we've
had a very strong program over the past several years to make sure
all employees know any form of mischarging is wrong and can lead to
disciplinary action, including dismissal, if warranted.
   ``We are also are very confident the suit, if it goes to trial,
will show the company has not engaged in any improper practices,''
he said.
   Saperstein said he would seek an order from federal court so he
could serve Lockheed with a copy of the suit, which was filed in
U.S. District Court in San Jose in January under the False Claims
Act.
   The Civil War-era federal law, which was strengthened with
amendments in 1986, allows whistle-blowers to keep some of the
judgments against companies convicted of cheating the government.
   Saperstein said such suits are kept secret for 60 days to allow
the Justice Department time to consider action. He said he released
the information on Wednesday after granting the Justice Department
two extensions.
   ``They still haven't made up their minds,'' he said.
   The suit said one senior manager at the plant, using government
charge numbers, had Lockheed machinists build him an airplane. He
was allowed to retire when the project was discovered, and he took
the plane with him, the suit alleged.
   ``(And) one Lockheed employee wrote out the entire Bible onto a
Lockheed computer, charging government contracts for his time,''
the suit claims.
   Newsham and Bloem, according to the suit, held special security
clearances from the National Security Agency, the code-breaking and
surveillance branch of the Defense Department.
   They worked at Lockheed on a project identified in the suit only
as P-285, from 1981 to 1984. The suit says the project was part of
the Pentagon's ``black budget,'' which involves projects so secret
that their funding is classified.
   The suit claims that Lockheed workers waiting for security
clearances were sent to the ``ice box,'' an unclassified area where
they had nothing to do.
   But while employees were there, some allegedly used Lockheed
computers and charged time to government contracts to run
businesses that included selling real estate, honey, stocks,
cosmetics, diet food, jewelry, belt buckles and cable television
decoders.
   Mulhern denied the allegation that employees waiting for
security clearances are given little or nothing to do.
   Newsham and Bloem claim employees were told that even if they
worked less than a full week, to bill various government contracts
for 40 hours. They also claim that Lockheed officials told
employees to charge their time to contracts on which they had not
worked.
   Newsham complained about the alleged abuses to a Lockheed
supervisor, who then threatened to fire her, the suit said.
   The Defense Contract Audit Agency, however, investigated the
allegations and substantiated them after Newsham called a Defense
Department hot line in 1984, the suit said. Reports from the agency
were filed with Newsham and Bloem's suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
