<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kuwait-Iran     07-06 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Iran,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Kuwait in Friendly Messages over Airbus Incident</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner-Gulf, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait and Iran, their relations strained by
Iran's repeated threats to this Persian Gulf Arab nation, were
reported Wednesday to have exchanged friendly notes since the
weekend downing of the Iranian airliner.
   Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Al-Ahmed received a written message
from Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, thanking him on
behalf of the Tehran government for condolences Kuwait offered
after the U.S. Navy shot down the Iran Air A300 Airbus on Sunday
with 290 people on board.
   An official Kuwaiti statement said Velayati's message also
expressed condolences ``for the loss of a number of ... (Kuwaiti)
nationals in the incident.'' Thirty-eight non-Iranians were among
the passengers.
   The statement said Sabah sent a reply to Velayati thanking Iran
for its condolences.
   ``Sheik Sabah underscored the gravity of such an incident which
necessitates investigation that would determine its causes and its
circumstances, and prevent its repetition,'' the statement said.
   The messages contained no direct reference to nearly 8-year-old
war between Iran and Iraq.
   Iran has often accused Kuwait of actively aiding Iraq in the
war. In the past years it fired missiles into Kuwaiti territory and
menaced this tiny country's oil shipments in the gulf.
   Iran also has been accused of backing Shiite Moslem saboteurs,
blamed for bombings in Kuwait over the past five yeras.
   The radical Al-Rai Al-Aam newspaper meanwhile urged Iran not to
retaliate for the incident.
   It said that ``such an error cannot be ruled out in area whose
land, sea and air are jammed by military equipment, civilian
aircraft and commercial ships. ... The threat of revenge against a
superpower will not serve the cause of peace or end tension but
rather it will lead to another series of violence and
counterviolence.''
   In the United Artab Emirates, the Dubai-based, English-language
newspaper Khaleej Times said: ``Iran appears to be in no need to
undertake any adventurist actions. The moral and propaganda gain
for it has already been enormous. ... Iran can easily sit back and
watch the Americans squirm with embarrassment as they try to
explain how one of their most sophisticated ships failed to
distinguish between an Airbus and an F-14 fighter.''
</TEXT>
