07-06 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Chappell, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0861,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC: Contractor Paid Chappell Campaign Expenses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Unisys official ...' to CORRECT Gardner's
first name to Charles sted George.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conversations wiretapped as part of the Pentagon
procurement inquiry indicate a defense contractor paid some
expenses incurred by a Florida congressman's campaign and may have
passed the cost on to the government, NBC said Wednesday.
   NBC said that according to the wiretaps, Armtec Inc., a
subcontractor for Unisys Corp., paid for a trip a political
consultant made to Rep. Bill Chappell Jr.'s district earlier this
year to do groundwork for the Chappell campaign.
   Unisys official Charles Gardner was heard on a wiretap telling
the consultant he could get paid for the campaign trip by going to
the top man at Armtec, the network said. The wiretap was placed by
FBI and Navy investigators.
   Investigators believe that Gardner also discussed doing phony
paperwork to bill the costs to the Pentagon, NBC said.
   The wiretap transcript indicates Armtec already had paid part of
the expenses, NBC said.
   NBC did not give the amount allegedly paid. It did not identify
the political consultant.
   Armtec officials refused to comment, the network said.
   NBC said investigators are looking into whether there is a broad
pattern of defense firms paying out cash for political purposes via
smaller contractors, with the costs charged to the Pentagon as part
of work on weapons contracts.
   Gardner is now working for defense contractors as a consultant.
   Armtec Inc., based in Palatka, Fla., manufactures wiring
harnesses and is in Chappell's congressional district. Its offices
were searched as part of the defense inquiry.
</TEXT>
