<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DefenseProbe-Lobbyist     07-06 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Lobbyist,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Officials Offered Lobbyist A Deal, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents who searched the home of an
aerospace lobbyist played tape recorded conversations for him to
induce his cooperation with the government, his attorney said
Wednesday.
   The attorney, William Dougherty, said his client, Fred Lackner,
refused to talk to the agents without consulting his lawyer and has
since turned down a deal offered by federal officials to help build
cases against others.
   Dougherty's comments provided the first indication of government
willingness to bargain with defense industry lobbyists and others
who have figured in the investigation into alleged Pentagon
procurement bribery and fraud.
   The purported deal indicates the government may be willing to
seek the help of lesser known consultants in building cases against
more prominent suspects in the alleged fraud scam.
   Lackner, a former San Fernando Valley aerospace industry
salesman, is one of about 275 people who have been subpoenaed to
appear before a federal grand jury in Alexandria, Va., on July 19.
   Dougherty said Lackner will appear voluntarily.
   The lawyer said agents urged Lackner's cooperation when they
came to his home with a search warrant on June 14.
   ``I wasn't there, but when they served the warrant, they asked
him to cooperate and played some tapes for him and he said, `I want
to see a lawyer,''' Dougherty said.
   The attorney said he isn't sure what tapes were played but
assumes they were of wiretapped conversations similar to those
mentioned in search warrant affidavits unsealed last week in
Dallas. He said he did not know whether Lackner's voice was on the
tapes.
   A federal court in Dallas last week unsealed government
affidavits that included excerpts of wiretapped conversations
between a Navy purchasing official and two consultants.
   Dougherty confirmed that investigators are trying to prove that
Lackner bribed former Pentagon official Stuart E. Berlin, but he
insisted that Lackner gave nothing of value to Berlin.
   Berlin, a friend of Lackner's since the 1970s, was removed as a
contracting official at Naval Air Systems Command last month after
his Pentagon office was searched as part of the defense probe.
   Dougherty said the government deal would have required Lackner
to plead guilty to two counts of bribery and stealing government
property and to cooperate in the investigation. In exchange,
prosecutors would remain silent at Lackner's sentencing, he said.
   The lawyer said he has not been told what charges might be
lodged against Lackner if he fails to cooperate. He added that he
has been unable to gain access to an affidavit filed in support of
the Lackner search warrant that would outline government suspicions.
   Material taken from Lackner's home during the search was not
incriminating, the lawyer said.
   ``He has done nothing illegal,'' said Dougherty. ``They didn't
get a single government document. They got invoices on his
letterhead. ... There were no classifed documents involved with my
client. They didn't seize anything of a proprietary nature.''
   Describing his client's business, he said, ``He's an independent
consultant to consultants. They go around, talk to one another,
pick up information and help people get contracts.''
   He said Lackner continues to work although, ``People do ask
questions I guess.''
   Dougherty said he has advised Lackner not to discuss the case
with reporters.
   Dougherty confirmed that Lackner apparently helped William
Parkin, a consultant for Hazeltine Corp. of Greenlawn, N.Y., obtain
a Navy contract for a device that tests radar-like equipment in
some Air Force and Navy planes.
   Dougherty also did not deny a report in Time Magazine that
Parkin, a former Navy contracting official-turned-lobbyist, paid
Lackner half of his $24,000 annual fee from Hazeltine in exchange
for ``marketing intelligence.'' But he contended there was no
evidence his client paid Berlin for the information later passed on
to Parkin.
</TEXT>
