<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-ChildAbuse     07-06 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Child Abuse,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Child Abuse Scandal An Honest Attempt Gone Wrong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A child sexual abuse scandal which tore apart
scores of families and horrified Britain last year arose from an
honest but misfired attempt to protect children, a judicial inquiry
concluded Wednesday.
   As a result of the 320-page report, the government said it will
spend $12 million to improve training for officials who deal with
abused children and that it was strongly considering setting up a
child protection office.
   In the report, Lord Justice Elizabeth Butler-Sloss blamed two
overconfident doctors, inflexible police and a lack of
communication between officials.
   ``It is unacceptable that the disagreements and failure of
communication of adults should be allowed to obscure the needs of
children ... in so sensitive, difficult and important a field,''
she said.
   During spring and summer 1987, 121 children were diagnosed by
Drs. Marietta Higgs and Geoffrey Wyatt as being sexually abused and
were separated from their parents. Ninety-eight have returned home,
but the report does not rule on whether they were actually abused.
   The spate of alleged cases triggered a national debate on
parents' rights versus child protection.
   Mrs. Butler-Sloss, who took four months to write her report
after her two-month inquiry, told reporters the scandal in the
northeast English county of Cleveland arose partly from the
increased recognition of child abuse and the new problems this
posed.
   ``In Cleveland, an honest attempt was made to address these
problems by the agencies,'' she said. ``In spring 1987, it went
wrong.''
   Mrs. Butler-Sloss said the doctors did not create the crisis but
shared responsibility for it and should be criticized for their
``certainty and overconfidence.''
   The two doctors were also criticized for relying too heavily on
a controversial diagnostic technique called anal dilation.
   The judge said police and the local social services director
failed to resolve differences between agencies involved, and they
and others failed to reappraise their practices although the
numbers of separated families reached dramatic proportions.
   She recommended improving techniques for dealing sensitively
with children and parents in such cases and urged improved
cooperation between doctors, social workers and police.
   An independent children's rights group, the Children's Legal
Center, called the report a ``milestone in the development of
children's rights,'' but some parents who felt wrongly accused
expressed bitterness that the report was not critical enough of
officials involved.
   Some families called for the resignations of local officials and
for Wyatt and Higgs' medical licenses to be taken away.
   ``At the end of the day we are left with the feeling that this
terrible thing happened to us, but nobody says what they're going
to do about it,'' said one parent, who spoke on the condition of
not being identified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
