<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BorderDispute     07-06 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Border Dispute,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Officials Postpone `Walking the Line' to Settle Border
Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from the towns of Ashford and
Willington were forced Wednesday to postpone ``walking the line''
to settle a longstanding border dispute when they discovered that
heavy woods made it too difficult to get their bearings.
   Officials of the rural northeastern Connecticut towns decided to
resort to the method used for centuries by New England farmers to
re-establish property lines each spring after being told that an
engineer's survey of the 20 acres of disputed land would cost about
$40,000.
   ``If we're going to actually do any walking, we've decided we
have to do it when there aren't any leaves on the trees, because
it's just too hard to see anything at all,'' said Ashford First
Selectwoman Paula Faulkner.
   Poet Robert Frost immortalized walking the line in his poem
``Mending Wall,'' in which he described to property owners walking
along a stone wall dividing their land that had been partly
demolished by winter weather and hunters.
   Connecticut statute once required that officials from
neighboring towns also walk the line every 10 years to maintain
boundaries, according to Albert Fitzback of Putnam, a surveyor and
member of an arbitration panel appointed by a Superior Court judge
to help settle the border dispute.
   The panel suggested walking the line after Ashford and
Willington officials balked at the cost of a survey.
   At issue is an eight-mile long, mile-wide stip of land that the
General Assembly took from Ashford in 1727 when Willington was
incorporated. Ashford authorities contend the border originally was
drawn as a straight line, but Willington officials have relied on
markers placed in 1916 that create a slight jag in the line.
   The officials did locate one of the key markers during their
abbreviated walk Wednesday night. They expect to continue the
exercise in September or October, once the leaves are off the
trees, said Willington First Selectman Carlton Csiki.
   ``It's a country problem, we're country people and we'll most
likely resolve it in a country fashion,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
