<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SanMarino     07-06 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-San Marino,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government Named in San Marino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN MARINO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature on Wednesday named a
government composed of Christian Democrats and Communists, who
together have ruled this tiny republic for two years.
   The new government was formed following May 29 elections for the
legislature, known as the Great and General Council.
   The government is comprised of six Christian Democrats and four
Communists, a gain of one for the Christian Democrats.
   The legislature retained the three top ministers from the
previous government _ Gabriele Gatti, secretary of state for
foreign affairs; Alvaro Selva, secretary of state for internal
affairs and Clara Boscaglia, secretary of state for finance and
budget.
   The Christian Democrats and Communists both posted gains last
month in the elections in this hilltop republic of 23 square miles
surrounded by Italy near the Adriatic coast.
   The smaller Socialist Party lost ground and the Unitary
Socialists stayed steady at 13.6 percent of the vote.
   San Marino, the world's oldest republic and with a population of
22,400, depends on tourism, postage stamps and financial services
as its chief sources of income. It was founded in 301.
</TEXT>
