<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseProbe 4thLd-Writethru a0836 07-06 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0836,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Budget Shortfall Seen Imperiling Pentagon Fraud Protection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs bgng, `Meanwhile, in,' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with NBC report on defense contractor allegedly paying bills
of a congressional campaign consultant and possibly billing the
government for the cost</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many defense contractors still aren't serious
about policing themselves, and the Defense Department likely won't
get the money to hire as many fraud investigators as it needs, the
Pentagon's top two inspectors told Congress on Wednesday.
   June Gibbs Brown, the Pentagon's inspector general, said the
number of investigators specifically assigned to track down
contractor fraud has risen from 375 six years ago to more than
1,000 now.
   But at least 450 more are needed, she told the House Armed
Services Committee, and ``Given the department's projected budget
shortfalls for the coming years, I am pessimistic'' they will be
hired.
   Brown and Derek Vander Schaaf, the deputy inspector general, did
not speak specifically about details of the ongoing criminal
investigation into fraud and bribery allegations.
   That probe centers on allegations that defense contractors and
consultants, many of them former defense officials, bribed Pentagon
officials for contracting details that could be vital in winning
contracts worth billions of dollars.
   In other developments:
   _In Southern California, an attorney for aerospace lobbyist Fred
Lackner said federal agents who searched Lackner's home played
tape-recorded conversations to him to induce him to cooperate with
the government. Attorney William Dougherty said Lackner refused to
talk without consulting his lawyer and has turned down an offer of
a deal from federal officials to help build cases against others.
Dougherty confirmed that investigators are trying to prove that
Lackner bribed former Pentagon official Stuart E. Berlin. But he
insisted that Lackner gave nothing of value to Berlin.
   _NBC News reported that conversations wiretapped as part of the
defense probe indicate a defense contractor _ Armtec Inc., a
subcontractor for Unisys Corp. _ paid some expenses incurred by a
congressional campaign consultant and may have passed the cost on
to the government.
   Charles Gardner, then a Unisys official, was heard on a wiretap
telling the consultant he could get paid for the campaign trip for
Rep. Bill Chappell Jr., D-Fla., by going to the top man at Armtec,
the network said. Investigators believe Gardner also discussed
doing phony paperwork to bill the costs to the Pentagon, NBC said.
   The Pentagon recently developed a self-policing code of ethics
that it wants defense contractors to follow, but that hasn't worked
very well, said Vander Schaaf.
   Of the 46 companies who signed the self-policing code, 39 are
under investigation for contract fraud, he told Rep. John Kasich,
R-Ohio.
   Brown said, moreover, ``it is discouraging to me that only 46
defense contractors'' signed the ethics code.
   ``If corporate officials do not recognize this responsibility
and take appropriate actions, no number of auditors, inspectors or
investigators will have a measurable impact upon reducing fraud and
waste in defense programs,'' she said.
   ``Unfortunately, some contractor officials have not taken this
responsibility seriously and have inappropriately blamed their
shortcomings on excessive oversight, regulations and legislation by
the DoD or Congress,'' she said.
   Vander Schaaf agreed. He said ``the contractor situation has
gotten out of hand to a large degree,'' explaining that the
Pentagon doesn't have enough people to effectively oversee
contractor employees.
   While problems with contractors remain, Brown said the Pentagon
itself is doing a better job.
   For example, she said, complaints by contractors about
duplicative audits led to an overhaul of the way the Pentagon
coordinates the numerous agencies it uses to look at contractor
work.
   In the past two years, there have been more than 1,500
convictions in federal courts of contractors or their employees for
a variety of crimes, she said, and $357 million has been returned
to the federal government.
   Also on Wednesday, The Washington Times filed a motion in U.S.
District Court to unseal documents filed in connection with
warrants to search the offices or wiretap the telephones of defense
consultants.
   A number of such warrants were signed by U.S. District Judge
John H. Pratt here. The newspaper sought affidavits filed to obtain
warrants as well as inventories of items seized in searches.
   ``The public's common law and First Amendment fights to access
require the unsealing of these documents,'' the newspaper's lawyers
said in court papers. ``The public has a heightened interest in
obtaining access to the sealed documents at issue since they may
contain sufficient information for the secretary of defense to
suspend payments under contracts obtained with criminal conduct.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
