<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-US     07-06 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-US,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Briefly Detains Three U.S. Soldiers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No home towns available for detained U.S. soldiers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian troops briefly detained
three U.S. soldiers who strayed off base in a military vehicle,
U.S. officials said Wednesday.
   The pro-government newspaper Matutino said Panamanian forces
detained the soldiers Tuesday for unspecified ``suspicious''
activities in Veracruz, a town on the Pacific six miles from the
capital.
   Mercedes Morris, a spokeswoman for U.S. Southern Command
Headquarters in Panama, said the soldiers had simply driven off
Clayton Air Base by accident.
   The soldiers were identified as Lt. Andrew J. Johnson, Sgt. Paul
L. Coach and Sgt. Edward E. Tate. Matutino said they were detained
briefly, then handed over to Southern Command officials.
   Matutino said Panama will formally demand that the United States
end such ``threats of a military invasion'' and breaches of the
1977 Canal Treaties, which forbid U.S. military personnel from
leaving base in uniform.
   The three soldiers were in uniform at the time of the incident.
   Matutino also said their vehicle was equipped for espionage.
Morris denied this, saying the vehicle had nothing but standard
radio-communications gear.
   Tensions are high between the United States and Panama because
of U.S. backing for the ouster of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, head
of the Panamanian Defense Forces and the country's de facto ruler.
Noriega is under indictment in the United States as a drug
trafficker.
</TEXT>
