<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-VesselSeized 1stLd-Writethru a0775 07-06 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vessel Seized, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0775,0828</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pot Ship Towed To Port With 72 Tons Of High-Grade Marijuana</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to UPDATE that nationalities now certain.
INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf `If it...' to UPDATE with
identities, appearance before magistrate; picks up 9th graf pvs,
`Cecil Allison....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian-registered ship seized on the high
seas with more than 72 tons of marijuana was towed into port
Wednesday, and the Coast Guard said its capture was the largest
drug bust ever on the West Coast.
   Officials said the Encounter Bay had endured 60 rounds of
machine-gun fire about 600 miles offshore last Friday, and
surrendered only when threatened with cannon fire.
   The ship was towed into port under tight security by the Coast
Guard cutter Boutwell, which was flying a makeshift ``pot buster''
flag.
   The crew of 18 _ including three Americans, one from England,
one from New Zealand and 13 from Indonesia, Thailand and Singapore
_ were photographed and fingerprinted aboard the Boutwell in
preparation for an appearance before a U.S. magistrate.
   Admiral Robert Kramek, installed last week as regional
commandant, used the occasion to criticize funding cuts in the
Coast Guard's patrol budget. He said the bust was the largest ever
on the West Coast.
   ``This ought to indicate to people ... that it's a flourishing
business, and for the government not to give the Coast Guard proper
funds ... to interdict is foolhardy,'' said Kramek.
   Agents from the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration were
waiting on shore for the converted oil-rig supply ship and set up
security for the crew and for the cargo, which will be burned,
officials said.
   If it can be proved they were headed for the United States, they
could face felony charges and prison terms of a few years to life,
said Gary Liming, DEA agent-in-charge.
   Sixteen of the ship's crew members appeared Wednesday afternoon
before U.S. Magistrate John Weinberg and were advised of their
rights, and two others will appear Thursday when a Thai interpreter
is available. All are being held pending a detention hearing Monday
when bail may be set, said deputy clerk Karen Lamborn.
   The Americans were identified as Samuel J. Colflesh, Terrance
Albert Nolan and Gary Robinson, but hometowns were not available,
Ms. Lamborn said.
   The others were Nico Jacob Tuwahatu, Abraham Rumahlaiselan,
Ramil Bin Samaila, Saptu Bin Ismail, Muhid Sus Pingi, Neh Sudariyo
and Bernhard Rumuat, all of Indonesia; Seng Beng Ng, Jupri Beh
Ariffin and Rusfi Beh Ariffin of Singapore; Wuthi Phibulsilpa,
Panya Aranyig and Abdul Syukur, all of Thailand; Jeffrey Bernard
Press of the United Kingdom; and Anthonyo Gilbert Sayers of New
Zealand.
   Cecil Allison, captain of the Boutwell, said the Encounter Bay
appeared headed for the Strait of Juan de Fuca, which separates
Canada's British Columbia and the northeastern corner of the state
of Washington.
   Family and friends of the Boutwell's crew cheered the cutter's
arrival and the makeshift flag of a marijuna leaf marked diagonally
by a red line.
   ``Noriega, put this in your pipe and smoke it,'' said a banner
held aloft by Allison's family. Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriego came under federal indictment in Florida earlier this year
on charges of drug trafficking.
   The 180-foot Encounter Bay was not flying a flag when it was
spotted last Friday by an air patrol 600 miles offshore. It did not
answer when contacted by radio, flag, light, bullhorn and gunfire
signals.
   The Boutwell's crew could read the word Panama in obscured
letters, and a few hours later, the Coast Guard had permission to
board the Encounter Bay from the Panamian Embassy, Allison said.
   Encounter Bay's owner was listed as Countess Shipping Corp. of
Panama.
   The Boutwell fired 60 rounds at the Encounter Bay's rudder and
engine areas. When there still was no response, the Boutwell
threatened cannon fire and the Encounter Bay surrendered.
   ``Our best estimate is there is somewhere in excess of 72 tons''
of marijuana on board, said Allison, who described the drug as
``very high grade with very few stems and very few seeds.''
   Allison speculated that the Encounter Bay stalled to destroy
records.
   ``It was a very organized operation, from the packaging all the
way through to the control of the ship and the cleaning out of the
boat's records.''
   Allison said they found no records that would indicate where the
vessel had come from or was headed to, or who may have been in
charge of the operation.
   He said the marijuana, with a street value estimated at about
$280 million, consisted of about 8,000 ``bales'' packed in four
large shipping containers. Each ``bale,'' in a blue nylon sack,
contained eight packets of marijuana vacuum-sealed in double
plastic wrappings.
   Liming said that much of the marijuana, possibly from Thailand,
probably would have gone to California.
</TEXT>
