<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Nazi     07-06 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Nazi,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>War Camp Survivors Complete Testimony In Nazi Deportation Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three survivors of Nazi camps
testified Wednesday in the deportation case of Josef Schwammberger
that the former Nazi SS captain personally shot Jews to death
almost daily, most with a pistol.
   Schwammberger, 76, has been accused of killing at least 5,000
Jews as commandant of the Rozwadow and Przemysl labor camps for
Jews in Nazi-occupied Poland during World War II.
   He escaped Austria with the help of the Nazi Odessa network in
1948, and made his way to Argentina in 1949, where he was arrested
last November.
   The survivors _ Abraham Secemski of Chicago, Edward Blonder of
Miami and Morris Reiter of Toronto _ testified before the
government for two days regarding their experiences in camps
commanded by Schwammberger in 1942-43, said their lawyer, Martin
Mendelsohn.
   They said that besides killing Jews with his own hand,
Schwammberger starved prisoners, killed those who were sick or
became unable to work and, for fun, set an attack dog on Jewish
prisoners.
   ``He was a sadist, an evil person. He played games of life with
humans, with Jews,'' said Blonder, 67, who was in six different war
camps, including Przemysl with Schwammberger. ``He always called us
dogs, schweinhund.''
   ``He was the god, the judge, the jury, the executioner. He was
everything,'' said Secemski, who was in Rozwadow. His uncle was
shot to death by Schwammberger, said Secemski.
   Secemski lost 97 family members during the war. Only he and one
brother survived.
   Reiter, 57, who met Secemski in Przemysl, said he came to
Argentina ``for the humanity of the world, (and to show) that after
40 years people cannot hide from the crimes they've done.''
   Mendelsohn, the Washington-based legal counsel for the Simon
Wiesenthal Center of Los Angeles, said he was optimistic the
Argentine government would strip Schwammberger of his citizenship
and deport him to Stuttgart, West Germany, where he faces war
crimes charges.
   The witnesses and Mendelsohn left Argentina Wednesday night to
return home. None of them saw Schwammberger here.
   ``I would like to face him. It would make me feel better. He's
in jail and now I'm the free man,'' Blonder said.
   Schwammberger is being held in nearby La Plata pending
deportation proceedings. He was arrested Nov. 13 in a
German-Argentine village in the Cordoba provincial hills 500 miles
northwest of Buenos Aires.
   Court records show Schwammberger worked in a petrochemical
company in La Plata for most of his years in Argentina and became a
citizen in 1965. Judicial authorities say he would not have been
granted citizenship had they known of the West German charges
pending against him since 1962.
   Those charges include murder, blackmail and stealing gold
fillings and jewelry from victims.
   Authorities say the French arrested Schwammberger in Innsbruck,
Austria, in July 1945, with eight sacks of plundered jewelry,
watches and gold teeth.
   According to police records in Innsbruck, Schwammberger admitted
possessing the sacks of goods and carrying out ``executions on 35
individuals, shooting them in the back of the neck with a pistol.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
