<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Low Flights,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rhineland Pfalz Votes to Curb Low-level Military Flights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Parliament of Rhineland Pfalz
state on Wednesday unanimously backed a resolution calling for a
ban on military training flights under 1,000 feet, West German
television reported.
   The vote came one day after a West German air force jet fighter
crashed on a training exercise in northern West Germany and after a
series of military-related plane crashes in West Germany in recent
months.
   The resolution, calling on the Bonn government to begin talks
with NATO officials on banning low-level flights, was approved by
all parties representing the state, ZDF television reported.
   The nation's new defense minister, Rupert Scholz, said last week
he would make the problem of low-level flights a top priority.
   On Tuesday a F-4 Phantom crashed into a field and exploded about
25 miles west of Hamburg. Its two pilots ejected safely.
   The area, like Rhineland Pfalz, is the scene of frequent
low-level military training flights.
   Citizens and environmental groups have protested the flights,
saying they make life in the region unbearable.
   On Sunday a West German army helicopter crashed into a cliff in
Bavaria state, killing all nine aboard.
   On Friday, a civilian-owned airplane under contract with the
West German army crashed into a house in northern Germany, killing
the pilot.
   Also last week, three U.S. Air Force F-16s crashed in one day.
One pilot was killed when two jets collided in flight. U.S.
officials said the F-16s involved in those crashes were not on
low-level flight missions.
</TEXT>
