<DOCNO> AP880706-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     07-06 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Church Official Appeals To Preserve Romanian Villages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hungarian church official has appealed
to the international community to pressure Romania into dropping a
village demolition project, the Austrian Catholic news service
Kathpress reported.
   The agency quoted Cardinal Laszlo Paskai, the Hungarian Catholic
primate, as saying the Romanian project would ``destroy the
culture, the history and hence the national identity'' of millions
of people.
   Under a plan unveiled by Romanian leader Nicolae Ceasuescu in
March, about 7,000 of Romania's 13,000 villages will be razed and
replaced by agricultural-industrial centers.
   The move would also affect hundreds of communities where many of
Romania's 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians live.
   The project led to an unofficial mass protest in downtown
Budapest June 27. Ceausescu, angered by the protest in the
Hungarian capital, closed a Hungarian consulate and ordered the
premises of a Hungarian cultural center vacated.
   Paskai said he was protesting not only in his own name but also
``in the name of the bishops, priests and the faithful.'' He said
he received petitions and letters indicating his concern was shared
by many Hungarians.
   ``Villages are more than just settlements of small groups of the
population, they are integral components of the entirety of a
country,'' Paskai said. ``The demolition of buildings, including
churches, means the destruction of historical and cultural values,
irrespective of which nationality is involved.''
   He called the Romanian plan ``all the more painful since it
occurs in a country with which we want to live in friendly
relations and with whose population we are bound by ties of
friendship and kinship.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
