<DOCNO> AP880706-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BritishColumbia     07-06 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-British Columbia,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confident Premier Shrugs Off Resignations, Shuffles Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada's most controversial
premier, Dutch-born William Vander Zalm of British Columbia,
shrugged off the resignation of two senior ministers and announced
a major Cabinet shuffle Wednesday.
   ``Showing leadership often involves having to make tough
decisions,'' said Vander Zalm, a former tulip importer who owns and
lives at Fantasy Gardens amusement park outside Vancouver.
   In the past week, his government was shaken by the resignations
of Attorney General Brian Smith and Economic Development Minister
Grace McCarthy, both of whom fought Vander Zalm for leadership of
the Social Credit Party in 1986.
   The two complained of meddling by the premier's office and
accused Vander Zalm of an autocratic style of leadership.
   In the Cabinet shuffle, Vander Zalm removed a third former
rival, Highways Minister Stephen Rogers.
   Bud Smith, another old rival, was named attorney general.
   The first two years of Vander Zalm's five-year term have been
marked by controversy, although his conservative-leaning party has
a 22-seat majority in the provincial legislature.
   He was accused of interceding in a public bidding process on
behalf of a friend who wanted to buy the Expo `86 site in Vancouver.
   A Roman Catholic, he threatened to ban government funding for
abortions until a Supreme Court ruling struck down his policy. And
he suggested Christianity was the best means of improving the
health of schoolchildren.
</TEXT>
