<DOCNO> AP880706-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EpiscopalConvention     07-06 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Episcopal Convention,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishops Reject Resolution Condemning Homosexuality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Episcopalian House of Bishops rejected by
voice vote Wednesday a proposal that would have condemned
homosexuality as a failure of Christian ideals.
   The bishops' group, one of the two governing houses of the
church here this week for the church's 69th General Convention,
voted instead to call for a dialogue among churches on sexuality to
continue.
   The bishops, as a step toward setting policy for the 2.6 million
members of the Episcopal Church of the United States, endorsed a
resolution that affirmed traditional and biblical teachings of
chastity and fidelity, but omitted phrases concerning homosexuality.
   Some delegates complained that the House of Bishops did not act
decisively on the homosexuality issue.
   ``People within the church are hungry for a statement of
principle,'' said the Rev. C. Brinkley Morton, the bishop of San
Diego. ``Putting forth another study is sweeping the issue under
the carpet. It's a cop-out.''
   Liberal delegates were pleased by the House of Bishops action.
   ``The love between people of the same gender is as valid as the
love between a man and a woman,'' said the Rev. Paul Moore Jr.,
bishop of New York. ``Gay people going through the tragedy of AIDS
should not be denied the strength of an intimate relationship with
a person of the same sex.''
   Earlier, the presiding bishop of the convention called for
church leaders of all denominations to form personal relationships
with AIDS carriers.
   The Rt. Rev. Edmond L. Browning made the comment during a
healing service for AIDS patients, which was attended by about 650
people.
</TEXT>
