<1ST_LINE>a a PM-VaneDispute Adv12   07-06 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vane Dispute, Adv 12,0846</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, July 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Firefighters, City Tussle Over Century-Old Weathervane</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a land where weather vanes are akin to
crown jewels, city leaders and firefighters are at odds over a
gilded prize that foretold the winds of New Hampshire's capital
city for roughly a century.
   The treasure is a meticulously detailed 4-foot-long, horse-drawn
fire wagon, cast in copper and covered in gold leaf.
   With manes and tails flying, two strong horses race ahead of the
big-wheeled wagon equipped with kerosene lanterns, nozzles, a
wood-fired steam boiler and pumping equipment. One helmeted fireman
holds the taut reins. A second stokes the boiler.
   The Cushing & White Co. of Waltham, Mass., no longer in
business, designed the vane around 1871 for $200, a sum then
representing about half the cost of a working man's home. Experts
today believe the vane could fetch $100,000.
   The vane graced the cupola of Concord's main fire station until
1980 when firefighters, without consulting city leaders, took it
down and put it in a room full of firefighting memorabilia in the
city's south-end station.
   The firefighters took it into protective custody because weather
vane thieves were active and because the city planned to sell the
main fire station to a developer, said fire department Lt. Robert
Constant.
   The vane issue has surfaced periodically, with firefighters
opposing city efforts to have the treasure again grace the Concord
skyline.
   ``This is a valuable part of the firefighters' heritage and it
belongs with us. No one can protect it like we can,'' said Wayne
Nickerson, a firefighter for 13 years.
   ``We don't pay the firefighters to be custodians of antiques. We
pay them to put out fires and to save lives, and they are very good
at that,'' said Martin Gross, a prominent Concord lawyer and the
city's mayor when the vane came down.
   The dispute flared anew recently when Mayor Elizabeth Hager
decided the vane belonged to the city.
   Hager said she was first drawn to the vane in the 1970s while
hawk-watching with her children, who learned to focus their
binoculars by training them on the intricate detail of the horses
and wagon.
   ``I was heartbroken when it came down,'' Hager said. ``And
recently, I just decided we should stop futzing around and get it
back up where it belongs.''
   Weather vanes are popular with thieves in New England, a region
once crowded with copper rooftop art depicting rural life in the
form of animals, farm equipment and other bucolic symbols. Many of
the most valuable vanes have been replaced with replicas, the
originals placed under lock-and-key in museums or private
collections.
   It is ``deceptively simple'' to steal vanes, said Samuel
Pennington, publisher of the Maine Antique Digest. Vanes turn on a
spindle and need only be lifted inches to remove them, he said.
   In 1983, Pennington helped find and recover a valuable weather
vane stolen from atop the fire station in Hallowell, a tiny
antique-filled town in central Maine.
   As for putting Concord's vane back on a roof, Pennington thinks
it akin to ``tying 10 ten-thousand-dollar bills up there and daring
someone to steal them.''
   Two fire department vanes similar to Concord's in age and style
disappeared during the renovation of buildings in Nashua and
Manchester. The Manchester vane was discovered six years ago in a
museum in Shelburne, Vt. The Nashua vane has not been found.
   Not taking any chances, Concord firefighters recently wired
their one-room museum with an ear-splitting alarm guaranteed to
catch the attention of the 20 men and women assigned to the station.
   The firefighters encourage visitors to come see the vane along
with the fire photos, records, badges and helmets on display.
   But seeing the vane means catching the firefighters between
engagements, which is not the city councilors' idea of public
access.
   Last month, the councilors unanimously ordered the firefighters
to relinquish the vane. This month, they rescinded the order and
formed a study committee.
   Both sides appear to be moving toward creation of a replica that
would foretell the winds from the roof of the original fire
station, now an office building.
   Hager said she would have no problem with a replica if
firefighters paid for it. Constant said firefighters are
considering how to raise the roughly $5,000 needed for the process.
   ``We probably wouldn't have it golded over though, because that
would just be an incentive to steal the replica,'' Constant said.
   While a replica would solve one issue _ returning a scenic view
to taxpayers _ it may be awhile before the fate of the crown jewel
itself is resolved.
   ``We don't want an argument, but the vane belongs with the
firefighters,'' Constant said.
   To which Hager replied, ``Oh, there won't be any argument; the
weather vane belongs to the city.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, July 12</NOTE>
