<1ST_LINE>a p AM-GOP-Blacks Adv11   07-06 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP-Blacks, Adv 11,0722</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, July 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Maryland, Virginia GOP Field Black Candidates in Tough Senate
Races</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maryland and Virginia Republicans are fielding
little-known black candidates in uphill Senate races, apparently to
help build bridges to a traditionally Democratic constituency. But
some observers say the tactic is likely to backfire.
   The Maryland party is putting up Alan L. Keyes, a 37-year-old
Harvard-educated businessman with conservative views and a gift for
rousing rhetoric. Keyes emerged as the likely nominee on June 25
after the victor in the party's nine-way primary bowed out.
   In Virginia, Republicans are offering Maurice A. Dawkins, 67, a
retired Washington-area preacher and lobbyist who claimed the
nomination after a stirring speech to delegates at the Republican
state convention.
   Common ground for the two candidates extends beyond their
speechmaking ability. Both are relative newcomers to elective
politics, and both face daunting opponents _ popular incumbent Sen.
Paul Sarbanes in Maryland and former Gov. Charles Robb in Virginia.
The political strength of both Democrats scared off more
experienced GOP prospects.
   That strength also virtually guarantees that Keyes and Dawkins,
the only two blacks running for the Senate this year, will not
crack the chamber's color barrier. The only black to be elected to
the Senate in this century was Edward W. Brooke, R-Mass., who
served from 1967 to 1979.
   But Republicans hope the two men can at least stir up excitement
this election season and change the mix of voters in the Republican
column.
   ``They have that tremendous speaking ability that can ignite a
group and galvanize the party in ways that don't require a lot of
money,'' said Tom Mason, a spokesman for the Republican Party's
national Senate campaign arm.
   ``They're dynamic personalities. They'll form a little bit
different coalition ... hopefully a little bit broader'' than would
other potential candidates, he said.
   Mason emphasized that the broader appeal is not part of a
national GOP strategy. The national party did not recruit either
man, he said, but both ``came up on their own, naturally, through
Republican ranks.''
   However, the similarities in the two neighboring states do raise
at least the appearance that the party is using the two candidates
for its own goals in a situation where victory is only a remote
possibility.
   ``If it appears to be some kind of cynical attempt to use
minority candidates in an effort to say they have them, but in
races that appear to be unwinnable, it could backfire,'' said Anita
Dunn, spokeswoman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
   One political analyst sees that as a real danger.
   ``There are a lot of things the GOP can do to attract black
voters and build bridges to the black community,'' said Charles
Cook, publisher of a newsletter on politics.
   ``The way not to do it is to take a nomination that isn't worth
anything because of the political situation and give it to someone
who under normal circumstances would not be able to get it, and
hand it to them when they are just going to get crucified,'' Cook
said.
   Neither Cook nor Dunn sees much prospect that black voters will
flock to the Republican column because of the choice of GOP
nominees. In Maryland, Democrats have a 2-to-1 registration
advantage. In Virginia, a recent poll gave Robb a 4-to-1 lead over
Dawkins.
   Cook points to the 1986 governor's race in Michigan, where
William Lucas, a black Republican county official, garnered just 31
percent of the vote against incumbent Democrat James Blanchard. The
GOP vote was the lowest in 150 years.
   ``I don't know that the Republican Party is stronger in Michigan
as a result of that, or that relations between blacks and the party
are better off,'' Cook said. ``I don't know what purpose it serves
... Maybe it's trying to cure by symbolism a substantive problem.''
   Mason calls that explanation ``really reaching.''
   ``I think these fellows were not nominated on the basis of their
race, but on the basis of their capabilities as a Senate
candidate,'' he said. ``To say they are only black candidates is to
really insult them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, July 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
