<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-DoubleJeopardy Adv10-2Takes   07-06 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Double Jeopardy, Adv 10-2 Takes,0939</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pregnant, Homeless Women Juggle Survival With Child Bearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spent vials herald a robust trade in crack.
Prostitutes turn tricks in stairwells. Robberies, beatings and even
killings are everyday risks. Amid the hostility and crime of New
York's hotels for the homeless, hundreds of expectant mothers mark
time.
   These women face double jeopardy, fending for a place to live
while luckless life grows inside them.
   Their babies die at twice the rate of other infants in the city.
Of the survivors, often underweight and fallen behind even before
they get started, many never recover. Many of the women are unaware
of the medical help available or ignorant of its need.
   They're usually single heads of households with two or three
children already. They have welfare checks to fetch, apartments to
seek and meager meals to cook on hotplates. Those grim priorities
come before prenatal care, nutrition, vitamins, rest and hygiene.
   ``These are high-risk pregnancies,'' said Dr. Philip Brickner of
St. Vincent's Hospital, which provides free care for the pregnant
and homeless. ``Without prenatal care, there's a relatively high
risk of a premature baby or a damaged baby, both of which lead to
enormous health expense.''
   ``It's a time bomb,'' said Dana Hughes, senior health specialist
with the Children's Defense Fund in Washington, D.C. ``The baby
born to a pregnant, homeless woman is at tremendous disadvantage if
it happens to survive.''
   Dabbing tears with toilet paper, hotel resident Juanita Williams
talked about a daughter born in December. Too busy with her other
children, she neglected prenatal care. The child, her 10th, was
born with spina bifida, a congenital defect of the nervous system
that doctors say can be related to drug or alcohol abuse early in a
pregnancy.
   ``I wonder if she'd be OK if I would have gotten better care. I
was on the run so much,'' the 42-year-old mother said. ``This is
not living. I don't even know if it's surviving. It's no place to
raise a child. You have to take it one day at a time and pray you
get out of this hell.''
   Efforts by the city, state and volunteers to reach these fragile
tenants are complicated by sheer numbers. In five years, the
homeless population has exploded and overwhelmed a stopgap shelter
system that scatters them all over the city. In that wave came
scores of pregnant women.
   New York leads the nation with 28,000 homeless, according to the
city's Human Resources Administration, and spends $312 million,
about 6 percent of its $4.9 billion annual budget, to care for
them. The city doesn't know how many homeless women are pregnant,
but estimates by the Legal Aid Society and the Coalition for the
Homeless put the number at 500 to 800.
   Because the city doesn't have enough private rooms in its 29
shelters, most get emergency housing in a network of 55 hotels,
some filled with welfare recipients while others are shared with
tourists. The city, acknowledging hotels make rotten shelters,
hopes to get out of them by 1993.
   Since 1986, the city has been under court order not to house
pregnant women or mothers with newborns in barracks-style shelters
where they can be exposed to such contagious ailments as measles
and respiratory infection.
   Advocates had argued the women should have private rooms. They
didn't bargain for the wretched conditions in welfare hotels.
   Four people may share a room as small as 9-by-12-feet furnished
with two bunk beds but lacking chairs or a table for meals. Paint
peels from walls and ceilings. Food is strung on ropes to keep it
from rats and roaches.
   Not all bathrooms are private. Afraid their children may catch a
disease or be molested in a communal toilet, some mothers make
their youngsters relieve themselves in plastic potties or empty
cans.
   ``The city's cure is perhaps worse than the disease,'' said
Arthur Fried of the Legal Aid Society.
   Nevertheless, some homeless women, desperate to escape
congregate shelters and knowing pregnant women get private rooms,
offer to buy urine from pregnant women. The city tests urine to
verify pregnancy, and a positive screening can mean a room alone
instead of a crowded floor.
   ``One girl said she'd pay me $5 for a sample of my urine because
she wanted a private room. She was strung out on drugs and she
wanted to do them in privacy,'' said Tracie Dillard, 22, who at
eight months pregnant was staying at a city shelter in Brooklyn.
   Urine sales do occur, city officials said, but followup
pregnancy tests have not found any cheaters.
   ``I'm sure it's happened,'' said Gail Gordon, first deputy
administrator of adult services for the Human Resources
Administration. ``But it's not the norm. If it did happen, my
goodness, how sad.''
   Medically and financially, being homeless and pregnant produces
a harsh principle of pay now or pay more later.
   Infants born to mothers who lived in welfare hotels during
pregnancy had a death rate of 25 per 1,000 births, according to a
1984 study by the city's Health Department. That's more than double
the city rate and 2.5 times higher than the national rate of 10
deaths per 1,000 births.
   Without prenatal care, babies are at least three times more
likely to have birth weights of less than 5 pounds, which means
they'll need followup care, according to the Children's Defense
Fund.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
