<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   07-06 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0541</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis B. Levine, the former investment banker
whose revelations triggered Wall Street's biggest insider trading
scandal, has been released from prison and transferred to a
work-furlough program in New York.
   Kenneth Treon, a counselor at the Lewisburg federal prison camp
in Lewisburg, Pa., where Levine had been serving a two-year prison
term since April 1987, said Levine was released Tuesday under a
halfway-house program for inmates within six months of their parole
date.
   Treon said the program helps convicts re-enter society.
Officials declined to identify the facility.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of the Farm Credit System have
announced a merger that will combine nine of the system's banks for
cooperatives into one lending institution.
   ``This vote is a landmark in agricultural finance,'' said Edward
Breihan of Lubbock, Texas, chairman of a committee on banks for
cooperatives structure.
   The merger decision was announced Tuesday in Denver and
Washington by the Farm Credit Council, an arm of the Farm Credit
System, a $50 billion network of borrower-owned cooperatives that
taken together represent the nation's largest farm lender.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Japan have signed an
agreement opening Japan to more American beef and citrus.
   The agreement, reached last month during negotiations in Tokyo,
will open Japan gradually over the next few years to more U.S. beef
and citrus and move away from the restrictive quota system that has
been in effect.
   The Commerce Department has estimated annual U.S. beef exports
to Japan could grow to about $1 billion a year from about $550
million now. Sales of oranges and juice, now less than $100
million, could rise to more than $150 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Management and union officials from Texas Air
Corp. and its troubled subsidiary, Eastern Airlines, have met with
a federal referee but were unable to announce agreement on ways to
defuse the carrier's labor problems.
   A four-hour meeting convened Tuesday by William E. Brock, who
was appointed to try to help the two sides ease their disputes,
ended with the former labor secretary saying more work was needed.
Transportation Department officials would say little about the type
of agreement that was being sought.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Co. says it has agreed to sell its
motor products division to Ryobi Limited of Japan for about $325
million.
   The division, located in Pickens and Anderson, S.C., is a major
source of power tools for Sears, Roebuck & Co. It also produces
floor-care equipment.
   Ryobi is a diversified manufacturer based in Tokyo with
consolidated annual sales of $1 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Co. Inc., a leading producer and
distributor of gasoline and petroleum products, says it has agreed
to buy the smaller Atlantic Petroleum Corp. for $513 million.
   The acquisition is to be made, Sun chairman Robert McClements
Jr. said Tuesday, by purchasing all shares of Atlantic Petroleum
Maatschappij BV, a Netherlands holding company.
   The holding company is owned by John Duess, who bought the
Atlantic properties from Atlantic Richfield Co. in 1985 for $420
million.
</TEXT>
