<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     07-06 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit Post-Crash High; Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Buying related to financial futures has driven the stock market
to its highest levels since last October's market crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 27.03 points
Tuesday to finish at 2,158.61, its highest post-crash level since
it closed at 2,152.20 on June 22.
   A weaker dollar, higher interest rates and the U.S. Navy's
downing of an Iranian passenger jet over the weekend had convinced
many traders that the stage was set for a selloff on Wall Street.
But while the market opened moderately lower, the Dow average moved
into plus territory around midday and climbed steadily for the rest
of the session.
   The oil market also shrugged off Iran's outrage over the
incident in the Persian Gulf, saying its aftermath probably would
not affect petroleum shipping or inflate prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, one barometer of world oil
prices, the contract for August delivery of West Texas Intermediate
crude oil rose 15 cents per barrel, to $15.09.
   Traders ascribed the price rise to short-term speculative buying
ahead of the American Petroleum Institute's weekly report on U.S.
oil supplies, but emphasized that the oil market remained depressed
because of world oversupply and the outlook for prices was down.
   In trading of other commodities, soybean futures closed sharply
lower on the Chicago Board of Trade as a rainy forecast diluted
fears of drought damage on the crop, but corn prices advanced on
speculation that the moisture would come too late to prevent
significant damage to that crop.
   Wheat and oats followed the soybean market, which saw some
contracts plummet the 30-cents-a-bushel limit for daily trading.
   Separately, the dollar drifted lower in light trading as the
pound jumped in response to Monday's increase in British interest
rates. The dollar fell in New York trading to 134.33 Japanese yen
from 135.40 yen late Friday, while the pound rose to $1.7075 from
$1.6825.
   Bond prices declined, sending interest rates higher, as traders
returned from the three-day holiday weekend without any strong
conviction about the market's direction. The yield on the
Treasury's closely-watched 30-year bond rose to 8.87 percent from
8.83 percent late Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     07-06 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Dip on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in the government's latest auction to the lowest
level since last month.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.6 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.57 percent on Tuesday, down from
6.59 percent last week. Another $6.6 billion was sold in six-month
bills at an average discount rate of 6.71 percent, down from 6.75
percent last week.
   The three-month rates were the lowest since June 20, when the
bills sold for 6.51 percent. The six-month rates were the lowest
since June 13, when the bills averaged 6.67 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.77 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,833.90 and 7.04 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,660.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages, dipped to 7.52 percent last
week from 7.53 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
