<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FinancialServices     07-06 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Financial Services,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Chicago Could Lose Role As Major Financial Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Possible regulatory changes stemming from the
October stock market crash could threaten this city's position as a
major financial center, according to a new report by local
government and business.
   Chicago is ``the world capital of hedging'' through its futures
and options exchanges, but changes linked to criticism of those
markets following the crash threaten that dominance, said the
report prepared by the city's Economic Development Commission and
the Civic Committee of the Commercial Club of Chicago.
   ``In particular, regulatory action could reduce the volume and
liquidity of trading here and could cause the Chicago exchanges to
lose their international leadership to exchanges that operate with
fewer restrictions,'' stated the report, released Tuesday.
   To prevent that, the city's political and business leaders must
unite to lobby against new government regulation of Chicago's
exchanges, the report recommends.
   The city also must improve its public schools and reduce its
business taxes to expand its financial-services economy, the report
recommends.
   ``Many executives interviewed stated that Chicago's development
as a financial services center is hindered by the poor education
provided by the Chicago public schools,'' it said.
   The report called specifically for public schools to do a better
job training students in computer literacy and typing skills.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer said his staff was studying how to institute
the report's recommendations.
   Chicago ranks third in the nation, behind New York and Los
Angeles, with 330,000 financial-services jobs and trails in such
global businesses as international banking and money management,
the report said.
   ``It is world-class in trading, but lags London, New York and
Tokyo as a broad-based financial capital,'' the report says.
   Instead of competing head-on with those cities, Chicago must
capitalize on its strength as a leader in ``global risk
management'' and work to attract new financial businesses in such
fields as insurance and banking, the report states.
   ``Internationally, Chicago is the center of risk management, the
world capital of hedging,'' the report says.
   The city has four major exchanges: the Chicago Board of Trade
and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, which together have 60 percent
of the world futures markets; the Chicago Board Options Exchange,
which has nearly 60 percent of the global options market; and the
Midwest Stock Exchange, one of the world's top five exchanges for
trading equities.
   The report recommends establishing a ``risk management center
committee'' comprised of business executives and economists. The
committee would act partly as a public relations unit to promote
Chicago's image as a financial services center.
   It also would help coordinate the introduction of new financial
services products in Chicago and create an institute at a local
university to train people in risk management services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
