<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC     07-06 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three States Reportedly Seek Emergency OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto, one name, is cq in last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three OPEC member states are considering a call
for an emergency meeting of the 13-nation cartel if world oil
prices continue to weaken, the Kuwait News Agency reported Tuesday.
   Citing high-level senior industry sources, the news agency said
consultations were under way among officials from Venezuela,
Algeria and Ecuador.
   The unnamed sources told the news agency the three nations have
not officially contacted other members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries about the proposed meeting.
   The agency quoted its sources as saying some OPEC nations would
give a ``positive response'' to a call for an emergency session.
   But they said major member states may not accept because there
is no guarantee an emergency meeting would have a positive effect
on the cartel's policies or oil markets.
   The agency did not elaborate, but the reference to nations which
might object to an emergency meeting apparently meant Kuwait and
Saudi Arabia.
   Both OPEC states have opposed calls for emergency sessions
without first establishing clear objectives.
   The news agency said its sources hinted that Venezuela, Algeria
and Ecuador might ask OPEC Secretary General Subroto, the former
Indonesian oil minister, to canvass member states about support for
an emergency meeting.
   Last month, the OPEC nations decided to extend until the end of
1988 the production and pricing agreement reached last year.
However, several cartel members are overproducing in violation of
OPEC's overall 15.06 million barrels-a-day ceiling.
   The agency's sources acknowledged severe weakness in the world
oil market. But they cautioned that without firm policy commitments
prior to any emergency OPEC meeting, an ineffectual session could
``increase the chaos.''
   The sources noted that overproduction and the definition of
exactly what constitutes crude oil production are key issues which
would have to be addressed.
</TEXT>
