<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 0949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Hewlett-Packard-Chips     07-06 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hewlett-Packard-Chips,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard Raises Some Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. has increased
prices on some circuit boards because of ``drastic, wholesale price
jumps'' for memory chips.
   The company on Tuesday raised prices on memory expansion boards
from 2 percent to 25 percent. There was no price increase on memory
boards for the company's new line of Precision Architecture
computers based on reduced instruction set computing, or RISC.
   Hewlett-Packard joined a growing list of companies that have
raised prices in response to the severe shortage of DRAMs, which
stands for dynamic random access memories.
   Until recently, the price of chips bought under long-term
contracts remained relatively stable, while spot market prices
escalated, said Hewlett-Packard spokesman Gene Endicott. Now,
long-term contract prices are also rising.
   Hewlett-Packard, which had revenues of $8.1 billion in 1987,
increased prices 3 to 25 percent on memory boards designed for
computers used in business, engineering and manufacturing.
   For example, the price of a memory board for the HP 3000, a
business computer, will increase 25 percent to $12,500 from $10,000.
   ``Although costs have increased, shipments to customers of
existing products have not been interrupted,'' the company said.
   ``We continue to share the concern of others in the electronics
industry about DRAM availability ... and are hopeful the problem is
corrected soon,'' the company said.
   The increase follows similar moves by Digital Equipment Corp.,
Sun Microsystems Inc., Apple Computer Inc. and other companies.
</TEXT>
