<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-CarImports     07-06 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Car Imports,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales of Imported Cars Up 38 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese purchased 58,474 foreign cars in the first
six months of this year, an increase of 31.5 percent over the first
half of 1987, the Japan Automobile Importers Association said
Wednesday.
   The association said the sales included 41,404 cars from West
Germany, up 21.6 percent from a year earlier; 5,028 from the United
States, up 159 percent; 4,270 from Britain, up 49.1 percent; 2,892
from Sweden, up 37.5 percent; 2,793 from France, up 81.6 percent;
and 1,947 from Italy, up 4.5 percent.
   The association gave no reason for the increase in sales, but
sales of Japanese cars also have increased, reflecting steading
consumer spending and strong sales campaigns.
   The Japan Automobile Dealers Association said Tuesday sales of
Japanese cars in the first half rose 16.9 percent from a year
earlier to a record 2.5 million cars.
</TEXT>
