<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0285</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market hovered in a narrow range
today, pausing after Tuesday's advance to new highs for the year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 2.14 to 2,156.47
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers held a narrow edge on losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 451 up, 442 down and 554
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 25.18 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said the recent strength of the dollar in foreign
exchange had encouraged many investors.
   In addition, Wall Street is looking ahead enthusiastically to
the corporate earnings reports for the second quarter that will be
issued over the next few weeks.
   However, brokers said, a good deal of skepticism persists about
the staying power of the market's recent rally. That seemed evident
today in the reluctance of many traders to chase after stocks at
their highest levels since the crash last fall.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines dropped [ to 129[; American Telephone & Telegraph slipped
[ to 26~, and General Electric was unchanged at 44{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.07 to 155.50. At the Americasn Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .57 at 310.16.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 27.03 to
2,158.61.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 9 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 939 up, 520 down, and 447 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 171.79 million shares, against 238.33 million in the
previous session.
