<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-NYSE-Collar 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYSE-Collar, 1st Ld-Writethru,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says NYSE Plans To Drop `Collar'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The Journal ..., with three grafs to
include New York Times report. Picks up 6th graf pvs, NYSE
spokeswoman ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major post-crash reform that bars program
trading during times of volatility in the stock market is expected
to be dropped by the New York Stock Exchange, a published report
said today.
   The NYSE plans to phase out by the fall its so-called
``collar,'' which bars index arbitragers from using the automated
stock order system when the Dow Jones industrial average rises or
declines at least 50 points in a day, the Wall Street Journal said,
quoting unnamed industry sources.
   Index arbitragers buy and sell large amounts of stocks and stock
index futures, profiting on price disparities between the two
related instruments.
   The New York Times and the Journal also reported today that the
Big Board was considering giving individual investors priority over
institutions under certain circumstances when both are using
program trading, a move designed to bring individual investors back
into the market.
   ``It's an express track for the individual investor,'' one NYSE
official told the Times. ``There is still a perception that the
individual investor is at a disadvantage, and we want to say that
it is not true. That's the push behind this rule.''
   Both proposals are expected to be considered by the NYSE's board
of directors at a regular monthly meeting Thursday, according to
the newspapers.
   NYSE spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin said she could not comment on
what issues the board would consider at Thursday's meeting.
   However, she noted the collar, enacted in February, had been set
to expire after six months unless the exchange decided to extend it.
   ``When the collar was put in place, it had a sunset provision in
it. It was never meant to be permanant,'' Ms. Gamsin said.
   The collar was enacted as a way of reforming the U.S. stocks and
futures markets in the wake of the Oct. 19 crash.
   Critics have complained the collar is ineffective and may even
add to the volatility it was designed to curb. For one thing, they
said, sophisticated program traders could get around the collar by
having their orders distributed on the trading floor manually by
brokers.
   Market regulators also were cool on the idea. When the
Securities and Exchange Commission approved it for a six-month
trial, it asked the exchange to consider other alternatives to
curbing market volatility.
   However, proponents say market swings of 50 points or more have
become less frequent because of the collar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DefenseProbe 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0962</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0992</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with today's testimony; picks up 2nd graf
pvs, Pentagon spokesman.
^LaserPhoto WX10</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has sharply increased the number
of inspectors trying to spot fraud among defense contractors, but
still more are needed and they are not likely to be added, the
Defense Department's inspector general said today.
   ``Given the (Defense) department's projected budget shortfalls
for the coming years, I am pessimistic that the investigative
organizations will get the additional resources they need,'' June
Gibbs Brown told the House Armed Services Committee.
   She did not speak specifically about details of the ongoing
criminal investigation into fraud and bribery allegations among
Pentagon contractors and consultants.
   But she said the Pentagon has about 1,000 people who do nothing
but investigate fraud, a sharp increase from 1982, when 375 were
assigned to that task.
   ``In spite of these impressive gains, I remain concerned over
the resources available to the defense criminal investigation
organizations for the detection and investigation of fraud,'' she
said.
   At least 450 more fraud investigators are needed, she said.
   Confusion surrounds Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci's hurried
announcement of contract suspensions in response to the widening
Pentagon bribery probe, with officials unable to say which projects
are covered.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said Tuesday that the Defense
Department is still trying to implement Carlucci's order.
   Howard suggested Carlucci's announcement was a response to
clamoring in Congress and elsewhere for the Pentagon to do
something to restore its credibility in the midst of the criminal
investigation.
   ``We had people here and people on the (Capitol) Hill demanding
immediate action to suspend people, to suspend contracts,'' Howard
said when asked to explain the timing of Friday's announcement.
   Defense contractors say they are still waiting for formal
notification of the contract suspensions.
   ``We're in the dark,'' said Cohann Whitney, a TRW Inc.
spokeswoman.
   ``We've received no official notification and until we do, we're
going ahead with production. The work will continue,'' said Robert
Knapp, a spokesman for Litton Industries.
   TRW is taking the same position. ``We're working with the Navy
to try to get some clarification on the announcement,'' Ms. Whitney
said.
   Carlucci announced last Friday he was ordering an immediate
suspension of what Pentagon officials said were $1 billion worth of
contracts. He said he was acting because the pacts may be tainted
by the bribery allegations.
   The investigation centers on allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former defense officials,
bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that could be
vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Asked for details of the contract suspensions, Howard said: ``We
worked that one very quickly and we gave you the best information
we had.''
   But he admitted, ``I don't know the answer'' when asked which
contracts are involved, or whether the freeze affects contractors
and subcontractors alike.
   Navy officials were trying Tuesday to figure out how to
implement Carlucci's order.
   ``We're working on it; we're still trying to figure out the
details,'' Lt. Barbara Kent, a spokeswoman for the Navy, said late
Tuesday.
   At a hastily called news conference late Friday afternoon,
Carlucci said he was acting on the basis of information in
affidavits that had been unsealed a day earlier by a federal
magistrate in Dallas. The FBI said in the affidavits that its
wiretaps had recorded a Navy procurement officer passing along
inside information to consultants about contracts.
   Pentagon officials have said one of the affected contracts is
between the Navy and Litton, to build hand-held computers for the
Marines for use in transmitting targeting information.
   But Knapp said work on the contract will go ahead until Litton
receives official word.
   The contract was awarded in 1982 and the remainder of the pact
is worth $23.5 million, according to John George, a spokesman for
Litton. The devices are produced by Litton's Colorado Springs,
Colo., plant, which employs about 100 people, he said.
   Another pact identified as being covered by the order is between
the Navy and TRW Inc., to build new operating centers for
anti-submarine warfare. It was let in October 1987 and is for $36.7
million, Ms. Whitney said.
   ``To the best of our knowledge, TRW is not one of the companies
involved in this probe and we have no idea why this action was
taken,'' she said. ``We are working with the Navy to try to get
some clarification on Carlucci's announcement.''
   Asked how long the freeze would last, Howard said, ``I can't
give you a black-and-white answer on that at this point.''
   He added, ``we're looking at it; we're looking at it very
carefully and I'm aware of this concern that you may be punishing
the innocent along with the guilty. This is no judgment of ultimate
innocence or guilt, freezing these contracts. It simply seems a
prudent step to take until we do sift through the evidence.''
   The spokesman added that ``we did not have to go to trial and
conviction in order to take this step, nor do I think it would be
essential that we would go through trial and conviction in order to
unfreeze a contract, if, as the evidence unfolds, it's clear that
they're not involved.''
   Howard indicated the Pentagon was responding to pressure,
particularly from outraged legislators, but said it waited until
the affidavits spelled out specific allegations before acting.
   ``We said we can't do that, we can't do that unless we have some
evidence. We had an affidavit come down that had some evidence,''
he said. ``We took immediate action.''
   House Armed Services Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., joined by a
number of other lawmakers, had urged Carlucci to do ``something
dramatic'' to restore credibility as increasing numbers of
contracts were called into question.
</TEXT>
