<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MorrisonKnudsen-Suit     07-06 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Morrison Knudsen-Suit,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Company Sues Illinois Businessman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morrison Knudsen Corp. has filed suit
against Illinois businessman Edward F. Heil, charging him with
filing a false and misleading statement with federal regulators.
   The Boise-based construction, engineering and shipbuilding
company charged in the suit filed Tuesday that Edward F. Heil did
not disclose in documents filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission the nature of a civil suit brought against him and
others by the state of Illinois over a major Chicago convention
center project.
   Heil, the president of Environmental Construction Co. of Downers
Grove, Ill., made the SEC filing following his purchase of 6.2
percent of Morrison Knudsen's stock. Federal regulations require
anyone buying more than 5 percent of a company's stock to reveal
their reasons for the acquisition to SEC.
   Morrison Knudsen officials said the Illinois attorney general's
office charged Heil and two companies he controls with trying to
defraud the Illinois Metropolitan Fair and Exposition Authority in
connection with the McCormick Place Annex, a recently completed
expansion of the McCormick Place Exhibition Hall in Chicago.
   Ileen Lasko of the Illinois attorney general's office said Heil
was one of 14 contracting companies named in the civil suit, which
seeks $7 million in restitution and damages from the defendants.
   In the suit, Illinois Attorney General Neil F. Hartigan charged
the contractors with submitting phony bills for labor and materials
through dummy minority contractors.
   Heil said in his SEC filing his purchase of 670,300 shares of
Morrison Knudsen common stock for $28.8 million was intended as an
investment and to gain a seat on the company's board.
   Wall Street analysts have dismissed a possible takeover attempt
of Morrison Knudsen by Heil.
   The Illinois suit seeks to bar any company of which Heil is a
director from doing business with public authorities in the state.
Morrison Knudsen's suit charged Heil failed to disclose to the SEC
what effect his presence on the board would have on its recently
awarded $156 million construction contract with the Metropolitan
Sanitary District of Greater Chicago.
   Morrison Knudsen claimed Heil's involvement could also affect
its bid on a large railcar refurbishment contract with the Chicago
Transit authority and a third Illinois project under consideration.
</TEXT>
