<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-06 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened narrowly mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid conflicting signals about
the condition of the crops and the potential for further drought
damage.
   ``This is the first quiet opening we've had in a long, long
time,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   On the bullish side, forecasts for record-breaking heat and
continued dryness in the Midwest this week threatened further
damage to the soybean and corn crops, especially with corn entering
its critical pollination stage, Spilka said.
   On the other hand, recent rains in the northern Plains, the
Southeast and the Mississippi Delta region _ and forecasts for rain
in the Midwest next week _ have tempered drought fears among
traders already nervous about high prices.
   Spilka said the rain may tempt farmers in the Delta and
Southeast to plant more soybeans.
   The Agriculture Department's weekly crop-progress reports
released late Tuesday also had a calming effect, Spilka said. The
reports showed less deterioration in the corn crop last week than
some had expected, and indicated little new damage to the soybean
crop.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.89 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 2 cents lower with July at $3.42{ a bushel; oats were
2 cents to 3{ cents lower with July at $3.19 a bushel; soybeans
were 4 cents lower to 2 cents higher with July at $9.55 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .38 cent higher with August at
65.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .35 cent lower
with August at 74.90 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent lower to .35
cent higher with July at 44.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were 1.85 cents lower to .35 cent higher with July at 33.60 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Tuesday while pork
futures were mostly lower.
</TEXT>
