<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BPStrike     07-06 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-BP Strike,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BP Employees Ratify Contract, End 5-Month Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARCUS HOOK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil refinery workers are ending a
five-month strike at the British Petroleum Co. refinery here after
ratifying a two-year contract.
   About 70 percent of the refinery workers who voted approved a
package that includes cuts in sick pay and the termination of two
employees for alleged picket line violations. About 95 percent of
the 345 employees voted. The votes were counted Tuesday night.
   The union workers, on strike since Feb. 3, are scheduled to
return to work Monday.
   ``The people are very upset over the contract, but they have
bills to pay,'' said Denis Stephano, secretary of Local 8-234 of
the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers.
   BP spokeswoman Anne Straitiff said, ``We're glad it's over,''
but declined to comment further.
   The refinery's union employees went on strike over issues
including sick leave, wages and medical benefits. Knots of strikers
have picketed the gates of the sprawling plant southwest of
Philadelphia ever since.
   Under the new contract, employees will get an increase of 30
cents an hour during the first year, followed by a 3 percent
increase the second year. The refinery's employees now average
$15.23 an hour, except those in packaging, who make between $6 and
$9 per hour.
</TEXT>
