<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, following
through on Tuesday's advance to new highs for the year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 27.03 points on
Tuesday, rose another 4.97 to 2,163.58 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers held a narrow edge on losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 654 up, 632 down and 522
unchanged.
   Analysts said the recent strength of the dollar in foreign
exchange had encouraged many investors.
   In addition, Wall Street is looking ahead enthusiastically to
the corporate earnings reports for the second quarter that will be
issued over the next few weeks.
   However, brokers said, a good deal of skepticism persists about
the staying power of the market's recent rally. That seemed evident
today in the reluctance of many traders to chase after stocks at
their highest levels since the crash last fall.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up \ at
44}; DuPont, up ] at 92~; McDonald's, up | at 46}, and Philip
Morris, up { at 84~.
   International Business Machines was unchanged at 129\ and
American Telephone & Telegraph was steady at 27.
   Pullman gained [ to 7| in active trading. An investor group led
by top executives of the company is proposing to acquire it for
$7.50 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.01 to 155.56. At the Americasn Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .74 at 310.33.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 88.93 million shares at
noontime, up from 73.78 million at the same point Tuesday.
