<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Airlines-Unions     07-06 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airlines-Unions,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am, Northwest Also Battling With Unions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Airlines Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While Eastern Airlines has a long history of stormy relations
with its unions, other major U.S. airlines also have been dogged by
labor troubles.
   Financially ailing Pan Am Corp. has been trying for months to
wrest pay cuts and other concessions from three of its unions. The
nation's eighth largest airline stepped up the pressure on the
holdout unions last month by threatening to sell most of its assets
if the concessions are not made.
   The Pan Am unions representing pilots and flight engineers have
agreed to cuts totaling about $240 million over three years, but
the flight attendants, Teamsters and transport workers have refused
to go along.
   To ensure its financial recovery, Pan Am needs labor concessions
totaling around $540 million over three years, analysts and company
sources estimate. The carrier posted a net loss of $83.3 million in
the first quarter.
   Northwest Airlines, the fourth largest U.S. carrier, narrowly
averted a strike by its 6,700 flight attendants in late March when
it reached a tentative contract agreement with them. The St. Paul,
Minn.-based airline said its net loss of $43.5 million in the first
quarter was partly due to the strike threat.
   Wage scales, pensions and work rules were among the major issues
in the dispute. Former Republic Airlines flight attendants had been
working under their old contract since Northwest acquired Republic
in 1986, and many former Republic employees were paid less than
their Northwest counterparts.
</TEXT>
