<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0265</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly today,
pausing after Tuesday's advance to new highs for the year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 27.03 points on
Tuesday, slipped back 1.25 to 2,157.36 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers held a narrow edge on gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 668 up, 715 down and 511
unchanged.
   Analysts said the recent strength of the dollar in foreign
exchange had encouraged many investors.
   In addition, Wall Street is looking ahead enthusiastically to
the corporate earnings reports for the second quarter that will be
issued over the next few weeks.
   However, brokers said, a good deal of skepticism persists about
the staying power of the market's recent rally. That seemed evident
today in the reluctance of many traders to chase after stocks at
their highest levels since the crash last fall.
   Among the blue chips, International Business Machines dropped \
to 129; American Telephone & Telegraph was unchanged at 27, and
General Electric rose [ to 44|.
   Pullman gained [ to 7| in active trading. An investor group led
by top executives of the company is proposing to acquire it for
$7.50 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.04 to 155.53. At the Americasn Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .48 at 310.07.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 124.18 million shares with two
hours to go.
