<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Braniff-American     07-06 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Braniff-American,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Agrees to Lend Braniff Up to $21 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines has agreed to lend recently
acquired rival Braniff Inc. as much as $21 million, documents filed
with the Securities and Exchange Commission show.
   American already has loaned Braniff $14.4 million, according to
documents filed Tuesday by BIA-COR Holdings Inc., the investment
group which recently acquired Dallas-based Braniff for $100 million.
   American, which competes with Braniff at Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport, also agreed to purchase $19 million to $23
million of Braniff's assets, the documents said. American has
already paid Braniff $5 million for landing slots at O'Hare
International Airport in Chicago and New York's LaGuardia Airport,
the documents said.
   Sources at American previously said they planned to buy $40
million of Braniff's assets from BIA-COR Holdings, including
terminal gates and landing slots at overcrowded airports.
   ``(The investor group) came to us with the proposition to buy
some (of Braniff's) assets,'' American spokesman Lowell C. Duncan
told The Dallas Morning News Tuesday. ``We agreed to buy the assets
and as part of the agreement, we agreed to lend them the money,''
he said.
   Fort Worth-based American has loaned Braniff $6 million in a 15
percent promissory note and $8.4 million at 15 percent interest
that is secured by unspecified Braniff assets in Ft. Lauderdale,
Fla., the documents said.
   Duncan said the purchase of assets and loans of a rival carrier
didn't pose antitrust problems.
   BIA-COR Holdings completed a deal June 25 to purchase Braniff
from Dallas-based Dalfort Corp.
</TEXT>
