<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Nader-Lloyd's 1stLd-Writethru   07-06 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nader-Lloyd's, 1st Ld-Writethru,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nader Accuses Lloyd's Of `Secretive' Role In U.S. Insurance
Industry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 2nd graf to delete word `firm' in reference to
Lloyd's.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader asserted
Wednesday that Lloyd's of London has an ``unregulated, secretive''
role in the U.S. insurance industry and was a major force behind
the nationwide liability crisis.
   He said the giant insurance underwriting exchange, looking for
ways to make up losses sustained during highly publicized internal
scandals, helped spawn higher rates in the United States and
reduced compensation for victims in liability cases.
   Nader added his voice to recent charges by a number of states
that the insurance industry touched off the crisis by conspiring to
stop providing some kinds of liability coverage.
   He released a report titled ``Goliath: Lloyd's of London in the
United States,'' which charged that Lloyd's ``was a driving force
behind the commercial insurance crisis of the mid-1980s.''
   Lloyd's wields its influence in the United States primarily as a
reinsurer, providing insurance for U.S. companies in exchange for
sharing the risk of their own policies. As such, it ``dictates to a
remarkable degree both the rate and policy decisions in the U.S.
property-casualty insurance industry,'' Nader contended at a news
conference.
   ``It is a foreign, unregulated, secretive powerful lever on who
gets insurance, when and at what price in the United States,
whether it is the ability of a day care center, a trucking firm, a
school, a hospital, a mass transit system or a farmer to get
affordable insurance,'' Nader said.
   Lloyd's of London spokesman David Larner said: ``We have not
seen the report and we are not going to comment until we have had a
chance to study it.''
   The 300-year-old Lloyd's has in the last decade faced a series
of insurance scandals and suffered heavy losses insuring ships and
cargos in the Persian Gulf.
   As a result, Nader asserted, Lloyds in the mid-1980s ``saw an
opportunity in the United States and, by generating a fictional
impression that there is a litigation explosion and a lawsuit
crisis in the United States'' worked with U.S. companies for
legislation reducing victims' rights in liability cases and
restrictions on coverage for various policies.
   That resulted in increased rates for what coverage could be had
and the ensuing crisis, he said.
   This year, 18 states have filed lawsuits accusing 32 insurance
companies and underwriting agencies of engaging in secret
agreements to eliminate pollution insurance and general liability
for damage discovered after expiration of a policy.
   The suits also claim that the companies got major reinsurers,
including Lloyd's, to threaten to boycott any U.S. insurance
company that provided broader coverage.
   The report called for greater U.S. regulation of reinsurers, and
alternative reinsurance programs to be set up by federal and state
governments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-P&G-China     07-06 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-P&G-China,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Procter & Gamble Stepping Up Trade in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Procter & Gamble Co. said Wednesday it is
entering a joint venture to make and sell personal care products in
China, the world's most populous country.
   The consumer products giant said it has entered a joint venture
with three China-based organizations to produce and sell products
including dishwashing detergents, shampoo, bath foam and other
personal-care goods.
   Edwin L. Artzt, president of P&G International and vice chairman
of the company's board of directors, signed the agreement Wednesday
for Procter & Gamble, the company announced. He said it represents
a long-term commitment to doing business in China.
   P&G officials said the joint venture will greatly expand
distribution of the company's products in China. Procter & Gamble
is to provide technical and management expertise to the venture.
   P&G officials declined to say how much of a profit they expect
the joint venture will produce for the company.
   Until now, Procter & Gamble products sold in China have been
imported into the country in small quantities, through so-called
``friendship stores'' established to serve foreign visitors.
   P&G said it and a Hong Kong-based company, Hutchison Whampoa
Ltd., reached agreement with Guangzhou Soap Factory and the
Guangzhou Economic and Technological Development District's import
and export corporation to form the joint venture company in
Guangzhou, a large city in southern China.
   The new company will be called Procter & Gamble (Guangzhou) Ltd.
It will begin making products in China by October, officials said.
   The initial product lineup will include Guangzhou's factory
brands of shampoo, bath foam and dishwashing detergents, along with
some well-known P&G products. Most of these products will be sold
in China, but some will be exported, officials said in making the
announcement in Cincinnati and Guangzhou.
   P&G's international trade is the fastest-growing segment of its
business. International sales accounted for about one-third of
P&G's $17 billion in total worldwide sales last year.
   ``Procter & Gamble is committed to providing products of
superior quality and value that best fill the needs of the world's
consumers. We look forward to playing an important role in meeting
the growing demand for these types of products in China, and in
sharing our business experience and advanced technology with our
new partners,'' Artzt said.
   The agreement resulted from three years of negotiations, Procter
& Gamble spokesman Don Tassone said. P&G prepared for the venture
by advertising its products on Chinese television for 18 months,
from 1985 through early 1987.
   ``That was an effort to introduce our company and some of our
leading brands to the people of the country,'' Tassone said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
