<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-Airbus     07-06 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Airbus ,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Government Agrees to Higher Subsidies for Airbus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German government officials have
agreed to more than double subsidies to the Airbus program, a
spokesman said.
   Dietrich Vogel, an Economics Ministry spokesman, said Wednesday
that the government plans to more than double its allocation to the
aircraft program in 1989 to 524 million marks, or around $291
million at current exchange rates.
   The Airbus jetliners are manufactured by Airbus Industrie, a
European aircraft consortium financed by the governments of West
Germany, France, Britain and Spain.
   The subsidy, originally planned at 200 million marks, will cover
the payments guaranteed by the West German government and made by
the state-controlled Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm GmbH, which holds
the West German share of the Airbus program.
   Vogel said the agreement to increase the Airbus subsidy was
reached at a meeting Tuesday between Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg, Economics Minister Martin Bangemann and other
officials from the two ministries.
   The higher subsidy is expected to be endorsed by the government
when it meets Thursday to finalize its 1989 budget plans, he said.
   Vogel said he did not see ``any difficulties'' that could block
the proposal at the cabinet meeting.
   Also on Wednesday, the European Economic Community's executive
Commission proposed in Brussels, Belgium, that the EEC should spend
60 million European currency units, or about $68.4 million, on
aircraft research.
   The funds would cover half of the program's costs over two
years. The areas of research proposed by the Commission include
aerodynamics, aircraft materials, noise and manufacturing
technology.
</TEXT>
