<HEAD>Soybeans Surge Into Close; Grains Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged near the close
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade while grain futures
finished mixed amid uncertainty over the potential for further
drought damage.
   Midday private weather forecasts that reduiced chances for rain
this weekend in the Midwest fueled the late soybean rally, analysts
said. Wheat and oat futures followed soybean prices higher after
trading lower for most of the session.
   But corn finished slightly lower, possibly indicating the bull
market has peaked, said Cathy Leow, vice president of grain and
soybean trading for Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   With corn plants entering the critical pollination stage, in
which silk and tassels appear, ``we're in the heart of causing
damage and the weather forecasts are pretty horrible,'' Ms. Leow
said.
   ``The fact that the corn market has been unable to sustain
stength in the face of these forecasts indicates to me that if we
haven't seen the highs, we're close to it.''
   At the close, wheat was 4 cents to 8{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.94 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents
lower to 1 cent higher with July at $3.42 a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 10 cents higher with July at $3.23 a bushel; soybeans were
.05 cent lower to 26{ cents higher with July at $9.85 a bushel.
