<2ND_LINE>AM-Trump-Casino,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Proposes Putting Up $75 Million Of His Own Money For New
Casino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump has proposed
putting $75 million of his own money into the Taj Mahal casino and
selling $675 million in bonds as part of his plans to buy the
project.
   In documents filed Tuesday with the federal Securities and
Exchange Commission in Washington, Trump also indicated the
1,250-room hotel and its 120,000-square-foot casino should be
completed by Dec. 1, 1989.
   The total purchase price of the Taj Mahal is $261 million,
including acquisition fees, according to the SEC filing. It will
cost another $493 million to complete the massive hotel casino.
   Trump's planned purchase of the Taj Mahal is the result of a
deal with entertainer Merv Griffin, who will buy Trump's
controlling interest in Resorts International Inc. and take that
company private.
   When the deal is completed, Trump will own the Taj Mahal, some
related real estate, two ocean piers and a helicopter airline that
offers service betwen Atlantic City and New York.
   Griffin will own the existing Resorts International Hotel
Casino, the balance of the company's real estate in Atlantic City,
its casino properties in the Bahamas and other corporate assets.
   Trump has formed a new partnership to acquire the Taj Mahal _
Trump Taj Mahal Associates _ which initially will borrow up to $186
million from banks and from Trump himself to finance the purchase.
Those borrowings will be repaid once the bonds are sold, according
to the SEC filing.
   Trump attorney Nicholas Ribis said Trump has filed a petition
with the state Casino Control Commission seeking approval of the
financing plan.
</TEXT>
