<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-06 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Surge On Drier Outlook; Corn Slips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged in late trading Wednesday as rain
evaporated from weekend weather forecasts, but corn prices dipped
and analysts said the drought-driven rally in that market was
nearing its end.
   Wheat and oat futures followed the soybean market in other
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   On other markets, cotton and sugar posted strong gains; the
tailspin continued for frozen pork bellies while livestock futures
were mixed; energy and precious-metals futures advanced; and
stock-index futures plummeted.
   The grain and soybean markets opened quietly mixed, then turned
sharply lower in what analysts said was a response to a weekly
Agriculture Department report showing less deterioration in the
corn and soybean crops than some traders had expected.
   But private midday weather forecasts reducing the chances for
rain this weekend in the Midwest fueled a late soybean rally, and
wheat and oat futures followed.
   ``Soybeans ... staged a very, very strong comeback,'' said
Walter Spilka, a grains analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &
Co. in New York. ``Traders basically looked at the private
forecasts, which still say hot and dry as far out as they can see.''
   The National Weather Service issued a 6-to-10-day outlook after
the close predicting above-normal temperatures and below-normal
rainfall in most major crop-growing areas for the middle and end of
next week. That forecast was in sharp contrast to Monday's
6-to-10-day outlook, which predicted above-normal rainfall in the
Midwest for the five days starting Sunday.
   Corn futures finished slightly lower, possibly indicating the
bull market has peaked, said Cathy Leow, vice president of grain
and soybean trading for Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   With corn plants entering the pollination stage, a critical
growth period in which silk and tassels appear, ``we're in the
heart of causing damage and the weather forecasts are pretty
horrible,'' Ms. Leow said.
   ``The fact that the corn market has been unable to sustain
strength in the face of these forecasts indicates to me that if we
haven't seen the highs, we're close to it,'' she said.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 8\ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.93{ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents lower to 1
cent higher with July at $3.42 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 10
cents higher with July at $3.23 a bushel; soybeans were .03 cent to
25 cents higher with July at $9.84 a bushel.
   The soybean rally triggered buying of sugar and cotton futures,
analysts said. Sugar for October delivery settled 1.17 cents higher
at 13.99 cents a pound on New York's Coffee Sugar & Cocoa Exchange.
July cotton finished 1.80 cents higher at 66.80 cents a pound on
the New York Cotton Exchange.
   Frozen pork-belly futures sank to new 8-year lows on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange amid a continuing lack of demand for the
near-record glut of bellies in cold storage, analysts said. Most
contracts plunged the daily limit of 2 cents a pound for the third
consecutive session.
   Hog futures were mixed in reaction to mixed cash markets. Cattle
futures were pressured by a statement by National Cattlemen's
Association President Dale Humphrey that the drought would continue
to cause liquidation of cattle herds, causing increased beef
supplies in the near term, said Dale Durchholz, an analyst with
AgriVisor Services Inc., an advisory service in Bloomington, Ill.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .88 cent lower with August at 64.82
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent to .88 cent lower with
August at 74.37 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .50 cent
higher with July at 44.57 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.85 cent to 2 cents lower with July at 32.40 cents a pound.
   Energy futures advanced on mostly technical factors on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   The weekly American Petroleum Institute report, issued after the
close, indicated continued strong demand for unleaded gasoline,
which should support futures prices on Thursday, said Peter Beutel,
energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 25 cents to 33 cents
higher with August at $15.36 a barrel; heating oil was .86 cent to
1.06 cents higher with August at 42.61 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .60 cent to .87 cent higher with August at 50.50 cents
a gallon.
   Precious metals gained slightly in thin trading on the Commodity
Exchange in New York in reaction to the higher oil and soybean
prices, analysts said.
   Gold was 40 cents to $1.10 higher with August at $440.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 5 cents to 5.7 cents higher with July at $6.819 a
troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures plummeted in a late flurry of program
trading linked to falling Treasury bond prices, analysts said. The
contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500 index
settled 6.65 points lower at 272 on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</TEXT>
