<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1811EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Warner-ESM     07-06 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warner-ESM,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors To Consider Whether Warner A Victim Or Participant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NAN HERLIHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors were asked Wednesday to
decide whether financier Marvin Warner was a victim of fraud in the
ESM Government Securities collapse or a cunning participant who
profited at the expense of investors.
   Closing arguments ended in the $21 million civil suit filed by
ESM's bankruptcy trustee against Warner at U.S. District Court
here, only blocks from ESM's former offices. Deliberations were
expected Thursday.
   The collapse of ESM led to the failure days later of Warner's
Home State Savings Bank in Cincinnati, ESM's biggest customer.
   ``Everybody takes credit for discovering the ESM fraud, but no
one knew about it until people from Home State were down here
trying to find the truth,'' said Andrew Hall, Warner's lawyer.
   ``It has not been proved he took part in the fraud. Warner is
the biggest victim of this case,'' Hall said in closing statements
to the six-member jury.
   Hall said Warner, 69, lost at least $26 million of his own
money, securities and real estate when ESM folded.
   Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, attorney for ESM's court-appointed trustee
Thomas Tew, painted a different picture for jurors.
   He described a jet-set world of complex and illegal transactions
on corporate jets and at private Kentucky Derby cocktail parties.
   Garcia-Pedrosa told jurors that Warner, a former U.S. ambassador
to Switzerland, was tipped off to financial problems at ESM in time
to pull out millions of dollars before the collapse.
   ``Help bring that money back to the estate of ESM,'' he urged
jurors. ``No other creditor got out early.''
   The lawsuit against Warner by the ESM estate originally sought
more than $60 million. That figure has been reduced to $21 million
by U.S. District Judge Jose A. Gonzalez Jr.
   Warner, who filed for Chapter 11 financial reorganization in
Jacksonville, placed his fortune in his family's name, Tew charged.
   ``I think we could recover the money from his wife and son,''
Tew said.
   Warner, looking tan and confident, nodded to jurors as they
entered the courtroom and smiled as he made eye contact with each
of them. The financier lives on a horse ranch in Ocala in north
central Florida.
   Warner has said he lost almost $30 million in 1985 when ESM
failed with a total of $315 million in losses to investors.
   ESM's downfall also sank Home State, setting off a thrift crisis
in Ohio and forcing that state to temporarily close 72 savings and
loan associations.
   Warner was convicted in Ohio last year of fraudulently
transferring Home State funds to ESM. He was sentenced to three
years in prison but is free on appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880706-0322 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1838EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MTMSale     07-06 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MTM Sale,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Buy TV Firm Co-Founded by Mary Tyler Moore</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA9</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MTM Entertainment Inc., the
television production company co-founded by actress Mary Tyler
Moore, will be bought by a British TV company in a deal the
companies valued at $320 million in cash and stock, it was
announced Wednesday.
   MTM, producer of such popular and critically acclaimed series as
``Hill Street Blues'' and ``St. Elsewhere,'' will retain its name,
management and creative philosophy after the takeover by Television
South PLC, officials said here and in London.
   Miss Moore and three MTM officers will emerge from the deal with
a 20 percent share in the buyer, known as TVS, producer of the
television movie ``Mandela'' and other programs aired on Britain's
two independent networks.
   TVS, which is selling an additional 20 percent stake to two
French media companies to raise money for the buyout, gets MTM's
library of old TV shows popular on both sides of the Atlantic and
becomes Britain's biggest independent TV production company.
   ``I'm very excited about it. I think it's a great opportunity
for MTM to grow, especially in the European market,'' Miss Moore
told a news conference here.
   Officials of both companies said they hoped to cooperate on
production and distribution of programs on both sides of the
Atlantic, but that both production operations would remain
independent.
   Responding to questions about possible changes in programming
that produced the sometimes controversial ``St. Elsewhere,'' Arthur
Price, MTM's chief executive officer, said: ``There are going to be
no changes in the creative attitude the company has displayed.''
   In a deal that must be approved by the TVS board of directors
and various regulatory bodies, the British firm agreed to pay
$242.3 million cash for the privately held MTM.
   Additionally, TVS will issue new stock it valued at $35.8
million to four members of MTM management: Price; Miss Moore, who
is a director; Mel Blumenthal, senior executive vice president; and
Tom Palmieri, executive vice president. That stock would give the
four a combined 20 percent of TVS, but Miss Moore's 6.4 percent
share and Blumenthal's 3.6 percent share wouldn't change hands
until 1993 under the agreement.
   Blumenthal and Price will get seats on the TVS board.
   The deal also calls for a second transfer of new stock, valued
at $41.9 million, to the MTM group five years after completion of
the buyout.
   TVS said it would finance the deal through bank borrowing and
the sale of $190 million worth of common and convertible preferred
stock.
   Two French media companies, Canal S.A. and Generale d'Images
S.A., have agreed to buy $99 million worth of the common stock,
giving them each 10 percent of TVS.
   The most valuable asset in the transaction is MTM's library of
old shows that are syndicated, or sold to television stations for
re-runs. The library, which TVS valued at $310 million, has 1,000
hours of programs, including ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' ``The
Bob Newhart Show,'' ``Lou Grant,'' ``Rhoda'' ``WKRP in
Cincinnati,'' and ``Remington Steele.''
   MTM also has a U.S. distribution arm that could help sell TVS
programs to American networks and a production studio in Ireland.
   MTM had sought to expand through a public stock offering in this
country last year, but dropped that plan after the October stock
market crash dampened investors' enthusiasm for new issues.
   The TVS deal, arrived at after 10 months of negotiations, blends
each company's desire to expand in the other's area, TVS Chief
Executive James Gatward said in London.
   Though officials at both the London and California news
conferences said they hoped the companies could jointly produce
shows, there aren't any specific plans to do so immediately,
Blumenthal said.
   MTM reported pre-tax profits of $43.8 million in its most recent
fiscal year. TVS reported net profits of $32 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
