<DOCNO> AP880706-0325 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Boeing-EasternEurope     07-06 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing-Eastern Europe,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Gets Licenses to Sell Wide-Bodies to Poland, Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. has received export licenses to
sell six wide-body jets to state-owned airlines in Poland and
Romania, a top Commerce Department official said Wednesday.
   Paul Freedenberg, undersecretary of commerce for export
administration, said that Cocom last week approved the licenses,
which were granted by the Commerce Department in May.
   Paris-based Cocom _ the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral
Export Controls _ rules on sales of sensitive technology to the
Communist bloc by the United States, Canada, the Western European
allies and Japan.
   Freedenberg said the Boeing licenses require that sensitive
electronic equipment, including navigation and communications
systems in the planes' cockpits, be sealed. Servicing of the
planes' engines will be allowed only in a Western country, he said.
   The licenses, good for two years, will permit Seattle-based
Boeing to sell three wide-body 767 jets to LOT, the Polish airline,
and three to Tarom, the Romanian airline. The combined sales are
worth between $250 million and $350 million, he said.
   ``I think it's fairly significant because you're talking a
potential multibillion-dollar Eastern European market. You're
talking a choice of American technology over Soviet technology and
you're talking about a growing trade relationship in commercial
aerospace. That's all good news for American companies,''
Freedenberg said in a telephone interview.
   Last month Airbus Industrie, a Western European aircraft
manufacturing consortium, announced its first aircraft sale to an
Eastern bloc nation under new Cocom rules. With similar
restrictions, it is selling three A310-300 jets to Interflug, the
East German national airline.
   Freedenberg said there are also applications pending from
several aircraft makers to sell to Malev, the Hungarian airline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
