<DOCNO> AP880706-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Manville-Aetna     07-06 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manville-Aetna,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manville Reaches Payment Agreement With Aetna</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. on Wednesday announced an agreement
settling the firm's disputes with Aetna Casualty and Surety Co.
over payments for asbestos damage claims.
   The agreement provides for three payments by Aetna totaling $19
million, Manville officials said in a news release. Aetna's
payments will cover all of Manville's claims against the insurer
for policies issued from 1980 through 1983.
   Implementation of the agreement was conditioned on final court
orders approving the settlement and an order of the Bankruptcy
Court for the Southern District of New York confirming Manville's
plan of reorganization, company officials said.
   The former asbestos maker has been operating under federal
bankruptcy law protection since Aug. 26, 1982.
   Manville sought bankruptcy protection because of thousands of
lawsuits pending by victims of asbestos, which causes asbestosis,
seeking billions of dollars, and future claims expected to develop.
Experts testified that the claims totaled more than the company's
entire worth.
   The lawsuits claimed damage from exposure to asbestos made by
Manville.
   Manville previously has reached settlements providing for
payments of nearly $790 million with Aetna, of Hartford, Conn., and
numerous other carriers, company officials said.
   Manville's reorganization plan requires insurance funding of
$615 million for a trust for compensating asbestos disease
sufferers.
   Insurance proceeds in excess of the $615 million will pass
through to the Asbestos Property Damage Trust, which was created to
handle property damage claims against Manville.
   Richard B. Von Wald, Manville senior vice president and general
counsel, said that under Manville's plan of reorganization, the
latest settlement ultimately would benefit the Asbestos Property
Damage Trust.
   ``This settlement will substantially increase the property
damage trust's ability to fund claims,'' Von Wald said in a written
statement.
   In 1985 and 1986, Manville announced it had reached settlements
with Aetna totaling $20.05 million for policies issued by the
insurer prior to 1980.
   The Bankruptcy Court approved Manville's reorganization plan in
December 1986, but the plan can not be implemented until all
appeals by claimants are addressed.
   Manville is one of the nation's largest manufacturers of
insulation, fiberglass and forest products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
