<FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PullmanOffer     07-06 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pullman Offer,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor Group Seeks New Jersey Manufacturer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pullman Co. said Wednesday it received a
buyout proposal valuing the company at about $308 million from an
investor group that includes some of its senior managers and its
largest stockholder.
   The group, which includes Pullman chairman Thomas M. Begel and
Hampton, N.H.-based Henley Manufacturing Corp., proposed a purchase
price of $7.50 per share.
   Pullman spokesman Thomas Davies said that there were 41 million
shares outstanding as of Sept. 30. Henley owns about 10 percent of
the company, while Pullman management holds more than 4 percent.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Pullman rose 12{
cents a share to close at $7.62{.
   Davies said it is not known how many of the company's senior
members were part of the investor group.
   Pullman, which is based here, is a maker of specialty truck
trailers, aircraft seating, automotive parts and food service
equipment.
   Begel said he would ``watch and see what develops'' before
commenting further on the offer. He said he hoped to have the
matter settled next week.
   Pullman said a special committee of independent directors of the
company's board will make a recommendation to the board.
   Shearson Lehman Hutton will act as independent financial advisor
to the special committee.
   If the proposal is accepted, the investor group plans to enter
into a financial agreement with ``a major money center bank'' to
fund the acquisition, according to a release from Pullman.
   Pullman earned $17.6 million, or 42 cents per share, on revenues
of $612.8 million in 1987.
   Henley, a producer of speciality and indstrial chemicals and
automotive parts, had earnings of $6.8 million, or 16 cents per
shares, on revenues of $440.6 million in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
